<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Urged to Boost Sugar Output for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye Thursday urged sugar producers to explore ways
to meet the need of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the sugar stake-holders here, Sumaye
said Tanzania's annual sugar demand stands at 300,000 tons, but
local production is only 130,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot continue importing sugar when the country has all
the prerequisites to attain self sufficiency," he told the
attendants, asserting that privatization of sugar factories means
to revamp the local production.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting, which drew officials form public and
private sugar factories, importers, sugar cane out-growers and
tax authorities, is to deliberate on the sugar policies.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Kilimanjaro Sugar Company said that
productivity at his company has declined in recent years due to
inadequate capital outlay, and deterioration of the assets and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"The installed capacity of the four sugar factories in the
country is 228,000 tons per year in 1998, but the production is
only 113,622 tons," he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Situated between latitude one and 11 degrees south of the
Equator on the Eastern African coast, Tanzania has identified a
host of places where the climate, soil and topography are well
suited for sugar cane farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
