<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's National Bank to Prioritise Acquisitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Romania's National Bank will
prioritise the acquisitions of hard currency next week in an
attempt to maintain the country's foreign currency reserves at one
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Quoting officials with the central bank, the local daily
Romania libera reported on Thursday that the bank has over the
last weeks bought huge amounts of U.S. dollars to strike a balance
in the exchange rates of the national currency leu.
</P>
<P>
Another way the central bank attempts to consolidate the
reserves is raising loans in the international capital markets.
Thus, the bank mounted a campaign of negotiations with important
commercial banks worldwide to reach short-term loan agreements,
hoping to get some 600 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Romania will get more than one billion U.S. dollars up to the
end of the year by accumulating certain loan tranches that are
already agreed upon, officials of the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Romania's foreign debt amounts to 8.9 billion U.S. dollars,
with more than 40 percent of which granted by international
financial bodies: the International Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
the International Monetary Fund and the Euozean Union.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debt's service for 1999 stands at 2.862 billion
U.S. dollars, the highest in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
Romania's foreign currency reserves stood at 1.4 billion U.S.
dollars in April this year, plus 920 million U.S. dollars' worth
of gold and 1.2 billion U.S. dollars of private reserves. Debt
servicing peak in May and June will entail the spending of 930
million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
