<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Islamist Virtue Party Deputy Chairman Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Aydin Menderes, deputy chairman of
the pro-Islamic Virtue Party (FP), Thursday resigned from the his
party post in protest against the inability of FP leader Recai
Kutan in solving the "headscarf controversy."
</P>
<P>
A FP deputy, Merve Kavakci, triggered the dispute among
political parties as she entered the parliament hall wearing a
headscarf on May 2 for oath-taking session, causing chaos in the
parliament and protest by parties.
</P>
<P>
Women are not allowed to wear headscarf in state and public
institutions under the law in the mostly Muslim-populated but
secular state of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Menderes has been said to be against the move by Merve Kavakci
in parliament, but he called on both his party and opponents to
settle the controversy within the norms of a state of law.
</P>
<P>
Menderes' surprise resignation is seen as a big blow to the FP
and some other FP deputies loyal to Menderes are also expected to
resign from the party.
</P>
<P>
The FP, which became the third largest party after the recent
elections and holds 111 seats in parliament, stems from the
Islamic Welfare Party which was outlawed in January, 1998 for its
ultra-Islamic policies.
</P>
<P>
Right after the incident, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
criticized Kavakci for wearing headscarf when attending the new
parliament oath-taking ceremony, saying such a move provoked
Turkish people.
</P>
<P>
He said that "if because of your headscarf you are claiming to
be a Muslim, this means you are making discrimination. This is
provoking people."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that "everyone in Turkey has
the right to wear whatever she would like in their private
lives. But, the General Assembly of Parliament is not within the
bounds of anyone's private life."
</P>
<P>
"In state life, the rules and regulations of the state should
be obeyed. Parliament is not the place to challenge the state,"
Ecevit added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
