<HEADLINE> Arab League Concerned Over Fightings in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Thursday expressed
deep concern over a fresh flare-up of fightings between two Somali
rival factions, which have taken a heavy toll of both sides.
</P>
<P>
In a related statement issued in the day, Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid appealed to Somali faction leaders to
exert efforts to forge national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Fightings erupted last April at the town of Bua Dhubo in
southwest Somalia, between two rival factions of the Somali
National Front, killing 11 people and wounding 25 others.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid held Somali faction leaders responsible for
hampering regional and international efforts aimed at realizing
durable national reconciliation in the country.
</P>
<P>
He called on the belligerent Somali factions to hold dialogs in
a bid to resolve their disputes in a peaceful way, stressing that
dialogs, not fightings, are the best way to settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
It is the Somali people who, in the end, pay the hefty price of
the bloody conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Warring factions have been controlling the country in the Horn
of Africa since 1991 when its dictator, Siad Barre, was toppled by
the anti-government forces.
</P>
<P>
The factions agreed last year to form a broad-based central
government in an effort to realize national reconciliation. But
few tangible results have been achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
Somalia is a member of the 22-nation pan Arab forum.


06/05/99 19:46 GMT

NNNN
03:51 03:52 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
