<HEADLINE> S. African Students Urged to Fight Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Nkosazana Zuma Thursday called on students to take the lead in
combating AIDS in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Addressing students at the University of Natal in Durban, Zuma
urged students to take responsibility to fight AIDS, a deadly
disease to human being.
</P>
<P>
She said when dealing with the epidemic, issues such as
inequality, gender, health services, safety and security,
education and discrimination should be considered.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that AIDS could have a negative impact on the
planning for the future if it was not attended to.
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of South Africans aged between 15 and 40 years were
 reportedly HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that about 85 percent of South African people
were not taking precautions to prevent the disease and 50 percent,
mainly youth, thought they could identify people infected with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way that you can identify someone with the disease
-- I appeal to you to remove this stigma and start to prevent the
disease," Zuma told the students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
