<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Seeks to Improve Ties With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa
Osman Ismail Thursday expressed hope for improving his country's
ties with all neighbors to achieve security and stability in the
African Horn region.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from an Asian tour, Ismail said the foreign
policy of Sudan especially towards its neighbors was based on a
dialogue principle.
</P>
<P>
The minister has recently visited China, South Korea, Malaysia
and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
On the Qatari-brokered accord signed by Sudan and Eritrea,
Ismail said that its was a positive step towards the normalization
of relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"From this starting point we seek to enhance our relations with
the neighboring countries without exception," he said, adding that
"Any country takes a step in this direction will find us taking
steps towards it."
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Eritrea signed on May 2 in Doha, capital of Qatar, an
agreement to solve the dispute between the two countries whose
relations remained strained since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The recent meeting between Speaker of the National Assembly
(parliament) Hassan al Turabi and leader of the opposition Nation
Party in Geneva on May 2 was part of "the government efforts to
unite all with the country and strengthen the national unity,"
Ismail said.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the meeting would lead to the return of
opposition members in exile and the resolution of all of the main
issues of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The minister also reaffirmed the government's endeavor to
settle the problem of south Sudan in the framework of the
initiative of the Inter-Governmental Authority for Development
(IGAD).
</P>
<P>
He urged the Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) to be
more serious in its talks with the government. He ruled out the
possibility that his government could accept the SPLA proposal to
establish a confederation in the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
