<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes East Timor Agreement on Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) --The United States on Thursday
called a U.N.-brokered agreement on East Timor an important step
forward for its future.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the agreement will be an important step
forward to achieving a peaceful resolution of East Timor's
future," a State Department statement said.
</P>
<P>
the statement came as Portugal and Indonesia agreed on
Wednesday on arrangement for a referendum on August 8 on whether
the people of East Timor want autonomy or independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was once a Portuguese colony. After it withdrew,
Indonesia invaded the territory in 1975 and held it ever since.
</P>
<P>
The State department called on all sides concerned to
"facilitate the immediate establishment of a U.N. presence."
</P>
<P>
But several hours after the agreement was reached,
anti-independence militiamen went house to house beating and
abducting civilians in Halolia, about 45 km southwest of Dili, the
territory's capital, according to the East Timorese Socialist
Party.
</P>
<P>
"The United States remains deeply troubled by the unrestrained,
violent activities of civilian militiamen who seek to bias the
consultation through terror and intimidation," the State
Department statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential that Indonesia take immediate steps to ensure
overall security for all in East Timor," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
