<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton and Schroeder Say NATO Air War Will Go on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his German host, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, Thursday in
Bonn said they backed the G8 statement of principles for resolving
the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
But they also said the NATO strategy of air strikes on
Yugoslavia would not change.
</P>
<P>
The statement was significant in that Russia and the Western
for the first time agreed on an international security force to be
deployed in Kosovo, Clinton said after his meeting with Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is a real peace process under way but it has no
chance of reaching a satisfactory conclusion unless we maintain
allied unity and firmness," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged the Western to stick to the NATO strategy with
more patience.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to aggressively support our air campaign and
aggressively support any diplomatic initiatives that will secure
the conditions necessary for lasting peace in Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
There was no reason to change NATO policy just when it seemed
air strikes were beginning to work, said Schroeder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
