<HEADLINE> Annan Hails G-8 Statement on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Thursday voiced his welcome to the statement on the
conclusion of a meeting of foreign ministers from seven Western
countries and Russia, known as the Group of Eight, which adopts
general principles on the political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued by his spokesman here, said, "The
Secretary-General welcomes the statement" and "he is pleased in
particular at the decision to prepare elements of a United Nations
Security Council resolution, to draw up a road map on further
concrete steps towards a political solution to the crisis, and to
involve other members of the Council in this effort."
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General believes this is an important step in
the direction he advocated when he spoke earlier this week in the
Council and appealed to the members to find the unity necessary to
achieve the required political solution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General reiterates his willingness to extend
full cooperation in the effort to rebuild a consensus on this
question and in this connection expects to announce the
appointment of his Special Envoys shortly," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the Group of Eight issued a statement at
the end of a meeting in Bonn on Thursday, saying that they had
adopted the general principles on the political solution to the
Kosovo crisis, including the immediate and verifiable end of
violence and repression in Kosovo and the withdrawal from Kosovo
of military, police and paramilitary forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
