<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO: Yugoslavia Must Accept Conditions By Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A NATO spokesman said here Thursday
that Yugoslavia must take practical action to show its acceptance
of an agreement reached Thursday by NATO allies and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Group of Seven most industrialized countries and Russia this
afternoon issued a joint statement on ending the war in Yugoslavia
by agreeing on an international presence in Kosovo under a United
Nations mandate. The foreign ministers from the United States,
Canada, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Russia reached
the principle agreement in Bonn at a so-called G-8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NATO welcomed the G-8 statement "very warmly," Jamie Shea,
the NATO spokesman, told a news briefing at NATO headquarters in
Brussels. It showed the "diplomatic track was very functioning"
and "a very important stage to bring the crisis to an end," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Yugoslav President must show his practical
action of withdrawing his military and paramilitary forces from
Kosovo. "We need to see action,....but not a verbal acceptance,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Another NATO spokesman for military briefing, Major General
Walter Jertz, told reporters that NATO will not change its
strategy at this moment and will continue to intensify its air
strikes against Yugoslav military forces without considering
political aspect.
</P>
<P>
However, the two spokesmen acknowledged that the NATO's Allied
Operation is far from success and had to pay heavy price if they
further escalate the bombing.
</P>
<P>
"We have not been able to achieve our objective we initiated
from the beginning,....we have intensified our air campaign over
last few days, we are going to intensify it further," Shea said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
