<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Community Urged to Pay More Attention to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Organization of African Unity (OAU)
chief Salim Ahmed Salim appealed Thursday to the international
community to pay more attention to the crisis in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Salim, who arrived here Wednesday for a two-day visit to
Angola, told the press after meeting Angolan President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos that the civil war in Angola has caused many
deaths and displaced thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
He hoped countries in Africa and other regions should "do their
best" to help the Angolan people "end the human tragedy as soon as
possible."
</P>
<P>
The OAU is calling on the international community for urgent
humanitarian aid extended to Angola, said Salim.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief also condemned the opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) for sabotaging the 1994
Lusaka Protocol, and held its Chairman Jonas Savimbi responsible
for the current situation in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Secretary General reiterated on behalf of the OAU that
every individual country should strictly abide by the relevant
resolutions of the U.N. Security Council which impose sanctions on
the UNITA rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Salim and dos Santos exchanged views on the
conflict situation in Congo (K) and Congo (B) and on the concrete
steps to peacefully resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Salim said the pan-African organization is "very worried" about
the situation in Congo (K) and hoped that Angola would "play a
positive role" in ending the nine-month conflict there.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief also announced that African heads of state and
government will issue a resolution on the issue at the forthcoming
OAU summit slated next month in Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
