<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Arab Monetary Fund extended financial
facilities to Algeria to the tune of 131 million dollars,
representing 75 percent of Algeria's paid quota in convertible
currency.
</P>
<P>
The facilities were extended under an agreement concluded in
Abu Dhabi Wednesday. It was signed on behalf of the Arab Fund by
its chairman and general manager Dr Jassem Al Manaa, and for
Algeria by governor of the Bank of Algeria Abdul Wahab Karman.
</P>
<P>
The loan is aimed at consolidating a reform program initiated
by the Algerian authorities in the financial and banking sectors
during 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
By extending this loan, the Fund will have provided Algeria
with six loans whose total value amounts to 756 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has called upon the United Nations to cease
deducting money from the revenues specified by the memorandum of
understanding, better known as oil-for-food program, in favor of
those harmed by the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
A message to this effect was addressed by Iraqi Foreign
Minister Mohamed Saeed Al Sahaf to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan. Underscoring that the program was termed "oil-for-food "
rather than "oil for compensations", he said payment of
indemnities negatively has affected the humanitarian needs of the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food and medicine accord, signed by Iraq and United
Nations, was enforced as from January 1996. It allows Iraq to sell
oil to 5.2 billion dollars every six months for the purchase of
food, medical supplies and other basic needs. Part of the oil
revenues are regularly deducted to compensate those harmed by the
Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese banks' interest rates covering both loans
and deposits are set to be cut by 1 percent following a decision
by the Banks Association in Lebanon, the Daily Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The association said Wednesday that the move was aimed at
helping the government cut interest rates on Lebanese pounds
and treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
The association suggested that all of its member banks
lower the charge on dollar loans to 9 percent and reduce
the interest paid to depositors to a maximum of 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The United States Agency for International
Development (USAID) has granted 90 million U.S. dollars to
support sanitation schemes in Alexandria, Egypt, Governor of
Alexandria Abdel Sallam el-Mahgoub said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be used to expand plants to treat waste water in
the Mediterranean port city, 210 kilometers northwest of Cairo,
el-Mahgoub told reporters after a meeting with a USAID working
group.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported in the day
the U.S. agency has also agreed to offer 2.6 million dollars
to a training course for irrigation engineers and farmers in
preserving water.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Ministry of Public Works and Water Resources will
organize a two-week training course and a three-month field
training course aimed at increasing awareness of preserving water
resources and protecting water against pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
