<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Political Stability Without Land: Zimbabwean Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's senior government official
said here Thursday that political stability and economic
development in the country remain under threat as long as the land
resettlement program is not fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Willard Chiwewe, chairman of the Task Force on Land in the
National Economic Consultative Forum, said poverty eradication in
rural areas remained a dream and the donor community had a moral
obligation to speed up the land resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
Chiwewe, who is also senior secretary of the Ministry of
Information, Post and Telecommunications, said this at a policy
seminar for senior diplomatic and local staff of embassies and aid
agencies.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had prepared and adopted a project
document covering the inception of the second phase of the land
reform and resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
"The stage we have now reached requires the mobilization of the
 government and donor finance, the refinement of alternative
models of land acquisition and resettlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, there would be a joint meeting on a
later date between selected donors, the government and
representatives of private stakeholders to map the way forward.
</P>
<P>
The international donors conference which was held last
September had set the stage for greater international
understanding and support for Zimbabwe's future land policies and
programs, Chiwewe noted.
</P>
<P>
However, some international financial lending institutions had
been delaying financial credit support to Zimbabwe, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has so far designated about 841
farms, of which 321 have been published in the government gazette
as acquired for resettlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
