<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Hails U.S. Productivity Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said Thursday the performance of U.S. economy over the
past seven years is "truly phenomenal", but warned that the global
recovery from a severe financial crisis remains fragile.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to an international banking conference in Chicago,
Greenspan said productivity (output per hour of work) had clearly
risen recently and he credited large investments being made in
computers and other high-tech products of the information age.
</P>
<P>
He said it is this increase in productivity that has allowed
the economy to grow as rapidly as it has in the past few years
without fostering higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's speech represented the most thorough view presented
so far by the Fed in a debate among economists over what has been
responsible for the extraordinary performance of the U.S. economy.
The economy has survived the global financial turmoil and
continued to expand at a strong clip without inflation.
</P>
<P>
But Greenspan also pointed out that the gains in productivity
cannot keep inflation at bay forever. He warned that the nation's
longest peacetime expansion will be threatened at some point down
the road by the tight labor markets.
</P>
<P>
He disagreed with some economists' claim of a new economic era
in U.S. saying "I have experienced far too many alleged new eras
in my lifetime that have come and gone".
</P>
<P>
U.S. productivity, which had been barely increasing at a weak 1
percent annual rate in the early 1990s, has been rising at close
to a 3 percent rate over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said while some of this may be a temporary upturn, he
believes the overall rise reflects the strong investments
businesses have been making in recent years, due to low interest
rates, in new computers and other productivity-enhancing
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Fed policy-makers will have to remain alert to address
imbalances in the economy, the most significant being the tight
labor markets, Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
"As I have said on previous occasions, there are imbalances in
our expansion that, unless redressed, will bring this long run of
strong growth and low inflation to a close," he said.
</P>
<P>
"At some point, labor market conditions can become so tight
that the rise in nominal wages will start increasingly outpacing
the gains in labor productivity," Greenspan added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the world economic situation, Greenspan said while
there were signs that the crisis countries in Asia were beginning
to recover, but the recovery "though real, remains fragile."
</P>
<P>
"With a little backing and filling, the emerging-nation crises
of the last two years are likely to gradually dissipate and these
countries should move onto a significant recovery path," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
