<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genocide Allegations Directed at Top Rwandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan prime minister's office
continued to be plagued by mounting allegations of involvement in
the 1994 genocide levelled against its top officials.
</P>
<P>
After allegations directed against Prime Minister Pierre
Celestin Rwigema himself, the arrest and trial of his former
director of cabinet, Antoine Bizimana, on genocide charges, and
the arrest of his personal secretary Martin Sibomana, the
newly-appointed Secretary-General Celestin Kabanda is reportedly
faced with similar charges, the Rwanda News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
''We were disappointed at hearing that the cabinet appointed
Kabanda at that very sensitive post,'' one member of the prime
minister's party -- the Democratic Republican Movement -- who
asked not to be named, confided. ''It is as if no prior
investigation was made into his case,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
Kabanda was appointed secretary-general in the prime minister's
office on April 23, 1999 by the cabinet meeting. He was
previously working in the Ministry of Agriculture. This post has
been vacant since last year following the death of Anastase
Nderebeza.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Rwandan capital Kigali as well as in
Kibuye Prefecture alleged that Kabanda actively participated in
the 1994 genocide as a ring-leader, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
''This man cannot dare go back to his village,'' one source
told the news agency. ''He knows that everyone there knows about
what he did there in 1994,'' the source added.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the police in Kigali arrested Kabanda three
times for genocide charges but he was released thanks to the
intervention of some big shots, including former Gendarmerie Chief
of Staff Col. Deogratias Ndibwami, Rwigema himself, former Justice
Minister Faustin Nteziryayo, now in exile in North Carolina in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
This new development in the Prime Minister's Office has raised
many questions about why Rwigema always shows preference to such
people whose reputation has been tarnished by their alleged role
in the tragedy which befell Rwanda five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Allegations against Kabanda hit the streets of the capital
while his boss himself still struggles to clear himself up of
alleged participation in the genocide which were widely spread in
local and international media.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Rwigema was involved in distributing arms
to marauding Hutu gangs of killers in one of the capital's
neighborhood, Biryogo, and was drawing lists of Tutsis to kill.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema strongly rejected the accusations blaming them on his
political foes who want to assassinate him politically by
spreading such unfounded accusations.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Vice-President Major General Paul Kagame, recently
told reporters that when such accusations are levelled against
such a high- ranking official or any political leader of his
caliber, they ''must be taken seriously, and more so carefully.''
</P>
<P>
Although there has been no official confirmation, it is
reported that a case file has been opened about the alleged role
Rwigema might have played in the massacres in Biryogo.
</P>
<P>
As for his former director of Cabinet, the prosecution had
requested death penalty for his role in the massacres of over
20,000 Tutsis in his home commune of Mbazi, southern Butare,
between April and July of 1994. The final verdict is still
awaited.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to claims by the Prime Minister, Kabanda in person
acknowledged that his case file has been established by the Muhima
brigade, and that he was interrogated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
''It is not the first time these allegations are levelled,''
Kabanda said. ''I was asked about my participation in the
destruction of the Nyange Church.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0024 </DOCNO>
