<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean State Enterprises Incur Huge Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's major public enterprises
incurred huge losses totalling 10.6 billion Zimbabwean dollars
(278 million U.S. dollars) during the 1997/98 fiscal year largely
due to mismanagement, inappropriate investment and the unfavorable
economic climate, the Treasury has said.
</P>
<P>
In a summary of the Public Enterprises' 1998 performance
released Thursday, the Treasury said the major contributors to the
losses were the National Oil Company, the Electricity Supply
Authority, the Cold Storage Company, the National Railways and the
Iron and Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural Finance Corporation was the only major
government-owned enterprise to make a profit of 50.5 million
Zimbabwean dollars (1.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is under the second phase of its economic reforms
dubbed the Zimbabwe Program for Economic and Social
Transformation.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury said a number of achievements had been made in the
 implementation of the program launched last year.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the government was progressing with the
establishment of the Revenue Authority meant to increase revenue
collection and improve on administrative efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to trim the size of the civil service and thus reduce
the wage bill were continuing although the actual size remained
high due to need of personnel in sectors such as health, education
and specialized fields.
</P>
<P>
The civil service rationalization exercise was expected to
continue with 6,000 posts abolished by December, 1999, according
to the Treasury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
