<HEADLINE> Protestors Closely Watch NATO Activities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Anti-war protestors in the northern
Greek port city of Thessaloniki are now closely watching the
activities of NATO vehicles heading for neighboring Macedonia and
ready to block the port's gates at any movement.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) Thursday quoted an
anti-war committee member as saying that they had groups of
monitors watching the gates of the port and in the case of NATO
activity, they would immediately inform members of the committee
and the local Communist Party branch to set up a blockade.
</P>
<P>
Continued NATO bombing against Yugoslavia and civilian
casualties would only serve to harden the stance of the committee
against NATO forces using Thessaloniki as a vital landing and
transit point for any operations in the neighboring country,
committee member and municipal councillor Agapios Sahinis said.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 vehicles, including armored tanks and supply
containers, as well as hundreds of soldiers, are reportedly
waiting to head out of Thessaloniki to NATO operations in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
NATO officials were reported to be concerned about the
increasing frequency of protests and obstruction of NATO work
despite the fact that the largest part of the NATO force
originally planned for Macedonia are already in place.
</P>
<P>
In another port city of Piraeus, near Athens, three foreign
banks, the American-based Chase Manhattan bank, the British-based
Midland bank and the French-based Banque Nationale de Paris were
attacked by anti-tank rockets shortly after midnight Wednesday.
</P>
