<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Slams NATO Air Strikes as Being "Genocidal" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia, which has accused
the U.S.-led NATO of mounting "genocidal" air strikes, said the
destructive power of the explosives so far used was equal to that
of about nine Hiroshima-type atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president of the U.N. Security Council
circulated on Thursday, Vladslav Jovanovic, charge d'affairs of
the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations, said NATO used
"special bombs" on May 2 to attack power plants and transmission
stations, blacking out hospitals, water supply systems, food
stores and bakeries.
</P>
<P>
"The air strikes were aimed at destroying the power grid of
the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They constitute unprecedented crimes, genocidal in nature, as
they target the entire population of Yugoslavia and are aimed at
provoking shortages of food and other essential provisions which
would cause widespread famine and, eventually, a humanitarian
catastrophe of unseen proportions," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
In another open letter to all agricultures and specialized
agencies in agricultural field, Yugoslav Agriculture Minister
Nedeljko Sipovac said his country had been the target of "11,000
tons of most destructive explosive."
</P>
<P>
This was "on average more than a kilogram (2.2 pounds) per
citizen, which equates to the destructive power of about nine
atomic bombs launched on Hiroshima," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sipovac, whose letter was also sent to ministers of
agriculture and specialized governmental agencies in other
countries, said that "by daily planned bombing NATO has caused
(an) ecological catastrophe, not only on the territory of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, but on the territories of all
Balkan, Danube Basin, Mediterranean and European countries as
well."
</P>
<P>
He cited what he said were attacks on chemical plants and
fertilizer factories, use of ammunition containing depleted
uranium, and the "burning of vast quantities of oil, gasoline,
crude oil, asphalt, tyres and other materials at high
temperatures."
</P>
<P>
He said the pollution "permanently endangers the flora and
fauna of the river basins of the Black Sea, the Adriatic Sea, the
Aegean Sea and the Mediterranean Sea."
</P>
<P>
The NATO air strikes, which entered the seventh week Thursday,
has created a large exodus of refugees from Kosovo, a Serbian
province, and huge damages to civilian facilities, including
civilian residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
