<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Keen on Iraq's Unity, Integrity: Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid on Thursday expressed the league's keenness on Iraq's
national unity and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Iraqi Justice
Minister Shabib al-Maliki, Abdel-Meguid said the league is opposed
to any attempt to interfere in Iraq's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League rejects the so-called no-fly zones in the north
and south of Iraq as "lacking in international legitimacy," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain set up the no-fly zones to
allegedly protect the ethnic Kurdish minorities in the north and
the Shiite Muslims in the south of Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War,
which drove the Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The league is "in continued contact with" the United Nations,
its chief Kofi Annan and the Security Council president on the
necessity to end the sufferings of the Iraqi people, Abdel-Meguid
said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi people are in dire need of food and medicine after
nearly nine years under U.N. economic sanctions imposed in 1990
following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The league is closely following the contacts and discussions in
the U.N. Security Council on the reports by the U.N. committees on
Iraq, especially the humanitarian committee in which the league is
participating, Abdel-Meguid said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
