<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Lawyers Appeal Against UK Extradition Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers acting for former Chilean
dictator Augusto Pinochet on Thursday launched a legal challenge
to the British Home Secretary's decision to allow extradition
proceedings against him.
</P>
<P>
The retired general's legal team went to the High Court to
lodge an application for a judicial review of Home Secretary Jack
Straw's authorization of extradition proceedings.
</P>
<P>
"I can confirm that after very careful consideration we have
today lodged an application for permission to apply for judicial
review of the Home Secretary's decision," Pinochet's solicitor
Michael Caplan said after filing papers at the High Court.
</P>
<P>
"I have informed both the home secretary and the government of
Spain. We are anxious for the application to be considered as
soon as is convenient to the court," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he would not discuss the grounds on which the lawyers will
appeal his case.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, was arrested in London last October at the
request of Spanish judges who are seeking to try him for crimes
including torture and genocide relating to his 1973-1990 rule in
Chile.
</P>
<P>
Spain will be represented at a later hearing that will
determine if the judicial review will be allowed. If it is
granted, it is likely to go ahead within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
In March, a seven-man panel of the Law Lords -- the UK's
highest court -- reduced the number of charges General Pinochet
would have to face.
</P>
<P>
They argued that only crimes allegedly committed after the UK
signed an international convention on torture in 1988 could be
tried.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet remains under armed guard at a rented mansion on the
exclusive Wentworth estate in the suburb of London while the
latest moves are made in this highly complex legal battle.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts expected that Pinochet's appeal would focus on
whether Straw had properly considered all factors in the case,
including the time which had elapsed since the alleged offenses as
well as the appeals by Chile for Pinochet to be returned home.
</P>
<P>
They also expected Pinochet's lawyers to question whether Straw
had properly considered the offenses attributed to Pinochet and
the views of Britain's top court, the Law Lords.
</P>
<P>
With all of the legal wrangling, no date for extradition
proceedings has been set.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
