<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Bestseller Published in Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Embassy here held a
ceremony this evening to mark the publication of the Chinese
version of the Australian bestseller A Fortunate Life by Albert
Facey.
</P>
<P>
It is the story of an ordinary Australian man who is tested by
many adversities in life. At the age of two, Facey lost his father,
and his mother had deserted him later. He started work at eight on
the rough West Australian frontier, struggled as an itinerant
rural worker, survived the gore of Gallipoli, the loss of his farm
in the Depression, the death of his son in World War II and of his
beloved wife after 60 devoted years.
</P>
<P>
Facey was one of those rare individuals who embraced life to
its fullest. Every experience, no matter how bad, was always
enriching. His guiding star was hope.
</P>
<P>
When Facey finally wrote his autobiography, he concluded, "I
have been very fortunate and I am thrilled by it when I look back.
"
</P>
<P>
Facey, who had no formal education, taught himself to read and
write. He made the first notes on his life soon after World War I.
Then, after retirement, at the suggestion and with the support of
his wife, Facey wrote his stories in book form.
</P>
<P>
The book was published in 1981, winning Facey great fame. The
unschooled, octogenarian kitchen-table writer died in 1982, aged
88, nine months after A Fortunate Life had been published to wide
acclaim.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has sold more than 500,000 copies worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Values Ties with Madagascar: Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China values its friendship and
cooperation with Madagascar, and is keen to work with Madagascar
to develop a long-term, equal, mutually beneficial and
comprehensive relationship into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao made this remark in a meeting
with Madagascar's Foreign Minister Lila Ratsifandriamanana.
</P>
<P>
He said that both peoples have a deep and traditional
friendship, and pointed to the fact that bilateral relations have
been developing well since the establishment of diplomatic ties 27
years ago, although the international situation and their
respective domestic situations have undergone great changes.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also maintained frequent high-level
exchanges of visits, and they have pursued gratifying cooperation
in a variety of areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that China appreciated and thanked Madagascar's
government for its adherence to the "One China Policy", and the
abolition of its "Special Arrangement" with Taiwan, as well as its
consistent support in the U.N. Conference on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-president also spoke highly of Madagascar's
domestic and foreign policies. He said that he appreciated the
efforts made by Madagascar's government and people, under the
leadership of President Didier Ratsiraka, to maintain national
stability, develop the national economy and promote regional
cooperation, as well as its increasingly important role in
regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ratsifandriamanana said that during her China visit, she had
seen for herself China's achievements in its economic construction
and the country's splendid cultural heritage. She added that the
two countries have a deep friendship, and that bilateral ties have
been developing rapidly and smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The visitor praised the bilateral relations highly, and thanked
China for its support and assistance for Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
She said that the two countries share the same views on many
international issues, including the Kosovo issue, human rights,
and the issue concerning respect for sovereignty and non-
interference in others' internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Madagascar firmly supported China at the U.N. Conference
on Human Rights held last month, she added, and expressed that
hope that the cooperation and friendship between the two
governments and peoples will continue to grow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
