<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Somali Town Council Resigned Amid Speculations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The permanent committee for the
district council of Merca Town, southern Somalia, Wednesday
resigned amid speculations, making the situation there uncertain.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that an administration of some sort
voluntarily steps down in the war-torn east African country. Merca
Town is the regional capital of Lower Shabelle region controlled
by faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aideed.
</P>
<P>
According to the members of the council, their resignation has
nothing to do with the arrival of the Oromo ethnic military
personnel who arrived in Merca Town, a natural port about 100 km
south of Mogadishu, Tuesday on a ship together with their arms.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of this mysterious ship shook the town and southern
Somalia as a whole. Reports speculated that the Eritrean
government is supporting Aideed in an extension of Eritrea's
year-long border conflict with its Horn of Africa neighbor
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Port officials said that the ship chartered by the Eritrean
government for Somalia is transporting between 500 and 700
military personnel mainly Oromo ethnic Ethiopians and quite a few
Eritrean officials.
</P>
<P>
The ship is also reportedly carrying over 40 anti-aircraft
heavy machine guns, about four armed personnel carriers, more than
80 other kinds of heavy machine guns, in addition to thousands of
assault rifles mainly AK- 47s and a large consignment of
ammunition for those guns together with their spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The heavy weapons aboard the ship are yet to be off-loaded, but
some food was off-loaded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an unusual meeting of the district council Wednesday, the
nine-member permanent committee forwarded their unanimous and
collective resignation from their official duties they held on
behalf of the people in the region in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
In a three-page document issued at the conclusion of the
meeting, the local authority of the port town of Merca said they
have seriously reconsidered the political, security and public
matters in the town.
</P>
<P>
In the document which was also made available for the press,
the committee said their resignation was prompted by the
increasing unemployment after the natural port of the town had
stopped 95 percent of its operations for the prevailing
circumstances in the town.
</P>
<P>
The increasing insecurity which they said is further raging and
the tax collected from the business centers, markets and shops
which never return back to the development of the town are among
the matters which forced the local authority to step down.
</P>
<P>
The use of the gun and organized crimes which are rampant
throughout the region have also forced the local authority to
reconsider their public duties and turn the responsibility back to
the people of Merca to elect again their own and appropriate
non-clan-based leaders to tackle their problems.
</P>
<P>
All nine members including their chairman, Sherif Abdurahman
Ahmed Dhegaweyneh, have signed the document.
</P>
<P>
Among the embarrassing issues forcing the local authority to
step down include the killing and robbing against the civilians on
the public transport buses from Merca Town toward the capital, and
the recent departure of the international aid workers from the
region due to insecurity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Blood Agency May Reject Donors Who Visited U.K. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Blood Service (CBS) said
Thursday it may stop accepting blood donations from people who
have traveled to the United Kingdom because they could have been
exposed to a fatal brain disease.
</P>
<P>
The CBS wants to avoid blood donations contaminated with new
variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease -- the human equivalent of
bovine spongiform encephalopathy, also known as mad-cow disease --
that may be transmissible through blood.
</P>
<P>
Ian Mumford, vice-president of communications for the CBS,
confirmed there was likely to be some sort of deferral of donors,
but the agency will seek advice from the public before it makes a
decision on which donors will no longer be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, about 598,000 Canadians visited Britain. A new
survey by the CBS found that 22 percent of the Canadian Blood
Service's donors have traveled to the U.K. since 1980, the period
where they would have been at risk of getting Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease.
</P>
<P>
In Britain, at least 40 people have contracted new variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease from eating tainted beef, as has one
person in France. But there has never been a confirmed case of the
disease in North America.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be aired publicly Thursday when the National
Blood Safety Council, an advisory body to federal Health Minister
Allan Rock, begins a two-day public forum in Vancouver on
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease and the blood system. Officials from
the blood agencies and experts from Canada, Britain and the U.S.
will discuss how to formulate an appropriate safeguard.
</P>
<P>
Canada would become the first country in the world to institute
a ban on donors who have been to the U.K.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
