<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets South African President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua)-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), today expressed
satisfaction over the development of relations between China and
South Africa, and the conviction that President Nelson Mandela's
current visit will further promote ties.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the visiting South African president, Li said
since the establishment of diplomatic relations early last year,
bilateral ties have grown smoothly, high-level contacts have been
frequent, and the momentum for cooperation in various fields has
been sound.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China, the
Chinese government and people have always sympathized with and
firmly supported the South African people's struggle for racial
equality and national liberation, and fostered a deep friendship
with the African National Congress and other liberation
organizations, he noted, adding that Chinese leaders of different
generations have all paid special attention to relations with
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Li said that since the end of the 2nd session of the Ninth NPC,
Chinese leaders have paid visits to some European, American, and
Asian countries, and sent a message worldwide that China is firmly
devoted to the causes of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to further consolidate relations with South
Africa and other African countries, and develop friendship with
all countries, based on the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-
existence, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Li said that contacts between the NPC and the South African
National Assembly have been increasing. Last year, he received
Frene Ginwala, speaker of the South African National Assembly, in
Beijing, and they reached a common understanding on expanding
cooperation. He said China welcomes more parliamentarians from
South Africa to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Mandela expressed thanks for China's past selfless support for
South Africa in its struggle for racial equality and national
liberation. He agreed with Li that bilateral relations have
progressed greatly since the establishment of diplomatic ties,
saying this has brought about benefits to both sides.
</P>
<P>
He said his current visit is successful, and expressed the hope
that it will raise bilateral ties to a new level.
</P>
<P>
The two also exchanged views on the African situation and other
issues of common concern.  
</P>
</TEXT>
