<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Says Africa's Growth Prospects Better in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) said here Thursday that Africa's
economic growth prospects in 1999 would be better than in 1998 and
forecasted that Africa's growth rate would increase to four
percent from 3.3 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The "Economic Report on Africa in 1999" issued by the ECA said
the 3.3 percent growth rate in Africa last year, compared with 2.9
percent growth in 1997, was the highest among regions of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"For the fourth consecutive year, gross domestic product (GDP)
in Africa grew faster than population, contrasting markedly with a
decade and a half of declining per capita income," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
On performance at sub-regional level, the report said North
Africa doubled its growth rate from 2.1 percent in 1997 to 4.4
percent last year, while central African countries improved their
performance to 4.9 percent last year from 4.0 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"In the remaining three (regions), there was definite
deceleration in growth momentum," the report said, adding that
West Africa declined from 4. 1 percent to 3.6 percent, East Africa
from 2.8 percent to 2.5 percent and Southern Africa from 2.5
percent to 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
For sub-Saharan Africa, recovery was robust, at 2.6 percent,
from two percent in 1997, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Africa's 11 oil-exporting countries
obtained their 3.7 percent growth rate in 1998, compared with 3.6
percent in 1997, while 42 non-oil exporting countries increased
their growth rate from 2.3 percent in 1997 to 2.9 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The 33 least developed countries in Africa continued to
increase and deepen their growth momentum and they managed to
boost their growth to 4.1 percent in 1998 compared with 2.4
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Africa's agriculture grew by 3.5 percent compared with 1.7
percent of the previous period while industrial sector grew by 3.2
percent in 1998, down from 3.8 from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Africa's export revenue declined by 17 percent, down to 95.6
billion U.S. dollars in 1998. "For the first time in the decade
of the 1990s, the trade balance turned negative, boosting the
current account deficit to a high of 16.5 billion U.S. dollars,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Resource flows into Africa declined to three billion U.S.
dollars from 4. 5 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 as the result of
reduced private flows and bilateral credit, the report said. For
sub-Saharan African countries net transfers declined by nearly 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Africa's total debt was 350.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 and
the debt service at the same period was 35.7 billion dollars,
raising the debt service ratio to nearly 31 percent of goods and
service exports in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"If Africa is to reduce poverty by half over the next decade
and half, it would need to attain and sustain an average growth
rate of seven percent per annum," the report said, adding "this is
the major challenge for African policy-makers and their
development partners." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
