<HEADLINE> Tanzania Trade Account Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade account
deteriorated by 4.3 percent to a deficit of 91.8 million U.S.
dollars during March, compared with 88 million recorded in the
previous month, the central bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration was contributed by a significant decrease in
export earnings which went down by 14.1 percent, despite a
1.8-percent decrease in imports, the Bank of Tanzania said in the
April issue of its monthly economic review .
</P>
<P>
The decrease in export earnings was mainly due to a fall in
export volumes as well as decline in export unit prices. Earnings
from traditional sector decreased by 15.2 percent while
non-traditional export earnings increased by 12.2 percent over the
review period.
</P>
<P>
Decreases in export unit prices of cotton, sisal, tea, tobacco
and cashew nut and decreases in export volume of coffee, tobacco
and cashew nut caused the decline in traditional export earnings.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the bank said Tanzania's annual
inflation rate increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared with the
rate recorded in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest national food supply statistics indicate that a
shortage of 585,000 tons of grain emerged in the first half of
this year, due to inadequate short rains experienced in most parts
of the country since last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
