<HEADLINE> Tanzania's External Debt up 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's external debt has
risen to approximately 8.3 billion U.S. dollars, the central bank
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The total debt committed at the end of March this year stood at
8.295 billion U.S. dollars, representing an increase of 4.7
percent when compared with 7.923 billion U.S. dollars registered
at the end of March of 1998, the Bank of Tanzania said.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total amount, disbursed outstanding debt was 6.836
billion U. S. dollars while committed undisbursed debt was 1.459
billion U.S. dollars, the Bank said in the April issue of its
monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
When the disbursed outstanding debt is classified by economic
sectors, it reveals that for the period ending March this year,
25.9 percent of the debt was disbursed in the form of balance of
payments support, while transport &AMP; telecommunications and
agriculture received 20.1 percent and 14 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Energy &AMP; mining received 12 percent, followed by industries
which absorbed 7.7 percent of the debt.
</P>
<P>
Social welfare and education, finance and insurance and tourism
received 4.2 percent, 3.2 percent and 1.2 percent of the debt,
respectively. The remaining 11.7 percent of the debt was absorbed
by other sectors.
</P>
<P>
In March of 1999, new loans amounting to 10.2 million U.S.
dollars were contracted. During the same period, disbursements
amounted to 13.1 million U.S. dollars, while actual debt service
amounted to 20.6 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
