<HEADLINE> Number of U.S. Jobless Claims Rises Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of first applications
for unemployment benefits increased slightly last week after two
consecutive weekly declines.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported Thursday that 301,000 people
filed for jobless benefits, an increase of 6,000 from the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
In the previous week, the benefit applications had dipped below
the 300,000 level to 295,000. From late January through mid-March,
the weekly applications number remained below 300,000 for a nine
week stretch, the longest period since 1973.
</P>
<P>
The Thursday's jobless claims report showed that a four-week
moving average for claims was essentially unchanged at 307,000,
compared to 307,500 the previous week.
</P>
<P>
In state-by-state data which lags the national figures by one
week, the Labor Department said 35 states and territories had
decreases in claims for the week ending April 24, and 17 had
declines with one reporting no change.
</P>
<P>
The largest increase in unemployment claims was in
Massachusetts, a rise of 4,639, reflecting increased layoffs in
service industries; Rhode Island, an increase of 1,161 because of
higher layoffs in service industries and manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
