<HEADLINE> At Least Four People Killed by Storms in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- At least four people were killed
as a line of powerful tornadoes blew through the west of the U.S.
state of Tennessee early Thursday, damaging buildings in 30
counties.
</P>
<P>
Two of the victims, a man and woman, died in Linden City when
their home was destroyed by winds. A 14-year-old girl, who had
been missing since Wednesday night, was found early Thursday and
taken to a hospital where she died upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
The fourth person was killed when his car hit a tree that had
been blown down across the highway in Madison County.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified number of injuries were reported in Tennessee.
Funnel clouds were spotted in eight counties.
</P>
<P>
Nashville International Airport was closed for a time because
of the winds. Two people received minor injuries due to flying
debris and about 30 small planes in a hangar were damaged, airport
officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the counties reported scattered power outages, downed
trees and torn-off house roofs and some damaged buildings. Near
Nashville City, several campers at a trailer park were injured.
</P>
<P>
It was the third straight night that deadly tornadoes have hit
southern plains of the United States. Forty-three people were
reportedly killed in Oklahoma, Kansas and Texas States earlier
this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
