<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern met in Downing Street on
Thursday, opening a new round of Northern Ireland negotiations on
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The two premiers met with key party leaders of the province in
fresh efforts to end the political stalemate over arms
decommissioning in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Ulster Unionists, the Social Democratic and
Labor Party (SDLP) and Sinn Fein were scheduled throughout
Thursday to have their own sessions with Blair and Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Despite efforts by the leaders of the two countries, government
officials did not believe that the talks would deliver a
breakthrough on the issue of paramilitary weapons.
</P>
<P>
"There's no new blueprint on the table, but there are a number
of ideas around that we want to tease out and discuss with the
parties," said a Downing Street spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"There are well known difficulties but there's a determination
to move this forward," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party, led by Northern Ireland First
Minister David Trimble, has refused to sit with Sinn Fein in
government unless the IRA first begins to dispose of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein and the IRA have refused to surrender their arms,
arguing that handing over weapons was not a precondition of the
peace agreement for Sinn Fein to join the cabinet. 
</P>
