<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mainland City, Macao Company End Debt Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The city government of Jingzhou in
central China's Hubei Province and the Macao-based Keymon
International have ended their three-year-old debt dispute through
intermediation by China's Supreme People's Court, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
The concerned parties in Jingzhou have paid back 2.6 million U.
S. dollars to the Macao investor, while the overseas lender has
donated five million RMB yuan to the city.
</P>
<P>
Observers here urge local governments at all levels to learn a
lesson from the case, so as to promote the building of China's
market economy, especially at a time when China is eager for early
entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
In July 1991, the leader of a synthetics project in Shashi,
which was later merged with Jingzhou City, based on the former
Jingzhou Prefecture, borrowed 2.05 million British pounds and 20.
50 million Deutsche Marks from the Macao company with an
irreversible guarantee issued by the city government.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the debtor factory began to return the money gradually.
However, it failed to repay the whole debt, due to financial
problems caused by market fluctuations. By June 1996, the two
parties confirmed that the synthetics producer still had to repay
the remaining sum of 2.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The creditor then brought a lawsuit against the city government,
the city finance bureau and the synthetics company.
</P>
<P>
The dispute aroused due to the different legal systems in Macao
and the Chinese mainland. In Macao, the government is eligible to
secure business deals, while in the mainland, governments are not
allowed to provide guarantee for the borrowing of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Both plaintiff and defendant, who also differed on the amount
of money the government had guaranteed, appealed to the Supreme
Court, when they received the ruling of the higher court of Hubei.
</P>
<P>
They finally reached an agreement in February this year, under
which the city government is obliged to supervise the problem and
help the synthetics manufacturer to repay the amount outstanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
