<HEADLINE> Beijing Sets Up Anti-Poisonous Gas Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A special team responsible for
fighting calamities related to poisonous gas leaks was set up here
today.
</P>
<P>
The team, operating under the municipal fire brigade, is
equipped with imported vehicles specially designed for this work,
as well as protective clothing and advanced rescue devices.
</P>
<P>
The members of the team have received special training.
</P>
<P>
Liu Ruixiang, director of the Beijing Fire Brigade, stressed
the importance of the new team at today's inauguration ceremony,
saying that as a result of rapid urban construction, the city is
likely to witness a high incidence of fire and explosion accidents
in oil, gas and chemical plants, and at underground construction
sites, involving leaks of poisonous gas.
</P>
<P>
Police statistics show that 4,763 fire accidents occurred last
year, which left 40 people dead and 101 injured, and caused 42
million yuan in direct economic losses. In many of these cases,
the fire-fighting work was obstructed by poisonous gas at the
sites.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the establishment of the team will substantially
enhance the rescue ability of Beijing's Fire Brigade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
