<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Distributes Nearly 500,000 Tons of Food in 9 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
distributed 497,000 tons of food grains under the vulnerable group
feeding (VGF) program among flood victims across the country
during the past nine months, the official BSS news agency reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The food grains distribution through VGF cards began shortly
after the devastating floods that started to strike the country in
July last year, Press Secretary to the Prime Minister Jawadul
Karim said in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In view of the huge losses of crops due to the two-month-long
flood, the government embarked upon a massive VGF card
distribution program and distributed 400,000 cards in October
1998, with another 200,000 cards added in November the same year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
About 30 million people in 53 of the country's 64 districts
were affected by the prolonged flood, inflicting an estimated loss
of 4.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, each card holding family was given eight
kilograms of rice and eight kilograms of wheat each month till
November, and five kilograms of rice and 15 kilograms of wheat
from December to April this year except the month of January,
according to Karim.
</P>
<P>
The distribution and implementation of VGF cards were made
through three committees, comprising people's representatives,
government officials and representatives from non-government
organizations, with members of parliament as advisers, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the VGF program, the government also sanctioned
195,000 tons of wheat under the Food for Work Program for the
post-flood rehabilitation activities, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
