<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 FMs Pass Framework Pact on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn May 6 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the Group of
Eight (G-8), seven western industrialized countries and Russia,
ended their talks Thursday at Petersburg near Bonn with a five-
point statement, including seven "general principles" on a
political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers agreed that Yugoslavia should withdraw
from Kosovo its military, police and paramilitary forces.
</P>
<P>
They also called for establishment of an interim administration
for Kosovo to be decided by the U.N. Security Council to ensure
peaceful and normal life for all inhabitants there.
</P>
<P>
An effective international civil and security presence,
endorsed and adopted by the United Nations, should be deployed in
Kosovo to guarantee the achievement of the common objectives, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers urged a political process to be initiated towards
the establishment of an interim political framework providing for
substantial self-government for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo self-governing process must take full account of the
Rambouillet accords and the principles of sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Yugoslavia and the other countries of the
region.
</P>
<P>
And the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army should be demilitarized,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Other principles include: the safe and free return of all
refugees and displaced persons and unimpeded access to Kosovo by
humanitarian aid organizations, a comprehensive approach to the
economic development and stabilization of the crisis-torn region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
