<HEADLINE> Kenya to Safeguard Donor Aid to Health Sector: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Health Minister Jackson
Kalweo has pledged that his government will safeguard donor aid
to the health sector reform program at all cost.
</P>
<P>
Opening a donors' group meeting at the World Health
Organization office here Wednesday, Kalweo noted that his
government greatly valued donor contributions to the health sector
and would not want to see the assistance halted due to
misunderstanding, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied press reports that relations between his
ministry and some of donors were sour.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a recent report that a Danish donor had
withdrawn a 600-million-shilling assistance to the health sector
reform program following the ministry's failure to satisfy all set
conditions.
</P>
<P>
While re-affirming his commitment to strengthening the
existing cordial relations with the development partners, Kalweo
urged key donors to the health sector reform program to be more
open and frank and to raise any issues relating to the program to
his ministry.
</P>
<P>
The spread of HIV/AIDS pandemic, Kalweo observed, has become
one of the most different health challenges facing the country
today as the AIDS patients consume 50 percent of the resources
available.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that a National AIDS Council will be
established by December this year to fight and control the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Malaria, Kalweo added, previously confined to a few parts of
Kenya, is now widespread throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
