<HEADLINE> Highlight of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released today.
</P>
<P>
NPC Chairman Stresses Sino-South African Ties
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), today expressed satisfaction over the
development of relations between China and South Africa, and the
conviction that President Nelson Mandela's current visit will
further promote ties.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the visiting South African president, Li said
that China is willing to further consolidate relations with South
Africa and other African countries, and develop friendship with
all countries, based on the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-
existence.
</P>
<P>
Mandela agreed with Li that bilateral relations have progressed
greatly since the establishment of diplomatic ties, saying this
has brought about benefits to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Top Legislator Lauds Sino-Thai Friendship
</P>
<P>
Sino-Thai relations have been proceeding in an extensive and in-
depth way, as the two nations are sincere friends and good
neighbors, China's top legislator Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee, said this when meeting with Somsak Kiatsuranont, deputy
speaker of the House of Representatives of Thailand, and his
parents here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Somsak Kiatsuranont said that he is here to strengthen
relations between the two parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets S. African President
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today expressed appreciation of the
South African new government's domestic policy of pragmatism, and
its foreign policy of advocating a peaceful settlement of
international disputes.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government is willing to further expand
cooperation with South Africa in various forms based on equality
and mutual benefit," he noted.
</P>
<P>
 Vice-President: China Values Ties with Madagascar
</P>
<P>
China values its friendship and cooperation with Madagascar,
and is keen to work with Madagascar to develop a long-term, equal,
mutually beneficial and comprehensive relationship into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao made this remark in a meeting
with Madagascar's Foreign Minister Lila Ratsifandriamanana.
</P>
<P>
Ratsifandriamanana said that the two countries share the same
views on many international issues, including the Kosovo issue,
human rights, and the issue concerning respect for sovereignty and
non-interference in others' internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese FM Spokesman on TMD
</P>
<P>
China has today expressed strong displeasure with and resolute
opposition to the incorporation of Taiwan into the U.S. Theater
Missile Defense (TMD) system.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao made the remarks at the
regular press conference when asked to comment on a recent report
submitted by the U.S. Defense Department to the U.S. Congress on
TMD Architecture Options for the Asia-Pacific Region, in which it
makes "research" on the incorporation of Taiwan into the TMD.
</P>
<P>
"The move has violated the principles set forth in the China-U.
S. August 17 Communique and constituted a serious interference of
China's internal affairs," he said, adding that the move is also
detrimental to the stability across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
</TEXT>
