<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renewed Commitment Required to Eradicate Polio by 2000: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Renewed efforts are needed to meet the
goal of polio eradication in the South-East Asia Region by the
year 2000, the World Health Organization (WHO) said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite remarkable progress made by all its 10 member countries
in the region, four countries have to accelerate efforts to ensure
that the region is polio-free by the end of the century, according
to a press release from the WHO Regional Office for South-East
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The WHO, which is leading the international efforts to
eradicate polio by the year 2000, concluded the sixth annual
meeting of the Technical Consultative Group TCG) of the South-East
Asia Region on vaccine preventable diseases here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number of reported polio cases in the region decreased from
25,711 cases in 1987 to 2,268 in 1998, and Indonesia, Myanmar and
Thailand, after making remarkable achievement in controlling
vaccine-preventable diseases, have joined other polio-free
countries of the region: Bhutan, Maldives and Sri Lanka, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Only four countries - Bangladesh, the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), India and Nepal - in the region remain
polio-endemic.
</P>
<P>
The TCG recommended that the four countries should plan and
conduct "mopping-up campaigns" to reach every child along with
National Immunization Days and sub-National Immunization Days to
ensure all children are protected.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh, the DPRK, India and Nepal need to implement
expansive house-to-house, door-to-door, boat-to-boat polio
immunization campaigns in the remaining areas where polio virus
continue to persist," the release said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the four countries are on track to meet the
December 31, 2000 deadline, the TCG will meet in a mini-session in
September this year to review polio eradication progress in these
countries.
</P>
<P>
Critical to the eradication process is detection of cases of
acute flaccid paralysis, a symptom of polio, and essential to
polio eradication is a good surveillance system, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The South-East Asia Region accounts to more than half the
world's cases of polio each year, with most the cases from India,
followed by Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
