<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Keeps Interest Rates Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England has decided to
keep interest rates at 5.25 percent despite calls from
manufacturers to lower them.
</P>
<P>
On making its decision the Bank's Monetary Policy Committee
referred to "encouraging signs of recovery" Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is only the second time in the past eight months the
committee has pegged the level of rates amid expectations that the
current cycle of rate reduction is at or near an end.
</P>
<P>
The decision was hardly a shock as a majority of economists and
analysts had been predicting no change.
</P>
<P>
Although this hold on the interest rates is disappointing news
for British manufacturing, which had lobbied for a cut, the Bank
expects sterling to weaken from its "present high level".
</P>
<P>
The Bank says: "If sterling were not to weaken as assumed,
there might.... need to be further easing of interest rates in
order to keep inflation on track to meet the 2.5 percent target."
</P>
</TEXT>
