<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Calls for Political, Peaceful Settlement for Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Ambassador to the United
Nations Office at Geneva (UNOG) has urged NATO to stop aggression
against his country in order to reach a political and peaceful
settlement for the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The most important precondition to settle all political issues
in Kosovo and Metohija and to resolve humanitarian problems is
halting NATO aggression, destruction and killing of people," said
Branko Brankovic at a press conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the lasting commitment of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to reach a political, peaceful settlement for the
crisis in Kosovo and Metohija," the Yugoslav ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that direct talks with equal participation of
representatives of all national communities are the direct way of
achieving a broad autonomy, with the April 28 joint statement by
Serbian President Milan Milutinovic and Ibrahim Rugova as an
example.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the operations of the Yugoslav military forces in
Kosovo, Brankovic said, "As long as NATO continues its aggression
it is the duty and responsibility of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to engage as many forces as needed for the defense of
the country, just as any other country in the same circumstances
would do."
</P>
<P>
However, he added, after the aggression stops and NATO forces
withdraw from Yugoslav borders, Yugoslavia will establish peace-
time level of deployment of its forces in Kosovo and Metohija.
</P>
<P>
On the issues of the safe return of refugees and displaced
Yugoslav citizens, Brankovic said that his country has already
several times publicly appealed for their return. "For the time
being, the only obstacle to their return is the continuous NATO
bombardments," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
As for an international presence in Kosovo and Metohija, the
Yugoslav ambassador said that the Yugoslav government is ready to
receive a UN-led mission but its structure and mandate shall have
its prior agreement.
</P>
<P>
Brankovic reaffirmed that Yugoslavia "will not accept to be
imposed on any solutions, interests and strategies which may put
Yugoslavia into the status of someone's colony or protectorate."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministers Meet on Financing Africa's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A joint conference of African
ministers of finance, economic development and planning opened
Thursday here at the United Nations Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
This conference, the first joint meeting organized by the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) since its
structural reform in 1997, is taking place against the background
of a number of important developments that pose serious challenges
to financing Africa's economic and social development and thereby
alleviating poverty on the continent.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
said Africans today are at a very critical juncture in their
history and the challenges Africans face are complex and the task
they face to ensure sustainable development is indeed herculean.
</P>
<P>
"Our prospects for development hinge on our ability to mobilize
 resources for that task, and on our ability to make that
mobilization sustainable," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Africa's debt burden, Meles said "obviously the debt burden
of Africa which has now reached over 350 billion U.S. dollars and
representing a debt stock to export ratio of well over 300
percent, is by consensus beyond debt sustainability."
</P>
<P>
ECA Executive Secretary K.Y. Amoako recalled that the 1995
World Summit for Social Development ratified the plan to reduce
poverty in Africa by half by the year 2015, which requires a four
percent reduction in the number of people living in poverty each
year.
</P>
<P>
To reduce poverty by half by the year 2015, an average growth
rate of seven percent per year is required, he said, adding the
growth rate requires an investment rate equal to 33 percent of
gross domestic product, which in turn needs 15 percent of domestic
savings and nine percent of official development assistance.
</P>
<P>
Vijay S. Makhan, Assistant Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), said official development
assistance has fallen for six consecutive years, from 0.33 percent
of the combined gross national product (GNP) of the Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD)--Development
Assistance Committee (DAC) donors in 1992 to 0.22 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
This is now less than one third of the agreed U.N. target of
0.7 percent of the GNP, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 participants, including ministers of finance,
ministers of economic planning and development and governors of
national banks, from 53 African countries as well as
representatives from U.N. agencies, inter- governmental and
bilateral partners sectors are attending the three-day meeting
which will focus on challenges of financing African development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
