<HEADLINE> Fischer: Negotiations Still Needed After G8 Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- More negotiations will be needed after
the foreign ministers of seven leading western industrial
countries and Russia have passed a joint statement of general
principles aiming at solving the Kosovo crisis, German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which marked the first time that Moscow and the
Western agreed on a common policy on Kosovo, came amid diverging
views between the two parts, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we give you principles instead of the text for the
U.N. Security Council resolution," he said at a press conference
at Petersberg near Bonn after the G8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not mention the NATO, instead it called for
deployment of "an international civil and security presence
endorsed and adopted by the United Nations" in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But the Western stressed the NATO would have to play a main
role.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the "security
presence" in the satement meant "a strong military force with NATO
at its core".
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said only the NATO could
ensure the credibility and the implementation of the principles.
</P>
<P>
"It (the principles) must have teeth and those teeth will need
to be supplied by the NATO," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
It remains unclear whether Yugoslavia will accept the
principles, which need to be converted into a U.N. Security
Council resolution. But Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
Belgrade would give green light for the plan.
</P>
<P>
Other ministers attending Thursday's meeting came from France,
Italy, Canada and Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
