<HEADLINE> Israel's Main Parties Racing for Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Just about 10 days before the
general elections begin, the two main political parties in Israel
are maneuvering for the race.
</P>
<P>
There was growing feeling in the opposition Labor Party that
the race for premiership would be concluded in the first round of
elections scheduled for May 17, according to a report of Israel
Radio on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the ruling Likud Party also said that they were
expecting a decisive win in the first round.
</P>
<P>
A second round of voting will be held in early June if none of
the candidates for the premiership can get over 50 percent of the
votes in the first round.
</P>
<P>
The hope for a one-round voting emerged after a recent public
opinion poll showed that the supporting rate for the Center Party
leader Yitzhak Mordechai continued to drop.
</P>
<P>
The poll, published on Tuesday night, showed Mordechai would
win only 7 percent of the votes in the first round, compared to 12
percent in the last survey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor
leader Barak, according to the poll, would get more than 35
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Following the poll, the Labor Party has called for Mordechai to
join forces with it, in hope that Mordechai's supporters would
turn to Barak in the elections and the race for the premiership
would be able to finish in the first round.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, local analysts said that since a majority of
the newly-established Center Party had been traditionally Likud
supporters before Mordechai left Likud early this year,
Mordechai's drop in the race for the premiership might strengthen
Netanyahu's chance for winning.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Mordechai has insisted that he would not withdraw
from the race.
</P>
<P>
But senior officials of the Center Party told local daily
Haaretz on Thursday that if signs showed in the next few days that
Mordechai's pulling out of the race would not hurt his party's race
for the Knesset (parliament), a serious discussion of a withdrawal
scenario would be inevitable.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Israeli Interior Minister Eli Suissa
Thursday apologized for his remarks on the Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The minister, member of the right-wing Shas Party, said on a
TV campaign on Wednesday night that Shas and the Interior
Ministry are keeping the country from being overrun by call girls
and church-goers from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The remarks drew sharp criticism from the Yisrael Baaliya Party,
which mainly presents the interests of the Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The apology was made only after Netanyahu mediated between the
two parties on Thursday. Netanyahu reportedly is trying to get the
support of both Shas and Yisrael Baaliya in the coming elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
