<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, May 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- An Iraqi official newspaper Thursday urged
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to quickly move for the
unconditional lifting of the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ath-Thawra daily, the organ of the ruling Arab Baath Socialist
Party, said the U.S. and Britain will go ahead with their
feverish endeavor hostile to Iraq by premeditatedly holding off
Iraqi contracts signed under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The daily appealed to Annan to do his utmost and stand with
Iraq in its legitimate and legal demands and put pressure on
U.N. Sanctions Committee for speeding up the approval of
contracts with the aim of improving the humanitarian conditions
in Iraq. (BC-Iraqi Media-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An assasination attempt against former Iranian
President Hashemi Rafsanjani was discovered and disrupted, the
daily Iran News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An informed source told the daily that a group called Mahdiyoun
has targeted Rafsanjani. However, the source did not reveal
details about the issue.
</P>
<P>
The source said the group was also involved in the failed
assassination against head of Tehran Justice Department Ali
Razini, who was injured by a bomb adhered to his car in January.
(BC-Iran-Attempt-Rafsanjani)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Former mayor of Iranian capital Tehran Gholamhussein
Karbaschi, a well-known reformist, announced on Thursday morning
his readiness to serve prison terms over graft charges.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic News Agency reported that Karbaschi
introduced himself to the conservative judiciary while some of
his friends and a group of people gathered in front of the
judicial building to show their support for him.
(BC-Iran-Former Mayor-Prison)
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan saw an outbreak of meningitis with the total
number of contractors hitting 21,337, of whom 1,513 died since the
first week of last December.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of the Sudanese Health Ministry Prof. Bashir
Ibrahim told reporters that the recurrence rate of the epidemic
was low in the western Darfour province and high in other
provinces such as Khartoum. (BC-Sudan-Meningitis)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's doctors Thursday intensified their
strike for salary increases, shutting most of the nation's
hospitals and clinics except for emergency services.
</P>
<P>
The strike was launched by the Israel Medical Assosiation (IMA)
on Monday to protest against the lack of progress in the
negotiations with the Finance Ministry over wage growth.
</P>
<P>
The doctors are trying to win a new contract that would update
their salaries, set in a 1994 contract that expired in July 1998.
(BC-Israel-Doctors-Strike) 
</P>
