<HEADLINE> Fresh Round of N.Ireland Talks Achieve Little Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Little progress has been made in the
latest talks in London aimed at ending the stalemate in the
Northern Ireland peace process, a Downing Street spokesman said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said there was no prospect of a quick
breakthrough in negotiations involving Prime Minister Tony Blair,
his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern and key party leaders of the
province.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Ulster Unionists, Social Democratic and
Labor Party and Sinn Fein arrived later on Thursday for their own
sessions with Blair and Ahern.
</P>
<P>
As talks continued into the afternoon, a Northern Ireland
Office spokesman said the atmosphere was "low key".
</P>
<P>
He added: "The essential issues, the essential elements don't
change. It's a question of looking at different ways of bringing
things together. It's not for us to say 'this is the only way'.
</P>
<P>
Despite the continuing impasse Downing Street has stressed
there is "no question" of parking the Good Friday Agreement, which
provides for a power-sharing executive to be set up in the
province.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party, led by Northern Ireland First
Minister David Trimble, has refused to sit with Sinn Fein in
government unless the IRA first begins to dispose of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein has maintained publicly and privately that they
cannot deliver any IRA gesture on arms. 
</P>
