<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Welcomes Pacts on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council on
Thursday welcomed the agreements signed between Indonesia and
Portugal on East Timor and gave its support to Secretary-General
Kofi Annan in his efforts to solve the East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the council support the decision of the
Secretary-General to dispatch United Nations staff to East Timor
as soon as possible to assist in the implementation of the
agreements," said the council's May president Denis Dangue Rewaka
of Gabon.
</P>
<P>
The accords signed on Wednesday include East Timor's autonomy
package and security arrangements and procedures for a
U.N.-organized poll to determine the territory's future.
</P>
<P>
If a popular consultation results in the approval of the
autonomy by a majority of the East Timorese, Indonesia would
initiate the constitutional measures for the implementation of the
autonomy framework.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, on its part, would initiate the procedures for the
removal of East Timor from the list of Non-Self-Governing
Territories, now numbering 17 in the world, and the deletion of
the question of East Timor from the U.N. agenda.
</P>
<P>
If the majority rejects the proposed autonomy, Indonesia would
take the constitutional steps to terminate its links with East
Timor and restore the status the territory held prior to 1976.
</P>
<P>
Then Indonesia and Portugal would make arrangements for a
peaceful and orderly transfer of authority in East Timor to the
U.N. which would initiate a process enabling it to begin a
transition towards independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of 800,000 and an area of more
than 18,800 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until
1975 when a civil rift induced Indonesian occupation. In 1976
Indonesia annexed it and the U.N. has since been seeking a
solution to the question.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council Wednesday, Annan said the
U.N. will face logistical and other problems in carrying out the
consultation process in a short time-frame between now and the
poll on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Annan has emphasized the need for the parties to put the main
security elements in place, which include bringing armed civilian
groups under strict control and prompt arrest and prosecution of
those who incite or threaten to use violence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
