<HEADLINE> African States Urged to Pool Resources on Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the joint 33rd
World Tourism Organization (WTO) and 24th Africa Travel
Association (ATA) meeting in Accra Thursday stressed the need for
African countries to pool resources in order to make an impact on
the global tourism market.
</P>
<P>
 Delegates said that African states must also harmonize travel
 regulations and expedite action on conventions that facilitate
international travel "if they want to get their fair share of the
ever- growing lucrative tourism industry", the Ghana News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
 Delegates were deliberating on the theme "Access Africa:
tearing down the barriers to travel" at the five-day conference
being attended by more than 1,500 participants, including African
ministers of tourism.
</P>
<P>
The joint conference, the first of its kind, is under the
theme "Africa: tourism destination for the next millennium".
</P>
<P>
Delegates maintained that poor infrastructure and institutional
 facilities, coupled with conflicts on parts of the continent,
have rendered tourism development efforts insignificant.
</P>
<P>
They listed poor transportation network and travel formalities,
 numerous check points on roads, coupled with harassment by
customs officers, bureaucracy, poor marketing procedures and
political instability, as major obstacles to tourism development
on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Ousmane N'Diaye, WTO Representative for Africa, said it is
important for African countries to form national committees on
resolving travel problems.
</P>
<P>
N'Diaye, who projected that Africa would by 2020 get 75
million tourist arrivals, said national travel and tour
operators must also cooperate and plan joint packages to enhance
regional tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
