<HEADLINE> Computer Problem Delays Flights at U.S. Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A computer problem at the air
traffic control center on Long Island in New York State of the
United States delayed departures from Newark and LaGuardia
airports Thursday morning, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The traffic control center lost power in one of its main
computers, forcing a switch to a backup system, said U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) spokesman Jim Peters.
</P>
<P>
The Move prompted controllers to increase the separation
between departing flights from 16 to 32 kilometers, creating
delays of up to 45 minutes for each flight.
</P>
<P>
The problem was fixed in about 45 minutes, but flights out of
Newark were still being delayed as of mid-morning, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, computer problems at the main air traffic control
center for O'Hare International and Midway airports in Chicago in
Illinois State caused numerous flight delays and cancellations for
passengers traveling into and out of the city.
</P>
<P>
The trouble started when the Tracon Center in Elgin tested new
software that displays a plane's size on radar screens, said Tony
Molinaro, a spokesman at the FAA's Great Lakes office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
