<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON May 6 (Xinhua) - After a bright start, most European
markets reversed course Thursday to finish lower after an
inflation warning by Federal Reserve chief Alan Greenspan set
investors on edge.
</P>
<P>
"The performance of the American economy over the past seven
years has been truly phenomenal," he said. "There are imbalances
in our expansion that, unless redressed, will bring this long run
of strong growth and low inflation to a close."
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading shares ended the day
virtually unchanged at 6406, up a mere 4.9 points, after reaching
a high of 6485.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee voted to keep
the Bank's base rate at 5.25 percent, but the market had already
factored in the news.
</P>
<P>
Technology companies recovered from Wednesday's battering with
Sema and Misys putting on 36p to 586p and 8p to 541p respectively.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronically traded Xetra Dax finished down
0.37 percent at 5275.57 points. The floor traded Dax index of
shares also fell 0.62 percent to 5274.45 points.
</P>
<P>
French shares dipped into red ahead of Greenspan's speech on
the U.S. economy and kept on heading south. The CAC 40 leading
index slipped 0.8 percent, or 34 points, to 4333.24. 
