<HEADLINE> Sunflower Cultivation Becomes Popular in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The cultivation of sunflower as one of
the oil seed crops has become increasingly popular among
Bangladeshi farmers with the growing demand for edible oil.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture experts said that sunflower farming was less risky
because it could stand adverse weather condition and could be sown
and cultivated in winter as well as in summer.
</P>
<P>
The sunflower could be harvested after 90 to 100 days only from
the date of sowing the seeds and only four kilograms of seeds were
required for one acres, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
As Bangladesh has to import more than half of the edible oil
consumed in the country each year, sunflower cultivation has a
bright prospects, experts said.
</P>
<P>
In Nawabganj and Madaripur districts, northwest and southwest
of here respectively, sunflower cultivation has become visibly
popular, with an increasing number of farmers bringing more and
more acres of land under sunflower cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Sunflower was cultivated in about 30 acres of land in each of
the districts, according to local agriculture officials.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh produces only about 200,000 tons of edible oil a
year, far short of the country's domestic needs, according to the
Agricultural Extension Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
