<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guinea-Bissau Controled by Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Rebels seemed to be in control of
the west African country of Guinea-Bissau Friday after troops
loyal to President Joao Bernardo Vieira surrendered, according to
Portugal's Lusa News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier Humberto Gomes, Vieira's army commander, announced
that surrender, saying in a brief statement that he wanted to
avoid further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
"Taking account of the deteriorating situation and the
interests of the country, and that enough human life has been
sacrificed, the chiefs of staff of the armed forces, forces loyal
to the republic, declare their surrender," he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement was handed to the military representative of
Portugal, the country's former colonial power, for delivery to
rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
The president's army had laid down their arms in the capital
Bissau just hours after fierce fighting broke out Thursday night,
shattering a six- month truce since a peace deal was signed in the
Nigerian capital of Abuja in November, a Lusa report from Bissau
said.
</P>
<P>
Rebels, led by former army chief Ansumane Mane, have controlled
most of the country, one of Africa's poorest, soon after the
revolt first erupted on June 7 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
