<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Sees Economic Rebound Starting This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Friday he expects a strong economic rebound beginning this
year as a result of increased agricultural output, rising exports
and investments.
</P>
<P>
In his speech before the National Export Congress, Estrada
urged the export sector to support his administration's pro-poor
thrusts by creating more jobs and giving the poor in the
countryside a better life.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports grew 15 percent to 7.85 billion U.S.
dollars in the first quarter this year compared to 6.82 billion
U.S. dollars in the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the Philippines last year surged 17 percent to 29.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy that our export performance continues to rally
growth for the country. All throughout the crisis since the second
half of 1997, we maintained healthy, double-digit export growth
rates," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Estrada cited the observation of an
International Monetary Fund team that the country's agriculture
will grow by 2.6 percent to 3.4 percent this year to 2004 and that
the Philippines will be among the first to recover fully from the
regional economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The same team has projected that with the recovery in
agriculture, improved investments and the rebound in industrial
activity, the Philippine economy would be able to grow by 5.2
percent to 5.8 percent in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"There is so much expectation for an economic rebound to start
this year," he told exporters as he lauded the Department of
Trade and Industry and the private business sector for coming up
with an export master plan for 1999-2004.
</P>
<P>
Estrada approved the Philippine Export Development Plan, a
strategy that calls for sustained export growth in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
The plan, according to Estrada, will bring the benefits of the
export sector not only to a few Metro Manila-based businessmen but
also to the poor in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Estrada announced "decisive" government actions to
help the export sector cushion the impact of the prevailing Asian
currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Among these measures are easing the guidelines to make the
5-billion-peso (125 million U.S. dollars) special financing
program more accessible to small and medium enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The government will also explore the possibility of giving the
private sector access to low-interest funds, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
