<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Rises by 4.3 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate rose
by 4.3 percent in April as the number of lost manufacturing jobs
reached 402,000, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the April unemployment rate was only
slightly higher than the 29-year-low of 4.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. unemployment rate has been at or below 4.5 percent for
the past 12 months, the best showing in three decades, despite the
troubles being suffered by manufacturers and farmers.
</P>
<P>
Job creation actually accelerated sharply in April as the
losses in manufacturing were more than offset by big gains in
service sector, where 131,000 new jobs were created.
</P>
<P>
In all, payroll jobs shot up 234,000 in April after inching up
only by 7,000 jobs in March, which had been the weakest monthly
increase in more than three years.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate, which is based on a separate survey of
households, rose in April because the number of people entering
the work force looking for employment grew more rapidly than the
rise in the number of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earnings increased by three cents to 13.11
dollars in April. The length of the average working week rose to
34.5 hours from 34.4 in March.
</P>
<P>
The weakness in manufacturing included a drop of 7,000 jobs
because of a strike in ship building. Other manufacturing
industries shedding jobs last month included aviation, industrial
machinery, textiles and fabricated metals such as steel.
</P>
<P>
Jobs in mining fell by another 6,000 last month, reflecting
primarily cutbacks in oil and gas drilling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Army to Undertake Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Thai army will undertake
restructuring process, which is aimed at achieving its goals amid
the changing world situation, Army Commander-in-Chief General
Surayudh Chulanond said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Surayudh said the restructuring process is aimed at maintaining
the army's major principle with limited budgets and under the
rapid changing world situation.
</P>
<P>
The principle was to maximize its efficiency in national
defense, domestic order, security and national development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring was expected to be completed over the next 10
years with military personnel and major divisions being
maintained.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring process would automatically help reduce army
forces by 46,000 over the next eight years, from 236,000 at
present to 190,000 in 2007. 
</P>
</TEXT>
