<HEADLINE> Spanish Team Collects Rubbish on Mt. Annapurna I </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A Spanish team had collected about
1,500 kilograms of rubbish on the 8,091-meter Mount Annapurna I in
Nepal, the Nepali Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 18-member team named "Wilderness Annapurna I Expedition 99"
reached the Base Camp on March 26 and started the cleaning the
next day, the ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
They went as high as 7,200 meters to collect rubbish including
oxygen cylinders, tins, plastic materials, glass bottles, glass
and iron pieces and tent bass, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said about 1,500 Kgs of rubbish were brought to the Base
Camp. The team disposed about 300 Kgs of burnable rubbish in
Mristi Khola, a place one day walk down from the Base Camp.
</P>
<P>
They cleaned as well on the Base Camp-- Lete trail. About 1,
200 kilograms of rubbish were carried to Beni by nearly 650
porters and then to Kathmandu by trucks, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The team led by Ferran Garcia Creix, a 44-year-old photographer
from Barcelona of Spain, has a plan to carry the rubbish to Spain.
"The expedition has the objective of cleaning rather than climbing
the summit of the peak," the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Annapurna I is the 10th highest mountain in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
