<HEADLINE> Export Rebate Cheater Jailed for 14 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A local businessman has been
sentenced to 14 years in prison for export-rebate fraud.
</P>
<P>
The stiff sentence is seen as part of the country's campaign to
crack down on rampant fraud in this field.
</P>
<P>
Two local companies were ordered by the court in the Baoshan
District of Shanghai to pay 2.3 million yuan and 1.83 million yuan,
respectively, as fines for their involvement in the case.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, Zhuang Guohua, chairman of the board and general
manager of a village-based business firm, had collaborated with
the agent of a Hong Kong-based company to obtain over 4.7 million
yuan in export-rebate funds from the Customs by exporting empty
containers which were supposed to contain computer parts and
hardware.
</P>
<P>
In November 1997, Zhuang's criminal activities were uncovered
by local Customs officers, when they opened four containers and
found nothing in them.  
</P>
