<HEADLINE> Uganda Denies Rift with Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has denied
reports that it has any rift with Rwanda on the way to resolve the
armed conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued Friday, the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs described the New Vision and Monitor (newspapers) reports
about the rift and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa's
reconciliation efforts as groundless and therefore misleading.
</P>
<P>
"Both newspapers reduced the purpose of the mini-summit in
Dodoma to an attempt by President Benjamin Mkapa to resolve a rift
between Uganda and Rwanda over their military campaign in the
Democratic Republic of Congo," said the release.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry wishes to clarify that the Dodoma meeting was
part and parcel of the Lusaka process. It was a follow-up to the
Sirte meeting that was held recently in Libya," it added.
</P>
<P>
The summit in Dodoma, Tanzania, was convened to enable the
neighbors to enhance the peace process for the DRC and therefore
it was not an effort by Tanzania to reconcile Rwanda and Uganda
which enjoy cordial bilateral relations, the press release noted.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to the media to cross check information of this
nature before publication in order to avoid such erroneous
reports.
</P>
<P>
New Vision and Monitor, the two leading dailies in this capital
city, said Wednesday that the summit in Dodoma was an effort by
Mkapa to bridge the gap between Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
They said that the countries' position on the war in the DRC is
now at variance. Rwanda would like to march on to Kinshasa if they
can while Kampala wants to pull out because the situation at home
is not favorable.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have deployed many troops in the eastern part
of DRC to allegedly guard against their borders. DRC President
Laurent Kabila said they were aggressors. 
</P>
