<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Economies Grow in 1998 As World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- K.Y. Amoako, Executive Secretary
of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said
Friday that while the growth of world economy slowed from four
percent in 1997 to two percent in 1998, Africa's economies
actually expanded from a growth of 2.9 percent in 1997 to 3.3
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going three-day joint conference of African
ministers of finance, economic planning and development here in
the Ethiopian capital, Amoako said Africa has come out from being
the last among all regions in 1997 to the first in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his "report on the economic and social situation in Africa"
to the conference, the ECA official said as international economic
results suffered since commodity prices declined, Africa's balance
of trade turned negative for the first time this decade because
export revenue declined by a full 17 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Private resource flows into Africa were off 33 percent from an
already low base, he said, adding that these negative factors in
1998's performance are a source of worry for 1999.
</P>
<P>
On Africa's income inequality, Amoako said in Africa, those in
the top 20 percent receive nearly ten times the income of those in
the bottom 20 percent. "Forty-four percent of African people live
below the poverty line and a large number live close-by," he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently only 15 percent of Africans live in a national
economic environment considered adequate for sustainable growth
and development, he said, adding that "seven countries, with 27
percent of the population, have poor prospects for
sustainability".
</P>
<P>
The three-day joint conference, which has drawn some 500
participants from 53 African countries, will conclude Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader on Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar authorities continued to
publish on Friday evening the content of a recent interview by
French reporter Delphine Evmoon of the Faits and Projets Magazine
with Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first secretary
of the State Peace and Development Council.
</P>
<P>
This part of the interview, which deals with Myanmar's internal
affairs, was carried in an official "Information Sheet."
</P>
<P>
Asked why Myanmar refused to extradite Khun Sa, former drug
warlord, to the United States when he surrendered, Khin Nyunt said
that Khun Sa had made a pledge that he would not be involved in
narcotic drug activities in any way and abide the arrangements
made by the government.
</P>
<P>
"Now, he has totally given up his involvement in narcotics on
his own accord and is living (up) to the promises given to the
government, there exists no reason to extradite him to the U.S. to
be tried as a criminal," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Myanmar government's refusal to have dialogue with Aung
San Suu Kyi, general secretary of the opposition National League
for Democracy (NLD), he noted that he had initiated discussions in
August last year with U Aung Shwe, NLD chairman, for "confidence
building" between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He, however, complained that the NLD and Aung San Suu Kyi
insisted on including Aung San Suu Kyi at any meeting.
</P>
<P>
He accused the NLD of trying to create obstacles on the path to
discussions and derail the process of dialogue by issuing a
proclamation then calling for convening of the parliament of their
own on August 21.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Myanmar's new state constitution, Khin Nyunt
said that the guidelines of the new constitution are being drafted
in the on-going National Convention.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for certain time to discuss the topics of
sharing power in the legislative, executive and judicial branches,
assuring that the government has no desire to prolong this
process.
</P>
<P>
He added that once the new constitution is promulgated, the
Myanmar government will hand over state power to the
constitutional government.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar military government took over state power on
September 18, 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Increase Spending on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- African countries were urged
Friday to increase their budget on AIDS prevention activities.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Peter Piot, executive director of the
United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) at the on-going
three-day joint conference of African ministers of finance,
economic planning and development which was opened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Piot told participants that by one conservative estimate
one-quarter of the population of Africa, 150 million people, has
been personally affected by the epidemic. The nine most heavily
affected countries in the world are all in Africa.
</P>
<P>
At least nine million Africans have already died of AIDS, over
22 million Africans are currently living with HIV or AIDS, and
there are almost eight million African children under the age of
14 who have lost their mother or both parents to the AIDS
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Piot said, 3.5 million African adults were newly
infected with HIV and another half a million African children were
newly infected at birth because their mothers already carried the
HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, many in Africa and elsewhere still view AIDS
purely as a health problem. But in fact, it is much more than
this. AIDS is at the heart of the development agenda for Africa,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe today, he said, half of the in-patients in
hospitals are there because of AIDS-related illness and models
show that by 2005 AIDS treatment costs will be over 60 percent of
the Ministry of Health budget. "In Kenya by 2005 AIDS treatment
costs will be over 50 percent of the Ministry's budget," he added.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has conservatively estimated that countries with
high HIV prevalence will lose one percent of gross domestic
product (GDP) growth per capita annually.
</P>
<P>
A recent study found that in 1997, only 150 million U.S.
dollars a year was spent in African countries on AIDS prevention,
he said, adding "we are currently estimating that a billion
dollars or more needs to be devoted to AIDS programs in Africa, if
we are to come to grips with the epidemic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
