<HEADLINE> 410 Kosovo Refugees Arrive in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Four hundred and ten Kosovo
refugees, the first group of about 4,000 to come to Australia from
Macedonia refugee camps, arrived in Australia's largest city
Sydney Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Among those greeting the refugees at Sydney International
Airport were Australian Prime Minister John Howard, his wife
Jeanette, Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock and his wife.
</P>
<P>
The 410 Kosovars comprise 216 males and 194 females, 27 under
the age of two and eight over 60.
</P>
<P>
Howard indicated that they will not be allowed to stay in
Australia permanently.
</P>
<P>
"It is our solemn wish that you will soon be returned to your
homeland," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister announced last month that Australia will
accept 4,000 Kosovo refugees on a three-month basis, while
stressing that the refugees will not be granted permanent resident
status.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were later taken by bus to Sydney's East Hills
Barracks, about 25 km southwest of the city, and are expected to
stay there for about four days before leaving for Brighton
Barracks on Tasmania, an island state located about 400 km south
off the Australian continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
