<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Land Mine Conference Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The five-day meeting which has has drawn about 1,200
participants from 102 countries and some international
organizations, referred the anti- personnel mines to an insidious
instrument of war and terror, and said in the declaration that
states parties to the convention agreed that the use of the mines
exacerbate tensions and impede diplomatic efforts to find peaceful
solutions to conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on international community for any
possible assistance, be it financial or technical, to end the use
of anti-personnel mines around the world, so as to alleviate the
humanitarian crisis caused by them.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Mozambican Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao
who chaired the meeting told a press conference that he hoped all
United Nations members would become signatories of the Ottawa
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa Treaty was signed in December 1997 by 135 countries,
74 of which have ratified it. Its ambitious goal is to clear all
the mines on the earth, which is estimated to be over 300 million,
before the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
A report of the International Campaign to Ban Land Mines said
there are more than 100 million anti-personnel land mines planted
around the world, and that at least 108 countries are stocking
some 250 million anti- personnel land mines.
</P>
<P>
However, the report noted that more than 30 countries have
removed and destroyed 12 million such mines while 12 countries
have totally destroyed their land mine stocks.
</P>
<P>
Now, eight of the 12 big producers have signed on the Ottawa
convention on banning the use, stock, production and transfer of
anti-personnel land mines, said the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Grenades Found in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A batch of Japanese-made grenades was
found today at a construction site in Lindong Town in north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 58 grenades, buried at a depth of about one meter, were
discovered when a construction worker driving a bulldozer to
plough the earth.
</P>
<P>
The words "Made in Japan" can be clearly seen on them.
</P>
<P>
According to the historical records of the region, a group of
Japanese invaders attacked Bairin Zuoqi Banner, where the town is
located, in 1933, and occupied it until August 1945, when they
were expelled by troops of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
An official from the local historical relics administrative
department said that the Japanese soldiers stole a large number of
relics dating from the Liao and Jin dynasties (916-1234).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
