<HEADLINE> Canada to Support Peace Process in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Friday that it will
contribute 820,000 Canadian dollars (558,000 U.S. dollars) to
support the peace process in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's support will help East Timorese become more aware of
the democratic process and civic rights, enabling them to have
more influence in their future," said International Cooperation
Minister Diane Marleau.
</P>
<P>
"These initiatives will help create a favorable environment for
social and economic development," she added.
</P>
<P>
To help promote peace in the region, people in East Timor will
take part in conflict resolution and civic rights education. For
example, Development and Peace, a Canadian non-governmental
organization, will provide the tools necessary for the production
of radio programs that will recommend methods for peacefully
resolving conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian International Development Agency (CIDA) will work
with the Unitarian Service Committee, another Canadian non-
governmental organization, to increase the networking abilities of
local organizations and their capacity to peacefully resolve
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Canada, through CIDA, will contribute 820,000 Canadian dollars
over a two-year period towards these education and training
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Portugal signed an agreement on May 5 leading the
way for a UN-sponsored ballot on August 8 to determine East
Timor's future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
