<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists to Make 1st Arctic Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has decided
to initiate the country's academic research in the Arctic area,
and the first Arctic expedition by local scientists is scheduled
to be kicked off early in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Wang Dezheng, deputy director of the National Polar Research
Office, disclosed the academic program here today.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will be composed of scientists from 10
ministries and government-backed academic institutions. They will
study the effects of the North Pole and the Arctic Ocean on
China's climate and fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The "Snow Dragon", an ice-breaker that has be used in many
Antarctic journeys by Chinese scientists over the past 15 years,
will be used for the Arctic expedition, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will take more than two months, and the
scientists are expected to return home in late September.
</P>
