<HEADLINE> UN to Send International Staff to Northern Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations plans to send a
team of its international staff to Badakhshan province shortly to
monitor relief activities in the northern Afghan province, a U.N.
spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The team will stay in Faizabad, the provincial capital, and
will hold discussions with local U.N. staff and non-governmental
organizations on the relief operation, said Stephanie Bunker at a
weekly press briefing at the U.N. Information Center here.
</P>
<P>
A number of teams of the U.N. international staff have visited
Kabul, Jalalabad and Kandahar as part of its drive to assess
relief operations in the war-devastated country.
</P>
<P>
Bunker hinted that the U.N. also intends to send international
staff to the central Afghan province of Bamiyan and northern city
of Mazar-e-Sharif shortly.
</P>
<P>
All U.N. international workers were pulled out of Afghanistan
in August last year following killings of three U.N. staff, two
local workers and an Italian military official.
</P>
<P>
The organization announced plans to gradually send humanitarian
workers back to Afghanistan in March this year after the dominant
Taliban militant had promised to provide protection to the U.N.
staff and its premises and investigate into the killings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
