<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hongkong Telecom to Develop Beyond Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong Telecom will diversify
its businesses and explore opportunities beyond Hong Kong to meet
tougher competition in the future, the company's chief executive
Linus Cheung said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Hongkong Telecom will have no future if we remain to be a
telephone company," Cheung said at a press conference to announce
the company's final results for the year ended March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom, Hong Kong's major full-service communications
provider, Friday reported a net profit of 11.50 billion HK dollars
(1.47 billion U.S. dollars), representing a 7.7 percent decrease
from that of the previous year (before exceptional items).
</P>
<P>
The company's future will also be dark if it is just a
telecommunications company, Cheung said. That's why Hongkong
Telecom aggressively adjusts itself to intensify development in
Internet and E-commerce and explore investment opportunities
beyond Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We are seizing the growth opportunities of the Internet and
investing in skills and capabilities to strengthen our position
and achieve a clear lead in Asia," Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
"We shall drive to capture growth from global Internet and data
through closer integration with Cable &AMP; Wireless on international
network sharing, traffic management and new service developments,"
Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
"This will ensure we get the benefit of global reach, scale and
early adoption of new technology -- all of which is essential to
enable Hongkong Telecom to remain competitive amongst global
players," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom will have no future if it restrains itself
within Hong Kong, Cheung said. He said that he is ambitious to
play the "World Cup", not just the "Hong Kong League".
</P>
<P>
Cheung said that Hong Kong Telecom has a cooperation with China
Telecom and China's accession to the World Trade Organization will
bring fresh opportunities to the company.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has its own advantage in investing in China's
mainland including good reputation, modern technology and good
cooperative relations, Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
The company said Friday that its turnover decreased by 7.5
percent to 32.41 billion HK dollars (4.15 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Also at the press conference, Hongkong Telecom chairman Brian
Smith said that 1998 has been a very difficult year for companies
operating in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The weak economic environment in Hong Kong throughout the year
has dampened demand for basic telecommunications services," Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, Hongkong Telecom has faced intense price
competition, particularly in international telephone and mobile
services," he said.
</P>
<P>
Smith said that the board of directors remains confident of the
company's underlying strength and its longer term prospects and
has recommended a final dividend of 46.6 cents per share, making a
total of 85.2 cents for this financial year.
</P>
<P>
The company's international telecommunication services revenues
declined 18 percent to 15.56 billion HK dollars (1.99 billion U.S.
dollars) due to the economic downturn here.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom signed an agreement with the government in
March 1998 to surrender its exclusive international license.
</P>
<P>
However, local telecommunication services revenues grew by 6
percent to 9.40 billion HK dollars (1.20 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The firm said its mobile services revenues were 3 percent lower
at 5.82 billion HK dollars (74.61 million U.S. dollars) as the
numbers of customers switching networks has increased.
</P>
<P>
The firm said revenues for its Internet and interactive
multimedia services increased 146 percent year-on-year to 626
million HK dollars (80.25 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
