<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates for Macao SAR Chief Unveil Platforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The two candidates for the office of
the first chief executive of the Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR) announced here Friday their platforms, both promising
to uphold the principle of "one country, two systems" after
Macao's return to China.
</P>
<P>
"The 'one country, two systems' principle provides a solid
foundation for Macao's future development," candidate Edmund Ho
Hau Wah said at the second plenary meeting of the Selection
Committee for the first government of the Macao SAR here Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
To implement the principle of "one country, two systems," it is
necessary to adhere firmly to the Macao Basis Law, which provides
the constitutional basis for the establishment of the SAR, Ho told
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Any failure to adhere to the Macao Basic Law will seriously
affect Macao's future ... The practice of 'one country, two
systems' will have a profound and far-reaching effect on China, as
well as on Macao," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Ho said that, if elected, he would carefully study the problems
in Macao and formulate short-, mid- and long-term plans to address
them.
</P>
<P>
He said he would take measures to restore law and order in
Macao, noting that Macao has been affected by recurring crimes in
recent years and he is determined to fight crime and address the
issue of law and order thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
On the economic side, Ho said efforts should be made to boost
the major industries in Macao -- tourism and gambling, export and
processing trade, finance and real estate.
</P>
<P>
He also unveiled his plan to promote efficiency and fairness in
public administration, fight corruption to build a clean
government, enhance education and youth affairs, improve social
welfare and strengthen ethnic harmony, among other things.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Au Chong Kit, the other candidate, said at the same
meeting that the development of Macao in the future will depend on
the sense of mission of local residents under the prerequisite of
"one country, two systems," "Macao people governing Macao" and a
high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
It also hinges on the rule of law and a clean government, among
other things, Au said.
</P>
<P>
"In all the work I have participated to serve the Macao people,
I have never considered my personal glories and disgraces, gains
and losses. Instead, I have been concerned about the earnest
implementation of 'one country, two systems' and 'Macao people
governing Macao'," he told the Selection Committee members.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that the current social system and
life style in Macao will remain unchanged after its return to the
motherland on December 20 this year and this is a common
aspiration of the Macao people, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that, if elected, he would make efforts to reform the
gambling sector and raise the per capita income of the Macao
people through developing tourism, gambling, entertainment,
finance and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Au also voiced his concern about the public order in Macao and
stated his determination to combat underground gangs which vie for
interests from gambling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
