<HEADLINE> Scrutineers to Be Decided for Macao SAR Selection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- One chief scrutineer and three
scrutineers will be chosen for the day of selecting the candidate
of the first chief executive of the Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR), a Chinese official in charge of Macao affairs said
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ziying, secretary-general of the Preparatory Committee for
the Macao SAR, declared a decision on choosing the scrutineers at
the second plenary meeting of the Selection Committee for the
first government of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting participated by the vice-
chairmen of the Preparatory Committee just on the eve of the
Selection Committee plenum.
</P>
<P>
The Selection Committee consists of 199 members who are all
permanent residents of Macao. The committee convened its first
plenary meeting on April 23 and nominated two candidates for the
first chief executive. The chief executive selection will be held
on May 15 at the committee's third plenary meeting.
</P>
<P>
Selection Committee members come from four social quarters.
They are the industrial, commercial and financial sectors;
cultural and educational sectors and other professions; labor,
social services, religious and other sectors; and members of the
Legislative Council, the municipal organs, Macao deputies to the
National People's Congress and Macao members of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference.
</P>
<P>
One social quarter should produce a scrutineer and a chief
scrutineer will be chosen among the four scrutineers, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The four scrutineers shall be decided at the end of the second
plenary meeting of the Selection Committee on Saturday afternoon
and the name list will be submitted to a meeting of chairman and
vice-chairmen of the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
The names of chief scrutineer and three scrutineers will be
announced on May 15 at the third plenary meeting of the Selection
Committee before the chief executive selection begins, Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
