<HEADLINE> Rwandan Ruling Party Appoints Genocide Suspect as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Rwandan Patriotic Front
(RPF) has appointed a new law-maker who is suspected to have been
involved in the 1994 genocide in his home prefecture of Cyangugu
in southwest Rwanda, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Elisee Bisengimana, 33, was designated last week by
Secretary-General of the ruling party Charles Murigande, as one of
the new candidates to replace its four law-makers who resigned.
</P>
<P>
Since February 1999, the Rwandan transitional assembly is
rocked by purges engineered by the forum of seven political
parties sharing power in the government.
</P>
<P>
Up to 16 parliamentarians have either resigned, or been
expelled from the assembly because of absenteeism, incompetence,
misconduct, genocide charges, or collaboration with Hutu
extremists.
</P>
<P>
Bisengimana is said to have been a ring-leader in the massacres
of Tutsis, judicial sources in Cyangugu said.
</P>
<P>
Genocide survivors in Cyangugu contacted by the RNA alleged
that Bisengimana was seen at a refugee camp at Gihundwe, drawing
the list of Tutsi males who were then rounded up and killed at a
local soccer stadium.
</P>
<P>
"We have not heard of such allegations," Tito Rutaremara, head
of RPF parliamentary group, said. "If you have enough evidence,
put it out before he swears in and benefits from immunity."
</P>
<P>
This nomination has provoked a wave of reaction from other
political parties who said that the RPF choice was betraying its
record of being a party which fought genocide and promised to rout
out impunity in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Many have expressed concern about how these appoitments to
senior government posts or in parliament are made. In some cases,
well-known genocide suspects who have been denounced by human
rights organizations occupy key positions in the civil
administration or in the military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
