<HEADLINE> Arab Anti-Terrorism Pact Goes into Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- An anti-terrorism pact signed by Arab
countries took effect on Friday, 30 days after seven of the
signatories have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
"The enforcement of the pact marks a key accomplishment of the
Arab states in facing up to terrorism," Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said in a statement issued in the day
for the event.
</P>
<P>
The pact can "thereby protect people's lives and safeguard
their property," Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
The landmark agreement, which was signed by Arab ministers of
justice and interior in April 1998, seeks cooperation among the
Arab countries in combating terrorism, including extradition of
terrorist suspects, exchange of information and denial of shelter
and support to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Algeria, Bahrain, Egypt, Jordan, the Palestinian National
Authority, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates have approved
the pact, forming a quorum for the agreement to go into effect.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement ushers the Arab world into effective
cooperation in forging coordination leading to security and
stability across the Arab region," said a statement issued by the
Cairo-based Information Office of the Arab Interior Ministers.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that the pact repudiates violence and
its provisions in line with the principles of Islam,
international laws and the United Nations Charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
