<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Not to Totally Free Diamond Trade: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian government would
not allow a free-for-all trade in diamonds as has been proposed by
a parliamentary committee, South Africa's The Star newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The business report quoted Namibian Mines and Energy Minister
Jesaya Nyamu as saying Thursday that the suggestion that Namibia
decriminalize dealing in diamonds was "far-fetched and
unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
"We will not jeopardize our diamond industry or those of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
We value the industry and will not accept proposals by those
who are misinformed and ignorant of it," the minister was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said it was unfortunate that other diamond-producing
countries, notably Botswana and South Africa, had taken as fact
the recommendations made by the parliamentary committee.
</P>
<P>
"That the committee made this proposal does not mean we will
accept it. We don't want to promote chaos in the industry," Nyamu
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking to improve upon those archaic parts of the
existing legislation. That does not mean we are against anybody
or the Central Selling Organization (CSO of De Beers, the South
African diamond giant)."
</P>
<P>
Reports that Namibia would end the monopoly of the CSO for
diamond sales and allow free possession of cut or uncut stones
sparked concern from Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Botswana President Festus Mogae told a news conference in
Gaborone Tuesday that in that case, diamonds bought or stolen from
Botswana could be openly traded in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Namibian parliamentary committee of natural
resources, submitted to the National Assembly for consideration,
recommended the trade be deregulated and decriminalized through
the new Diamond Bill, now before parliament.
</P>
<P>
The committee argued that Namibian people were entitled to
benefit from the natural resources of the country.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's diamond trade is still regulated by the South African
Diamond Proclamation of 1939 which makes unauthorized diamond
buying a crime against the state. The new Diamond Bill has been
before the Namibian National Assembly since November last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
