<HEADLINE> Australia's Overseas Passenger Numbers Reach 14.2 million in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of passengers on
international flights into and out of Australia increased by one
percent between 1997 and 1998 to a record 14.205 million, the
latest aviation statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian federal Transport Department monthly figures
said the 1998 tally was also six percent higher than for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Major sources of traffic growth in December were Singapore,
Denpasar, Dubai, Auckland and London.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand contributed 19.1 percent of overseas airline
passengers in 1998, up from 18.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Singapore recorded growth rates of 13.7 and 13.6
percent respectively, while passenger numbers from Indonesia fell
9.1 percent and Japan 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Australia's flag carrier Qantas Airways carried 36.5
percent of all passengers to and from Australia, followed by Air
New Zealand, Singapore Airlines, British Airways and Malaysia
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Auckland-Sydney was the busiest route for the year, followed by
Los Angeles-Sydney, Singapore-Sydney, Hong Kong-Sydney and
Singapore-Perth.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Airport continues to be Australia's main international
gateway, with 49.7 percent of passengers passing through.
</P>
<P>
Melbourne handled 17.7 percent and Australia's third largest
city Brisbane 15.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
