<HEADLINE> UK Voters Reject Separatism, Blair Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Friday that Labor's victory in regional elections showed
voters' rejection of the break-up of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"I believe and I hope that out of these elections the union of
the United Kingdom will have been strengthened, rather than
weakened," Blair told reporters in London.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Labour Party looks set to be the largest party
after historic assembly elections in Scotland and Wales -- but
possibly without overall majorities in both places.
</P>
<P>
Blair noted that in Wales the nationalist party, Plaid Cymru,
had rejected separatism at the start of the campaign, while the
pro-independence Scottish National Party "has not done nearly as
well as they expected" in the voting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"What has happened is that as the debate has gone on, people
have rejected separatism," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said his Labour Party was likely to
form a coalition government with the Liberal Democrats in Scotland,
which was the third largest party next to Labour and the pro-
independence Scottish National Party.
</P>
<P>
Results showed Labour set to claim 57 seats in the 129-member
parliament versus a less-than-expected 37 seats for the Scottish
National Party, still several seats less than a required overall
majority to form a government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
