<HEADLINE> Four Blast Victims Seriously Injured: Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Among the victims of the bomb blast
that occurred here at 6:10 a.m. Friday morning, four people were
seriously injured and one was still in critical condition, a
hospital source told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Kikampikaho Gedion, deputy director of Mulago hospital, the
biggest in Uganda, said the hospital admitted eight people injured
in the blast at the Natete market.
</P>
<P>
"They are still in the casualty department receiving treatment.
The conditions of the remaining are stable," he said.
</P>
<P>
John Kimera, deputy spokesman of Ugandan police, told Xinhua at
11:30 a. m. that the bomb, which seems a grenade, was put in a
plastic bag and was abandoned between two pickups near the main
entrance to the market.
</P>
<P>
Among the injured are five men and five women. Police could
not establish the motive of the blast yet, he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the reasons for the recent spate of bomb
blasts in the capital city, most of them in the downtown area, the
spokesman said the terrorists just wanted to send waves of panic
among the public.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth bomb blast so far in the Ugandan capital this
year. Four of them occurred in or around market places. 
</P>
