<HEADLINE> More Imported Goods to Be Stamped in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government decided to
have five more kinds of imported goods to be stamped for
circulation in its domestic market from May 17 in efforts to fight
smuggling, protect domestic production and increase State budget
revenue.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam News Agency reported Friday that the goods are gas
cookers, electric rice-cookers, bicycle frames, thermos flasks and
explosion motors of working machines, according to a circular
jointly issued by Vietnam's General Department of Customs and the
Ministries of Finance, Trade and Public Security.
</P>
<P>
As of June 1, these imports, whether stored in warehouses,
displayed for sale in shops or delivered, will be regarded as
smuggled goods if they do not display the proper import duty
stamps.
</P>
<P>
Other imported goods required to be stamped include bicycles,
electric fans and pumps, alcohol, completely-assembled TV sets,
videocassette recorders, air-conditioners, refrigerators, engines,
ceramic bath installments and floor tiles.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam first introduced the stamping of imported goods on
December 1, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
