<HEADLINE> Kenya to Set Up Industrial Research Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has decided to
 establish a national industrial research fund to support joint
research efforts to achieve national objectives of
industrialization by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of Research and Technology Ministry, Sammy
Mbova said here Thursday that his government would increase its
funding for industrial research sector to 20 percent of total
research allocation.
</P>
<P>
The overall goal of the fund would be to strengthen the
national industrial productivity, create jobs and reduce poverty,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Kenya spends less than 0.5 percent of gross domestic
product (GDP) on research, and out of this, less than five percent
is spent on industrial research and development.
</P>
<P>
Local media Friday quoted Mbova as saying that the government
would speed up the initiative with policies to drive the country
to a newly industrialized status in light of declining funding
for research activities from the treasury.
</P>
<P>
Mbova encouraged the involvement of more private sector
participation in the country's industrial research and development
by creating partnership, contracting and consultancy.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Kenya Industrial Research and Development
Institute, Harry Kaane said that his institute would draw from the
fund to finance the five priority areas under the national
industrial research program.
</P>
<P>
The program include food security, job creation in micro and
small enterprises, promotion of cleaner environment, improvement
of habitation for urban low income workers and promotion of
industrial and technological information exchanges, Kaane added.
</P>
</TEXT>
