<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Launch Polio Eradication Drive in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is set to
launch a three-day massive anti-polio immunization campaign in
Afghanistan from May 9, U.N. officials said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the auspices of the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), the
World Health Organization (WHO) and the Taliban authorities of
public health, this campaign will involve more than 19,000
volunteers, health workers and social mobilizers, they said.
</P>
<P>
All 4.3 million Afghan children under five years of age are
targeted in two rounds for this year's polio vaccination campaign.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 3.6 million children between one year and
five years old are expected to benefit from vitamin A
supplementation during the second round scheduled for June 13-15.
</P>
<P>
Louis Georges Arsenault, UNICEF representative in Afghanistan,
told journalists here in a weekly press briefing that the two
warring Afghan sides have given verbal assurances to the UNICEF
that they will observe cease-fire during the vaccination campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said a surveillance system was established in Afghanistan in
September 1997, which continues to function despite the ongoing
conflict and complex situation there.
</P>
<P>
So far, 85 cases of confirmed polio have been detected, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mass immunization campaigns have been conducted in Afghanistan
since 1994. Every year, the United Nations has negotiated days of
tranquillity with all sides in the conflict so that more children
could be reached with the oral polio vaccine.
</P>
<P>
The campaigns are part of the ongoing global commitment to
eradicate polio by the end of the year 2000. Provisions are being
made for an intensified effort in 1999 and 2000 with another set
of immunization campaign later this year and two sets scheduled
for May/June and October/November in 2000 to attain polio
eradication in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
