<HEADLINE> U.N. Seeks to Check AIDS Spread in Tanzanian Teens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has launched a program to check the alarmingly high
spread of HIV/ AIDS in Tanzanian school-age children.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Senior Program Officer Kate Fleming said at a meeting
here Thursday that the move started this week in several regions
will help young people to change their attitudes toward the deadly
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the program is that between 2.5 and 3 million
school-age children are not in primary schools throughout
Tanzania, denying them access to information on the prevention
against HIV infection, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania has no specific institution taking care of such
children and their parents are too at a loss with regard to
communication with their children on the HIV/AIDS issue," local
media Friday quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
Richard Mabala,a program consultant, added that many Tanzanian
young people nursed a mistaken conception that HIV/AIDS is a town
disease.
</P>
<P>
He said that the program would restore confidence in the young,
 especially girls, on how to resist forced sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
"A research in Musoma region indicates that 25 percent of the
young girls admitted having been forced or raped in their first
sexual intercourse,"he added.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF program will involve leaders at all levels,
religious institutions and non-governmental organizations and will
organize workshops and seminars to intensify communication and
social mobilization.
</P>
<P>
It will also establish youth centers for medical and counseling
services to promote sustainable change in sexual behavior and
attitude especially among sexually active girls and boys.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a UNICEF report said Thursday that there are over
150,000 children in Tanzania at present who have been rendered
orphans because of the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The report said that families often break contact with AIDS
patients, resulting in a situation that after the death of the
last patient, the orphans usually fail to attend primary schools
and go into prostitution or criminal activities as a result.
</P>
</TEXT>
