<HEADLINE> China Visit Has Been "Fruitful": Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua)-- Visiting South African President
Nelson Mandela said here today that his current China tour has
turned out to be "fruitful."
</P>
<P>
The 81 year old, energetic president made this remark at a
press conference prior to his conclusion of a three day state
visit as guest of his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin. He left
Beijing earlier today at the end of his visit.
</P>
<P>
During the stay, Mandela met with President Jiang, Premier Zhu
Rongji and Chairman of Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
China is the last leg of his four nation tour which has also
taken in Russia, Hungary and Pakistan. Prior to this, he had
already toured many other countries. The soon to retire president
said that with these good-bye visits he was saying thanks to those
countries that had supported South Africa when the country was
almost all alone.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy to have chosen to end my political career by
visiting China," said Mandela, who will step down in early June.
</P>
<P>
The president voiced satisfaction over the development of
bilateral ties since the establishment of diplomatic relations
early last year.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision to sever relations with Taiwan and establish
diplomatic relations with China was and still is correct, and I
have no doubt that future development will show that we took a
correct decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the commercial relations between China and
South Africa have expanded very rapidly within the last eighteen
months to the satisfaction of both countries.
</P>
<P>
"Although no economic agreement was signed this time, there
have been successful meetings between the two foreign ministers on
issues that may deepen bilateral relations between the two
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president, who had been in prison for decades in his
struggle against apartheid and racial discrimination, expounded
his concept of democracy. "There are various interpretations of
what democracy is about," he said, stressing that it should be
based on the experience and conditions of different countries. "
Democracy for us means that we should be able to address economic
and social problems," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
