<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar tightened its
grip above 67 U.S. cents Friday, spiking briefly to a 14-month
high as euphoria over the Australian currency continued, before
settling to be little changed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 67.16 U.S. cents from 67.24
U.S. cents in Sydney Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the session it reached a peak of 67.43 U.S. cents, a
level not seen since March 1998. It marked a low during the day of
66.91 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
In its semi-annual statement the Australian central bank said
Thursday that it no longer expected a significant downturn in
growth in the second half of 1999, but underlying inflation was
still forecast to reach 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank did not comment directly on the future direction of
monetary policy, but the statement was interpreted as strongly
hinting that interest rates are on hold.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that this, combined with continuing positive
sentiment surrounding commodity prices, was supporting the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the Australian dollar was also buying 0.6226 euro
from 0.6257 euro Thursday and 80.51 Japanese yen from 81.07
Japanese yen while the euro was trading at 1.0788 U.S. dollars
from 1.0747 U.S. dollars. 
