<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural, Urban Consumption Gap Narrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The disparity of rising sales in
rural and urban China is narrowing, though the consumption level
in rural areas is still 10 years behind that in cities.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report issued by the State Administration
of Internal Trade, the income of rural residents grew 5.6 percent,
9 percent, 4.6 percent and 4.3 percent from 1995 to 1998, but
their consumption levels were 6.2, 2.3, 1.7 and 0.7 percentage
points lower than those of urban residents, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the consumption trend mainly to improved
living conditions in the countryside, including the development of
highways, power supplies, and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
If the income of rural residents can be raised steadily, there
will emerge a booming rural market, especially for durable
commodities, the reports says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
