<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower on Banks Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A major sell-off in the banking
sector dragged the rest of the Australian sharemarket sharply
lower Friday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index shed 50.9 points, or 1.7
percent, to close at 2,987.7, after lifting off an intraday low of
2,971.1.
</P>
<P>
The major culprit for the fall was the rapidly devalued banking
sector, hit hard by the belief that a cut in interest rates was
out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
The Banking Index tumbled 319.8 points, or 4.6 percent, to
6,611.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed recording a hefty fall of
113.8 points at 5,178.5 while the All Resources Index again showed
its strength with an 8.5-point rise to 1,267.2.
</P>
<P>
Market turnover was heavy with 744.99 million stocks changing
hands worth 1.019 billion U.S. dollars with 803 stocks falling,
741 rising and 461 remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
Among the pressured banks, National Australia Bank (NAB)
recorded the biggest fall, diving 1.71 Australian dollars to 25.79
Australian dollars, as analysts re-rated the stock following
Thursday's profit results. Turnover was 8.7 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Rounding out the biggest four banks in Australia, Commonwealth
Bank of Australia forfeited 65.9 cents to 24.89 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank dropped 53 cents to 11 Australian dollars and
Westpac bank shed 54 cents to 10.1 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
One of the few bright spots in the market Friday was the gold
sector. Miners dealing with the precious metal watched their share
prices soar Friday with the sub-index picking up 91.7 points to
1,173.5.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion in Sydney was trading at 288.8 U.S. dollars an
ounce at the close, up from 287.05 U.S. dollars at the close
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector generally, diversified miner BHP picked
up some of the positive sentiment, adding 9.2 cents to 17.792
Australian dollars, and global miner Rio Tinto tumbled 24.2 cents
to 24.85 Australian dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
