<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Companies in China Support China's WTO Ambitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- European companies in China have
stated their support for the country's ambitions to join the World
Trade Organization (WTO), saying the WTO should leave a
comparatively long transitional period for China's certain fragile
industries to adjust.
</P>
<P>
It is mutually beneficial, they said.
</P>
<P>
Michael Ricks, President of Ericsson (China) Company Ltd., told
Xinhua that China's entry into the WTO will benefit foreign
investors, who are now here or will come to China.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that this was because of more transparent
policies for investment, which will increase their confidence in
expanding investment.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson, which has set up more then ten enterprises in China,
including holding companies and research institutes, will double
its investment in the next few years, he pledged, adding that his
company will accelerate investment when China becomes a WTO member.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson hopes China and the European Union (EU) will reach an
agreement to allow China's accession within this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Frederic Cho, chief representative of
Skandinaviska Enskilda Bank, giving China the WTO membership will
benefit all parties, from a long-term perspective.
</P>
<P>
"It is reasonable to provide a long transitional period in
certain areas like banking, which will influence the reforms of
State-owned enterprises and the making of laws and policies," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted a Chinese saying, "haste makes waste" to warn those
foreign firms who hoped China to open comprehensively in a short
time to be cautious.
</P>
<P>
"Although my bank hopes China will allow foreign capital to
operate Renminbi business as soon as possible, and cancel the
regional limits for overseas banks, I insist that the opening of
China's financial sector should be step by step, and no acute
changes in the next few years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it will not benefit any side if China is left out of
the WTO in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Siemens, the world electrical giant, which has an investment in
China of above one billion deutsche marks, also demonstrated its
support.
</P>
<P>
Ernst Behrens, president of Siemens Ltd., China, said "Of
course Siemens supports China" in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He added that the WTO issue should not be affected by political
factors or human rights issues. This should be a principle in the
China-United States negotiations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
