<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Poised to Win Elections in Scotland, Wales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's ruling Labor Party looks
set to be the largest party after historic elections in Scotland
and Wales -- but possibly without overall majorities in both
places, according to unofficial results on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Results showed Labor set to claim 57 seats in the 129-member
Scottish parliament versus a less-than-expected 37 seats for the
pro-independence Scottish National Party (SNP).
</P>
<P>
And the Liberal Democrats look set to enter government for the
first time in decades as partners in a Scottish Lib-Lab coalition.
</P>
<P>
Donald Dewar, Scotland's Labor leader and likely head of the
new parliament, said things would never be the same again.
</P>
<P>
"Scottish politics will be forever changed. I am proud to be
part of a party that delivered Scotland its first parliament in
300 years," he said after winning his seat.
</P>
<P>
In Wales, where counting does not start until later on Friday,
a BBC exit poll forecast Labor would take between 28 and 32 seats
in the 60-seat assembly while the nationalist Plaid Cymru would
secure up to 17.
</P>
<P>
The likely results in Scotland and Wales vindicated Blair's
gamble of offering limited home rule to quell growing independence
movements.
</P>
<P>
The elections reshaped British politics by giving Scotland a
parliament for the first time since 1707 and Wales a less powerful
national assembly, its first ever.
</P>
<P>
But the SNP was also on course at least quadruple its tally by
being the single biggest victor in the battle for regional "top up
" seats, and looked set to form the official opposition against a
coalition administration.
</P>
<P>
SNP leader Alex Salmond said: "I think we've had the best
result in this party's history and whatever happens tonight I
think the SNP are moving forward and we're the only party that's
doing that."
</P>
<P>
Conservative leader William Hague was also bolstered by his
party's showing in the local government elections across most of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative won control of a number of key councils and
broke the 1,000-seat barrier -- enough for the Conservative leader
to claim he had led the faithful to the start of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
The downside for all parties was the low turnout. In the
locals, this was around 29 percent and in parts of Wales it
climbed only slightly higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
