<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants Aid Three Projects in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) provided
more than 50 million euros for three important projects in
Cambodia to help thousands of rural Cambodians get clean water,
improve agricultural yields and obtain quality education for their
children.
</P>
<P>
A signing ceremony was held Thursday at the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and International Cooperation. Ambassador Michel
Caillouet, the EU delegation's top diplomat to Cambodia and
Foreign Minister Hor Nam Hong inked the three financing
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 39 million euros will go to a EU project aimed at
providing financial resources for works related to irrigation and
road improvements, village water supply schemes and agricultural
and animal health programs.
</P>
<P>
The second project, known as "Support Program for Basic
Education in Cambodia," will receive about 7 million euros over a
period of 16 months.
</P>
<P>
The project aimed at improving primary school education across
the country, training teachers in colleges and helping develop new
curricula adapted to the requirements of the labor market.
</P>
<P>
And the remainder of 4 million euros will be used for funding a
"Technical Coordination Office" project which is aimed at
coordinating, facilitating and monitoring the implementation of EU
programs in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
EU member states finalized the allocation at an April 14
meeting in Brussels, after reviewing the progress of the programs
since they were started in 1995, according to the Cambodia Daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
