<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM to Move Office to New Capital Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and the 850-strong staff of the Prime Minister's
Department will start moving to the new federal administrative
capital in Putrajaya near here next week.
</P>
<P>
Minister in the Prime Minister's Department Siti Zaharah
Sulaiman announced here Friday that the shift to Putrajaya,
starting May 15, will involve the offices of the prime minister,
ministers, deputy ministers, parliamentary secretaries and
departments under the Prime Minister's Department.
</P>
<P>
The shift is expected to take two weeks, she said, adding
Mahathir is scheduled to occupy the prime minister's official
residence in Putrajaya next month.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Department complex and the prime
minister's official residence were built under the first phase of
the project covering 1,527 hectares out of a total area of 4,581
hectares of Putrajaya, designed to be a smart garden township.
</P>
<P>
The new federal administrative capital, located 25 kilometers
south from Kuala Lumpur, which cost 22 billion ringgit (about
5.789 billion U.S. dollars) to build, is expected to be completed
in June 2002 and could support a population of 330,000, according
to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Putrajaya is part of the much-publicized Multimedia Super
Corridor, which is under construction, where Cyberjaya, the
world's first intelligent city, is also located. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
