<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Departments Discuss Banning Smoking in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The issue of whether prisoners
should be allowed to smoke in jail has been under discussion
between officials of the departments of Health and Correctional
Services, the Citizen newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The discussion started soon after the Tobacco Products Control
Act was signed by President Nelson Mandela last month.
</P>
<P>
The act imposes a blanket ban on smoking in public places and
the workplace, but then allows Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma to
regulate for exemptions.
</P>
<P>
No details of the discussion about banning smoking in prison
has been available.
</P>
<P>
For now, only two countries are known to have dealt
specifically with smoking in prisons in their tobacco control
legislation. One is Botswana, the other is New Zealand. The
former completely bans smoking in prison while the latter offers
an option of smoking cells or designated smoking areas.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the South African Health Department said that they
tend to follow the New Zealand model, recognizing that smoking is
an addiction. And there is a feeling that complete ban is too
punitive, the officials added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
