<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maize Shortage in Kenya Sends Prices Soaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- An acute shortage of maize over the
past two weeks has led to a flour price rise of between 17 percent
to 25 percent in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kariithi Murimi, Chairman of the Wheat Millers Association of
Kenya said Thursday that the millers had been adversely affected
by a 36 percent rise in the price of maize over last month.
</P>
<P>
The serious shortage of maize forced the millers to operate
below capacity, the Daily Nation newspaper Friday quoted Murimi as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the higher prices of the flour of maize and wheat
were partly caused by high transport fees from the Indian port
Mombasa to Kenyan capital Nairobi due to the poor roads. Most
imports enter the east African country through Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Murimi also attributed the price increase to a 11 percent drop
in the value of the Kenyan shilling to the U.S. dollar in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The sector was expected to continue importing wheat until July
when local wheat is available, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
