<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 08:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports of Egypt's Free Zones Rise This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's free zone exports in the first
four months this year rose 30.5 percent from the same period last
year, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The free zone exports stood at 154 million U.S. dollars so far
in 1999, 36 million dollars more than the same period in 1998,
Ibrahim Fawzi, chairman of the General Investment and Free Zone
Authority, said on Thursday at a symposium entitled "Investment
Opportunities in Egypt."
</P>
<P>
The symposium was part of the five-day Francexpo '99 opened
last Sunday by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri and his
French counterpart Lionel Jospin during his two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The free zone exports increased to 406 million dollars in 1998
from 302 million dollars in 1997, Fawzi said, citing the soar of
direct foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has set up six free zones in Cairo, Ismailia, Suez,
Alexandria, Port Said and Dumyat, where investors are offered
favorable conditions including tax exemption as long as 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi pledged that Egyptian laws will protect foreign
investments against nationalization and confiscation.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year ending on June 30, Egypt exported
5.33 billion dollars worth of goods while its imports stood at
16.55 billion dollars, with a deficit of 11.22 billion dollars.
Egypt is seeking ways of promoting exports in a bid to reduce
trade deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
