<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Credit Insurance Develops Rapidly in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China has seen a rapid growth of its
export credit insurance business in the last decade, accompanied
by a steady growth of its export.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Yifei, an official from the People's Insurance
Company of China (PICC), the company has signed more than 200,000
short-term insurance contracts and over 50 medium and long-term
contracts with a total insured amount of 14 billion U.S. dollars
since November 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under these contracts, PICC has paid 70 million dollars in
indemnities to insurees.
</P>
<P>
It has also provided an insurance cover of one billion dollars
for overseas investment in China and recovered 200 million dollars
owed to Chinese firms by overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
As a major international export credit insurer, the PICC helped
Chinese exporters get more than five billion dollars in foreign
currency lending by international banks to many major export
projects by Chinese manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
For example, it persuaded 14 Chinese and foreign banks to lend
530 million dollars to the Tehran subway project, one of the
largest machinery and electrical equipment export projects
undertaken by Chinese firms in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Export credit insurance is a popular means used by various
governments in the world to encourage the exports of its products
by providing its exporters with a guarantee against risks
resulting in the non-payment on the part of the importers.
</P>
<P>
In November 1989, the PICC started its export credit insurance
service, the first such services in China, with 60 million dollars
from the Ministry of Finance as the initial reserve against risks.
</P>
<P>
In October 1998, the PICC, as the representative of China's
export credit insurers, was formally acknowledged and admitted as
a member by the International Union of Credit and Investment
Insurers, more simply known as the Berne Union.
</P>
<P>
As an umbrella organization of international export credit
insurers, the Berne Union plays a major role in co-ordinating the
export credit and investment policies of various countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, members of the union provided a total guarantee of 44.
6 billion dollars for foreign investment in China, surpassing the
amount of actual foreign investment in the country in that year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that PICC's admission by the union will help
international investors to have a better understanding of China,
and hence encourage more investment in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Fifth of China's Urban Residents Use Coal as Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- A Ministry of Construction
official said today that one fifth of China's city-dwellers still
use coal as fuel.
</P>
<P>
As the pollutants and dust are directly discharged into air,
coal burning has become one of the major factors worsening China's
urban atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "In terms of air pollution, south China's
cities are better than those in the north, and the summer is
better than winter.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting the use of gas in the cities and encouraging central
heating systems has become a task of great urgency."
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration issued a
circular in 1996, calling on China's large and medium-sized cities
to formulate regulations prohibiting the use of raw coal as fuel.
To date, a total of 123 cities across China have drawn up special
regulations governing the issue.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 23.7 billion cubic meters of gas and
natural gas, as well as some eight million tons of liquefied
petroleum gas were supplied to Chinese citizens in 1998, a rise of
31.7 percent and 75.2 percent respectively on the 1995 figures.
</P>
<P>
Some 79 percent of China's city-dwellers now use gas as their
fuel, an increase of 10 percent more than the figure in 1995.
While in Beijing and Shanghai, the rate of urban residents using
gas has been maintained above 90 percent for years despite
continuous growth in the urban population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
