<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Eastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Eleven rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in operations launched by the
Turkish security forces in eastern Turkey, the Anatolia News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces Thursday wiped out 30 PKK rebels
after a large group of PKK militants ambushed the government
troops on duty in Yayladere town of Bingol province late Wednesday
night, in which nine soldiers were killed and another was wounded.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces have launched large-scale military
operations in search of the PKK guerrillas in country areas of
Yayladere and Kigi towns between the provinces of Bingol and
Tunceli.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cobra and Skorsky helicopters also raided the
shelterings of PKK militants in the region.
</P>
<P>
Fightings between the Turkish security forces and the PKK
guerrillas are continuing in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. The conflicts have claimed
over 37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was captured by Turkish special
agents in Kenya in mid-February and has been detained on Imrali
Island in Marmara Sea near Turkey's western province of Bursa for
trial on charges of treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
