<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Selection Committee for MSAR Government Holds Plenum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Selection Committee for the first
government of the future Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)
held its second plenary meeting here Friday to hear the two
candidates for the first chief executive talk about their
conceptions on governing Macao.
</P>
<P>
Through drawing lots, Edmund Ho Hau Wah was chosen to be the
first one and Stanley Au Chong Kit the second to give speeches
expounding their administrative policies should they be elected
the first chief executive of the Macao SAR, which will be set up
on December 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
Out of nine applicants, Ho and Au were given candidacy for the
first chief executive on April 23 at the first plenary meeting of
the Selection Committee. Ho won 125 nominating votes and Au 65.
</P>
<P>
Each candidate spent about one hour to explain their
administrative programs at the meeting on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
"As a Chinese born and brought up in Macao, I have always had
the reunification of our country at heart and have been looking
forward to the return of Macao to our motherland," Ho said at the
beginning of his speech.
</P>
<P>
"Should I be elected chief executive, I will shoulder the
responsibilities incumbent upon me and lead Macao confidently
through a smooth transition to permanent harmony, stability and
prosperity," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to stressing the importance of the "one country,
two systems" principle, his speech also covered law and order,
economic restructuring, public administration, fighting corruption
and striving for clean government, education, social welfare and
ethnic harmony.
</P>
<P>
Au's speech was entitled "My Choice." He explained his plans
to improve the economic and social conditions in Macao on the
basis of his all-round understanding about the region.
</P>
<P>
He listed the virtues of a qualified chief executive as clear
conscience, justice, honesty and unselfishness.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the chief executive is expected to be able to
establish a fine image for Macao in the world, listen carefully to
the wishes of the public, push forward reforms in Macao, lead
Macao out of economic depression and improve residents' living
standard, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of the plenary meeting on Saturday, Selection
Committee members will raise questions for the two candidates to
answer.
</P>
<P>
The Selection Committee will choose the first chief executive
on May 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
