<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Sherpa Stays 21 Hours on Top of Mt. Qomolangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Babu Chhiri Sherpa from Nepal has
set a record of staying for 21 hours at the summit of the 8,848-
meter Mount Qomolangma, the world's highest mountain, the Nepali
Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old mountaineer scaled the mountain at 9 on
Thursday morning. He set up a specially-made tent on the summit.
</P>
<P>
At 7:30 Friday morning he left the summit for the South Col (8,
000m.), and at 8:30, he was at the Hillary's Step (8,760m.), the
ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
He had already scaled Mount Qomolangma for eight times. He was
serving the 1999 International Everest Expedition of Sweden led by
Tina Olga, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
An officer from the ministry's mountaineering division said
that summiters stay on the top usually for a maximum of one hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
