<HEADLINE> Climbers From US, Finland Scale Two Mountains in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. climber Edmund Viesturs and
Finnish climber Eero Veikka Juhani Gustafsson have scaled the 8,
163-meter Mount Manaslu and the 8,167-meter Mount Dhaulagiri I in
Nepal, the Nepali Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
They climbed Mt. Manaslu, the world's eighth highest mountain,
on April 21 from the northeast ridge, and conquered Mt. Dhaulagiri
I, the seventh highest mountain in the world, on May 4 from the
northeast face, the ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Viesturs, 40, is a carpenter while 31-year-old Gustafsson is a
climber. They were members of the 11-strong Saxon Himalayan
Expedition Manaslu'99 led by Gotz Wjegang and the 7-member Swiss
Dhaulagiri Expedition led by Martin Fisher, the ministry said.
</P>
