<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Utilizing Sea Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Various technologies including
desalination of sea water and the direct use of sea water in
industry are encouraged in China to relieve the lack of water in
coastal cities and islands.
</P>
<P>
Experts warn that the per capita fresh water rate in China is
less than one quarter of the world average, and more than 300
cities are short of water. The situation is more serious in the
coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
Utilizing sea water is an important method of solving this
problem, said Gao Congjie, an academician at the Chinese Academy
of Engineering, adding that desalination technology has been well
developed in China for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
A desalination plant with a daily capacity of 500 tons was
constructed in east China's Zhejiang Province in 1997, and China's
largest desalination plant, which can produce 1,000 tons of fresh
water, was completed in northeastern Liaoning Province last year.
</P>
<P>
At present, China's various desalination facilities can produce
four million tons of fresh water every year, according to an
official of the State Oceanic Administration (SOA).
</P>
<P>
Sea water is also directly utilized in industry, and about 170
million cubic meters of sea water is used as a coolant at the
Tianjin Dagang Power Plant every year.
</P>
<P>
Gao Congjie said that China takes no more than 10 billion
cubic meters of water from sea every day, much less than many
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that technology for exploiting sea water should be
further developed, and systematic sea water desalination projects
should be designed.
</P>
<P>
According to the 21st Century Agenda for China's Oceans,
created by the SOA, China will launch several pilot projects using
sea water for irrigation, industry, and everyday use in several
coastal cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
