<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Growing Support for Israel's Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Just 10 days before Israel's
general elections, a public opinion poll showed that support for
the left-wing Labor Party leader Ehud Barak was growing.
</P>
<P>
The poll, published on the local daily The Jerusalem Post, was
conducted among a representative sample of 500 voters early this
week and had a margin of error of approximately 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll suggested that Barak would beat current Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in a second round of voting by 49 percent to
43.5 percent. Seven percent of those questioned were undecided.
</P>
<P>
Barak's edge over Netanyahu, leader of the right-wing Likud
Party, was up slightly over a similar poll taken in the previous
week, when Barak garnered 48 percent compared with Netanyahu, who
got 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, Barak also led the first round voting
with 41 percent, followed by Netanyahu with 38.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister election is slated for May 17. If none of
the candidates can get more than 50 percent of votes in the
first round, a second round will be held in early June.
</P>
<P>
The latest poll also showed that the Center Party Leader
Yitzhak Mordechai's fortunes continue to sour: last week's polls
showed he would gain 9 percent of votes in the first round, but
this week the figure declined to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the support for Mordechai dropped, the Labor has called on
the Center Party to joined forces with it in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts noted that the majority of those classified as
"undecided" in the poll voted for Netanyahu in 1996 elections; if
they, about 7 percent of the voters this year, do so again, the
difference between Barak and Netanyahu would shrink. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
