<HEADLINE> Afforestion Program for Protecting Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 4,000 youngsters from north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region were organized to plant
pine trees along both banks of the Yellow River at weekends, said
local sources.
</P>
<P>
The effort is just part of the autonomous region's many
activities calculated to protect rivers running through it,
including the Yellow River, Nenjiang River and Liaohe River, to
curb soil erosion and protect the eco-environment.
</P>
<P>
Starting from this year, Inner Mongolia will spend five years
in erecting ecological belts with a total area of 6,666 hectares
in the valleys of the three rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River is the second longest river in China after the
Yangtze River, and its basin is regarded as the birthplace of
Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Yellow River has been running dry for
longer and longer periods because of ecological deterioration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong Registers High Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Exports of the Pudong New Area, an
emerging financial and trade zone in Shanghai, reached 1.28
billion U.S. dollars for the first quarter of the year, up 37.3
percent from the 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
The exports were worth 28 million U.S. dollars more than
imports, the first report of a trade surplus since the Pudong New
Area was founded in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Local trade experts attributed the growth mainly to increases
in exports of overseas-funded enterprises and high-tech products.
</P>
<P>
According to the Shanghai Customs, 52 percent of the exports
were accomplished by the area's more than 2,000 overseas-funded
enterprises, compared with 50 percent last year and 15 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports of technology-intensive goods, such as computers and
machinery, made up 50 percent of the total, while those of labor
and resource intensive products kept on declining.
</P>
<P>
Experts also point to a diversified market that has helped
boost exports. To date, the area has enhanced its presence in more
than 130 foreign countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
