<HEADLINE> U.S. Surgeons Operate for Free on Chinese Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- American surgeons today finished a 12-
day long series of operations on 31 orphans with various
deformities such as harelips, in northeast China's Heilongjiang
province and also donated medical equipment worth 150,000 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 14 surgeons arrived in the city of Harbin on April 23 under
the banner of the Children of China Pediatrics Foundation, which
was founded in 1997, with the aim of offering free medical care to
Chinese orphans with deformities.
</P>
<P>
"The operations have been very successful thanks to the Chinese
colleagues' cooperation, and we feel greatly rewarded when we see
the smiling faces of these lovely kids after the orthopedics."
said Regina E. Shannahan, the founder and general manager of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
She said that the activity is to inspire more foreign people to
show their love for these special Chinese children, and try the
best to help them, together with the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for these particular medical experts to
visit China.
</P>
<P>
"I have long been enchanted by China's long history and culture.
I am really happy to have the chance to contribute to the health
of the Chinese people," said a 70-year-old professor of the School
of Pharmaceuticals of Columbia University in New York.
</P>
<P>
The foundation has also discussed with the Chinese Ministry of
Civil Affairs about the possibility of engaging in similar
activities in central China's Hunan Province and southwest China's
Guizhou Province later this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
