<HEADLINE> Official Calls For Enhanced Efforts In Solving Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Information Industry
(MII) is calling on major government departments and crucial
sectors to make enhanced efforts to solve the computer 2000
problem (Y2K) and ensure sufficient funding.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qi, director of the Information Products Administration
Office under the MII, said that 18 major government institutions
have made progress toward solving the Y2K problem, but the task is
still "tough and requires more efforts."
</P>
<P>
For ten days last month, the MII investigated the 18
departments and found that the banking and financial sector, and
Customs had completed their tests and revisions.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qi said it is wrong for some enterprises and institutions
to believe that solving Y2K is strictly the technicians'
responsibility, and she stressed that leaders at all levels should
take part in these efforts.
</P>
<P>
According to one legal expert, China still lacks effective laws
and regulations for the Y2K problem, and in many circumstances
need help from international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qi disclosed that the MII will organize officials from
ten departments in Beijing and Shanghai to visit the United States
in October where they will seek international cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
