<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls for Action on Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has
asked his cabinet ministers and permanent secretaries to fight
corruption in their respective ministries instead of merely
speaking about its existence.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his cabinet members at the State House here
Thursday, Moi said that the public would like to see action taken
against corrupt officials, especially those in the departments
notorious for graft such as road department.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Kenya Times newspaper Friday quoted the president
as saying it is ironic that permanent secretaries grumbled about
corruption as they are charged with the role of implementing
government policies.
</P>
<P>
The ministries are required to make sure the projects they
started be completed, and never start the new ones unless the
earlier ones were complete, Moi said.
</P>
<P>
The president also requested the ministries to ensure no
dumping of cheap imports, which jeopardize local industries and
job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Moi told his subordinates that plans are to be made to
privatize the Kenya Meat Commission so as to improve the meat
industry and benefit livestock keepers.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a budgetary provision for training of civil
servants so that they become better managers and implementers of
government policies.
</P>
<P>
But he added that public servants should resist foreign
policies and advice which impacted negatively on the image of the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
