<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Accession Part of China's Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The only way to develop Chinese enterprises into high quality
and strongly competitive ones is through competition in the global
market, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Certain Chinese industries, including telecommunications,
finance, insurance, and tourism sooner or later will be opened to
international competition. That's why they have to deepen
restructuring, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Temporary pains will be replaced by upgrading of the entire
economy, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
"A strong rival can often excite the latent ability of the weak,
" the article said.
</P>
<P>
China's color TV market was almost monopolized by Japanese
products in the early 80's, but now domestically produced color
TVs account for three fourths of the market share. All the
personal computers in the Chinese market were imported ten years
ago, but last year half of all computers sold in China among the
top-ten brands were made by domestic manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Chinese negotiators have been able to secure a
transitional period. China will cut its tariff gradually to a
level that Chinese industries can withstand, imports of certain
sensitive commodities will be limited until 2005, trade of
significant agricultural products still need quotas, and the
service trade will be opened step by step.
</P>
<P>
Domestic enterprises have long suffered from unfair competition.
However, WTO membership will provide an opportunity for the
Chinese economy to become a part of standard and fair
international competition, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Accession Part of China's Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China's sustained effort to join the
World Trade Organization (WTO) is a part of its reform and opening-
up drive, according to a signed article in Friday's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The gradual opening of China's service sector is a need of the
ongoing reform and opening-up, rather than a concession, the
article noted.
</P>
<P>
China's goal is to foster new economic growth points and boost
consumption, as well as to create positions of high- and middle-
income job opportunities, it said.
</P>
<P>
China's confidence in opening winder to the rest of the world
is due to the fact that none of the WTO members, most of which are
still developing countries, have experienced difficulties in the
course of opening their service sectors, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
There were some arguments before China opened the manufacturing
of TVs and refrigerators, but it took the right step, according to
the article.
</P>
<P>
After 13 years of negotiations, the Chinese people have learned
that service is the engine of the entire economy, as it is
intensive in knowledge, professionals and technologies. "No
advanced service, no developed economy," the article stressed.
</P>
<P>
WTO membership will not only give China equality of trade
opportunity, but will also spur its initiative to institute
international trade norms, it noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Accession Part of China's Reform (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the process of opening to the world, the first consideration
must be the security of the Chinese economy, and this economic
security does not conflict with opening-up, the article pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the former economy which was formed in isolation was
extremely fragile, it added.
</P>
<P>
Practice demonstrates that the biggest threat to economic
security is exactly a closed economy, which features clogged
access to information, low competitiveness, and backward
macroeconomic management, it noted, adding that economic security
will only be consolidated through a continuous opening process.
</P>
<P>
After 20 years of reform and opening-up, China's ability to
ward off risks had not been weakened, but rather strengthened, it
said.
</P>
<P>
When taking part in the WTO, which accounts for 95 percent of
all global trade and investment, the Chinese economy will
gradually be connected to the world economy, widen its opening,
and dispose all its resources rationally.
</P>
<P>
With WTO membership, more Chinese enterprises will participate
in the world economy, more overseas investment will flow into
China, and Chinese consumers will gain great benefits, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, developing countries should be highly aware of
economic security, given the history of world trade which includes
protectionism, unpredictable international floating capital,
mergers among multinational corporations, and the defects of the
international trading system, it said.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries should open their economies in accordance
with the level of their economic development, and aid its fledging
industries, it noted.
</P>
<P>
In the course of WTO negotiations, China insists that it should
remain in a controlling position in Sino-foreign cooperation, open
its market gradually, and keep the door of the capital market
closed.
</P>
<P>
The article said in conclusion that WTO membership should be
based on the benefits of economic development and social stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closure Lawsuit Filed Against Turkey's Pro-Islamic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vural Savas, prosecutor of the
Supreme Court of Appeal, announced Friday to file a lawsuit to the
Constitutional Court to ban the pro-Islamic Virtue Party (FP), the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Savas made the announcement mainly on account of FP deputy
Merve Kavakci's attempt to take oath at the ceremony session of
the parliament on May 2 wearing a headscarf.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, FP deputy chairman Aydin Menderes resigned from
his party post in protest against the inability of FP leader
Recai Kutan in solving the "headscarf controversy."
</P>
<P>
Kavakci triggered the dispute among political parties as she
entered the parliament hall wearing the headscarf according to
Islamic custom, causing chaos in the parliament and protest by
parties.
</P>
<P>
Women are not allowed to wear headscarf in state and public
institutions under the law in the mostly-Muslim but strictly
secular country.
</P>
<P>
Menderes reportedly opposed Kavakci's move in parliament, but
he called on both his party and the opponents to settle the
controversy within the norms of law.
</P>
<P>
Menderes' resignation is seen as a big blow to the FP and some
other FP deputies loyal to Menderes are also expected to resign
from the party.
</P>
<P>
The FP, which became the third largest party after the recent
elections and holds 111 seats in parliament, stems from the
Islamic Welfare Party which was outlawed in January, 1998 for its
ultra-Islamic policies.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel also criticized Kavakci for
wearing headscarf when attending the new parliament oath-taking
ceremony, saying such a move provoked Turkish people.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister-designate Bulent Ecevit said that "everyone in
Turkey has the right to wear whatever she would like in their
private lives. But, the general assembly of parliament is not
within the bounds of anyone's private life."
</P>
<P>
"In state life, the rules and regulations of the state should
be obeyed. Parliament is not the place to challenge the state," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
