<HEADLINE> COMESA Strives for Free Trade Area by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has been urged to double its efforts in
ensuring that all programs are on course if it has to achieve a
free trade area by October 2000.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Minister of Communications and Transport David Saviye
said all key programs on regional integration should be fully
implemented so that the regional grouping could achieve a free
trade area next year.
</P>
<P>
Saviye was speaking at the opening of the second consultative
meeting on Advance Cargo Information System (ACIS) in Lusaka
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said programs like ACIS should be fully implemented because
it would provide service providers and users with online
information to enable them to conduct their businesses in a more
efficient and cost effective manner.
</P>
<P>
Saviye also called for the full participation of all
transporters in the ACIS program so as to promote efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same meeting, COMESA Secretary General Erastus
Mwencha said the ACIS program has had positive impact on railway
transport where it had been implemented.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to train users of ACIS so that the
program could be sustainable.
</P>
<P>
ACIS can only be an effective management tool if all parties
fulfill their obligations toward ensuring that each transport
operator, each user and each country will have access to
information they need, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
