<HEADLINE> Status of Dollar Unlikely to Change in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Despite the prospect that the euro
will assume an important role in world economy, the status of the
U.S. dollar is unlikely to change in Gulf countries in the near
term, the Gulf News daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The euro is still unfamiliar to the Gulf countries for them to
make any strategic decision regarding its use as an alternative to
the dollar, the paper said, quoting Gulf bankers.
</P>
<P>
Most Gulf currencies are pegged to the dollar, the reserves of
the Gulf countries are in dollars, and this is likely to continue
for some time, said Ibrahim Dabdoub, chief of the National Bank of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
However, the euro, which is adopted by 11 European countries,
is important for Gulf countries in the long run in oil pricing and
in maintaining exchange rate stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
This was echoed by Al Dukheil, chairman of the Saudi-based
Consulting Center for Finance and Investment.
</P>
<P>
Dukheil suggested that the authorities of Gulf Cooperation
Council countries, which include Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman,
Qatar, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates, should consider
introducing a dual system of pricing for oil.
</P>
<P>
With such a system, the Gulf oil exporters can use the euro in
transactions with European countries and the dollar when doing
business with another countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
