<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People Found HIV Positive in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Health (DH) here
in Hong Kong announced Friday that 46 people were found HIV
positive in the first quarter of 1999, bringing the cumulative
total number of reported HIV infections to 1,192.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen new AIDS cases were reported in the same quarter,
bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 390.
</P>
<P>
Of the 46 HIV infections reported, 32 were male and 14 female.
twenty-eight acquired the infection via heterosexual contact and
nine via homosexual or bisexual contact. One mother-to-child
infection was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
The transmission routes for the remaining eight were
undetermined, a DH spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 1,192 reported HIV infections, 664 contracted the
virus through heterosexual contact and 317 through homosexual or
bisexual contact. 17 were injecting drug users, seven got the
virus by mother-to-child transmission and 67 were infected by
contaminated blood or blood products.
</P>
<P>
As for the remaining 120, the information available was
inadequate for classification, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
DH monitors the HIV/AIDS situation through a voluntary
reporting system and seroprevalence studies. Reports are released
on a quarterly basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
