<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Aged People Play Active Role in Society (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China is now to embrace a "silver hair" era. Demographers
estimate that there will be 130 million 60-year olds or above in
China by 2000 and by the middle of next century the number will
reach 400 million.
</P>
<P>
The government and research organizations have paid close
attention to the growth of the ageing population and its influence
on the economy, employment and social insurance.
</P>
<P>
Yu noted that China has now set its working goal for elderly
citizens which is providing medicare, the opportunity for study,
leisure time and their working chances.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is now launching activities to encourage old
people to carry out jobs within their abilities, participate in
social development, and continue to realize their life value, all
of which will help the old population to live more actively.
</P>
<P>
Yu said: "More senior citizens are now willing to do social
work after their retirement. They are even irreplaceable in some
fields."
</P>
<P>
A survey by the China Elderly People's Research Center showed
that China's senior citizens are now extending their working scope
to include technology consultation, education and community
services.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that over 20 percent of the retired people in
China have gone taken up new working positions. Over one million
senior citizens are helping to educate the next generation and
nearly two million retired teachers are now still continuing their
careers.
</P>
<P>
Si Xia was 85 years old when she retired from the attached
primary school to Nanjing Normal University, and was possibly the
oldest on-the-post teacher in China at that time.
</P>
<P>
She is now nearly 90 years old, and still reading newspapers
every day and paying close attention to the development of
children.
</P>
<P>
"There does exist some prejudices toward old people. But most
important of all, we aged people should make contributions to
society for as long as we can," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adequate Funding for Y2K Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- An information industry official
today called for ensuring the adequate allocation of funds for
tackling the millennium computer bug.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a national seminar, Zhang Qi, director of the
Information Products Administration of the Ministry of Information
Industry, said the key sectors of China's national economy and
industries vital to people's livelihood cannot afford to overlook
the Y2K problem, despite the fact that computer applications in
China are not as prevalent as in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Estimates on the Y2K problem have set the global costs at 600
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far, the People's Bank of China, the country's central bank,
has invested 5 billion yuan on tackling the millennium bug, and
more funds are expected to be added.
</P>
<P>
The Construction Bank of China has used 600 million yuan on
working out the contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
The General Administration of Customs has invested 2 billion
yuan on software upgrading.
</P>
<P>
These institutions are among the government departments and
industries which have completed their computer system revision and
testing.
</P>
<P>
However, shortages of funds are holding back many institutions
and businesses in their attempts to tackle the Y2K problem. "This
is a key issue," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
She pointed to the fact the Northeast Earthquake Monitoring
Network is unable to meet its budget by 2 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A series of policies in favor of the Y2K efforts are needed to
ease the funding shortages, Zhang said, suggesting discount loans
aimed at the computer bug projects, and tariff exemptions on
imported equipment as a result of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she pointed out, computer and electronics companies
should not treat this problem as a business opportunity. She
warned about the short-sightedness of those companies that have
set a "sky-high price" for their services in solving the
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
"They should charge very little or not at all for the sake of
the interests of the broader pictures and their own reputations,"
she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
