<HEADLINE> Palestinians' Destiny in Their Own Hands: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian people have the
absolute right to set up an independent state on their own land,
Palestinian consul-general in Dubai Saleem Abu Sultan has said.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people alone will determine the appropriate
time for such a declaration," the envoy was quoted on Friday by
Khaleej Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to delay the declaration of a Palestinian state
was not the result of external pressures," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The decision came following exhaustive studies and
consultations between President Yasser Arafat and world and Arab
leaders and the Palestinian Legislative Council," he added.
</P>
<P>
On April 29, the Palestine Liberation Organization Central
Council decided to postpone making a final decision on the
declaration of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
He said that no deadline has been set for the declaration of an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"It could be in a month's time, two months time or in a year's
time. It has not been decided yet," he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the current unrest and street protests by the
Palestinians in Gaza and the West Bank disappointed at the passage
of the May 4 deadline without a statehood declaration, he said
"frustration is a natural reaction."
</P>
<P>
The envoy stressed, however, that "while the Palestinian
people and various political factions have a right to protest
within democratically accepted parameters, they do not have the
right to ignore the PNA (Palestinian National Authority)
leadership and threaten the security of the state." 
</P>
</TEXT>
