<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in New Zealand drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's unemployment has
dropped sharply and is expected to continue to fall as its economy
builds up steam.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Statistics New Zealand said Friday that the
unemployment rate for the first quarter of this year declined to
7.2 percent from 7.7 percent in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The number of people officially out of work fell to 135,000 in
March this year from 143,000 in December last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Statistics NZ, 1,741,000 people were estimated to
be employed in the first quarter of this year. Of these, 950,000
were men and 791,000 were women. The number of people in
employment has increased by 15,000 from the fourth quarter of last
year and by 9,000 from a year ago. The increase over the year has
come solely from an increase in female employment of 14,000 while
male employment declined by 5,000 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey shows that unemployment in the Wellington
region fell to 6.5 percent from 6.9 percent, but that in the
Auckland region rose from 6.5 percent to 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local economists hold that the drop in unemployment in New
Zealand was far bigger than expectations and reflected a wider
economic recovery. They are of the view that the labor market in
the country is responding quite rapidly to the general recovery in
the economy, and it likely to continue to improve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
