<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Many Large U.S. Companies Lag Behind Y2K Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Many large companies in the
United States are not spending enough to complete their year 2000
computer(Y2K) compliance, according to a study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study conducted by research firm Triaxsys examined the
spending of the companies through the end of last year on Y2K
technology, as disclosed in their quarterly financial reports
submitted to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC).
</P>
<P>
Although many companies have made major progress in their Y2K
efforts, Triaxsys said, "there are a significant number of
companies that have a tremendous amount of work to do and they
might not make it."
</P>
<P>
Of the 647 Fortune 1000 companies examined, 231 companies may
achieve Y2K compliance, but 241 companies have made only 41
percent to 60 percent progress, and 175 companies are at or below
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the companies showing the least progress, as measured by
percentage of total budget spent, are the computer networking
giant 3Com which spent just 7 percent of its budget, and
TeleCommnications Corporation, with just 10 percent spent.
</P>
<P>
According to the research firm, the average Fortune 1000
company is about 56 percent done with Y2K work. The SEC filling
also indicated that the companies' estimates of the total cost of
the Y2K problem continue to rise. Total estimated spending by
companies is now projected to be at least 53 billion U.S. dollars,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "conventional wisdom" lately is that all large U.
S. companies have the Y2K problem under control. "That kind of
generalization is not only inaccurate but overly complacent,"
Triaxsys said.
</P>
<P>
The research firm expects to see a surge of spending over the
next few months as companies try to accelerate projects to meet
year 2000 deadlines. However, the firm said, in the information
technology industry, throwing more money and bodies at major
projects do not necessarily mean success and in some cases can
hamper progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
