<HEADLINE> New Zealand Provides More Help for Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is to give a further

450,000 NZ dollars (248,000 U.S. dollars) to help refugees from
Kosovo and will accept a number of them into the country very
soon.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said Friday in a
statement that New Zealand's aid to the region will be delivered
by
two U.N. agencies. 250,000 NZ dollars will go to the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to buy tents, blankets, sleeping

bags and other essentials for families arriving in refugee camps
in
Albania and Macedonia. And a further 200,000 NZ dollars will go to

the U.N. food agency, the World Food Program (WFP), in response to

its emergency appeal for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand is concerned to see that the basic needs of
refugees,
such as food and shelter, are met," Shipley said. "New Zealand has

now provided 650,000 NZ dollars in aid, following earlier grants
of
100,000 NZ dollars each to the Red Cross and UNHCR."
</P>
<P>
She also announced that a three-person New Zealand Immigration
Service team is to leave tomorrow for Skopje to identify and
select
Kosovo refugees with family links in New Zealand, in line with the

government's decision to offer permanent places for people with
relatives in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first group of up to 50 refugees is expected to arrive in
New
Zealand on May 22 and the second group to arrive in early June,
Shipley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
