<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Ministers Sign Initiative on Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Seven African ministers signed an
initiative on water supply and management with the United Nations
Center for Human Settlements (Habitat) and the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) here Thursday, in a bid to address the
looming water crisis in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are from Cote d'Ivoire, Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya,
Senegal, South Africa and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
During the signing ceremony, Klaus Toepfer, acting executive
director of Habitat and executive director of UNEP, announced that
he would soon set up an annual award for best practices in urban
water resource management.
</P>
<P>
Toepfer revealed that he was considering to appoint Goodwill
Ambassadors for Water in African Cities who could take the message
of conserving water for the urban poor to all parts of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is the first of its kind to help African
countries in managing the growing urban water crisis and protect
the continent's threatened water resources and aquatic systems
from the increasing volume of land-based pollution.
</P>
<P>
The project is a follow-up to the Cape Town Declaration in
1997, adopted by African ministers to address the urgent need for
managing water for African cities. It is also a joint initiative
of the Habitat and the UNEP within the framework of the U.N.
system-wide Special Initiative on Africa.
</P>
<P>
The project will be implemented in collaboration with the
ministers of water resources, environment and urban development in
the participating countries.
</P>
<P>
Other agencies involved in the project include the Water Supply
and Sanitation Collaborative Council, the Southern African
Development Community and the Water Utility Partnership for
Capacity Building in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to be funded by the German government
and the United Nations Foundation for International Partnerships.
</P>
<P>
The on-going 17th session of the Habitat Commission on Human
Settlements is focusing mainly on the revitalization of the
Habitat, work program and budget for the biennium 2000-2001,
security of tenure for all residents in cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
