<HEADLINE> Thai Pork Safe to Eat: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai officials have said that pork
in the country is free from the Nipah virus, which is raging
through neighboring Malaysia's pig herds, and is safe to eat, The
Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Health and livestock officials made the remark after demand for
live pigs continued to nose-dive in the southern provinces of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Demand for pork in 14 southern provinces, especially the five
nearest to Malaysia, has slumped from as much as 20,000 head to
5,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
Officials said fears of a possible spread of the virus in
Thailand were unfounded and they urged the public to remain calm
over the reported disease incidents.
</P>
<P>
People in the southern provinces have been asked to avoid
purchasing live pigs or their by-products which have been smuggled
from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Agencies concerned have also taken several measures to cut the
smuggling of pigs and other animals including horses, cats, dogs
and goats from Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
