<HEADLINE> E-Commerce to Get Boosted in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Electronic-commerce in Thailand,
valued at 40 million baht (1.09 million U.S. dollars) last year,
will see a boost to 600 million baht (16.4 million dollars) by
2003, a seminar here was told Friday.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce, which includes every business transaction done
electronically in addition to on-line trading and on-line
shopping, has been adopted worldwide as a weapon by companies to
stay competitive, participants at the seminar on E-Commerce Law
agreed.
</P>
<P>
Many governments are lagging behind the private sector in this
regard, according to the seminar, which opened Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It also said that worldwide e-commerce transactions will be
worth 300 billion dollars by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda, who attended
Thursday's meeting, said Thailand needs to step up efforts to meet
the world's new economic order by fully adopting e-commerce to
improve fiscal and monetary systems and production.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Thai government is working on six new laws on
e-commerce, consisting of E-Commerce Law, EDI Law, Privacy Data
Protection Law, Computer Crime Law, Electronics Digital Signature
Law, Electronics Fund Transfer Law and Universal Access Law.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has said he believed three of them
would be ready for consideration by the cabinet by the end of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
