<HEADLINE> Thai Stock Brokerages Urged to Get Y2K Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET)
could punish brokerage firms which fail to solve the Year 2000
computer problem, Somkid Jiranuntarat, SET senior vice president,
confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Somkid said brokerage firms could be suspended from trading
local securities if they fail to pass a system-wide Y2K testing
scheduled for June.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of SET member brokerages have already spent
about 150 million baht (4.1 million dollars) to upgrade computer
systems to cope with the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
Regulators have placed a priority on guarding against
settlement and trading problems in the new year. Brokerages must
now submit monthly Y2K progress reports to the SET.
</P>
<P>
The SET has also asked listed companies to detail their Y2K
progress every quarter, to keep investors informed about the
potential risks in the event of computer failures, either
internally or with their trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The 400-plus listed companies are said to have spent 5.6
billion baht (153.4 million dollars) so far on solving the Y2K
problem. The SET estimates that between 70 percent and 80 percent
of the companies are now compliant.
</P>
<P>
The SET will run a test on May 22. It will be an industry-wide
test which will also involve external users and members. Another
round of tests is scheduled for January 1, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
