<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0440 GMT May 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Global economic slides are easing; multilateral
lending institutions are playing a favorable role in Asia; and
China is the most attractive Asian market in 1999 from the
standpoint of U.S. exporting.
</P>
<P>
These are some of the results of two economic outlook surveys
released Thursday by the Business Council, a voluntary association
representing a broad range of large American corporations from all
major industries and regions. The 300-member council meets three
times a year for the free exchange of ideas among themselves and
representatives of the government. (World-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Microsoft Corp. agreed Thursday to invest 5
billion U.S. dollars in AT&AMP;T in exchange for a bigger role in AT&AMP;
T's digital future.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement announced here, AT&AMP;T will double its
purchases of Microsoft software to 10 million copies, giving the
software giant up to 40 percent of AT&AMP;T's cable business.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after AT&AMP;T made a deal with its bidding
rival Comcast Tuesday to pave the way for the MediaOne merger.
Comcast dropped its bid for MediaOne after AT&AMP;T allowed the cable
company to buy two million of AT&AMP;T's cable subscribers.(Microsoft-
AT&AMP;T-Deal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Robust exports coupled with slowing imports helped
boost a surplus in the current account of the Philippines, the
Manila Times said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Central Bank, was quoted as
saying that the current account surplus rose to 570 million U.S.
dollars in January 1999, 10 times higher than 57 million U.S.
dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The hefty current account surplus pushed the balance of
payments to a surplus of 881 million U.S. dollars, a turnaround
from the deficit of 145 million U.S. dollars in January 1998, the
newspaper said. (Philippines-Current Account)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's Foundation Institute of Economic
Investigation (FIIE) predicted the country's inflation rate will
be seven percent this year, Jornal do Comercio reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said this figure is far below the 12 percent
predicted by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in January when
the real -- Brazil's currency -- experienced a drastic devaluation
against the U.S. dollar. (Brazil-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate on Thursday passed legislation
which would lift Depression-era barriers and let banks, securities
firms and insurance companies get more deeply into each other's
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Senators voted 54-44 for the bill on a party-line basis.
</P>
<P>
The bill includes a provision that would make it a federal
crime for anyone to misrepresent himself to obtain someone's
private financial data. (US-Senate-Merger) 
