<HEADLINE> Belgraders Spend Third Quiet Night </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents of the Yugoslav capital
spent a third consecutive quiet night as NATO air raids on the
Balkan country entered the 45th day Friday.
</P>
<P>
Air raid sirens wailed across the city at 21:05 local time (19:
05 GMT), but neither bomb explosions nor anti-aircraft gunfire
were heard before the all-clear was sounded at 06:05 (04:05 GMT)
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the country, at 23:35 (21:35 GMT) Thursday, NATO
planes targeted Vrsac, a city near the border with Romania,
destroying power grids and a railway bridge that connects Belgrade
with Budapest, the Romanian capital, the Tanjug news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
During the daytime Thursday, industrial facilities and
residential quarters in Novi Sad, Uzice and Pristina, capital of
Kosovo, were hit by NATO.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday morning, NATO planes bombed Nis and Sremska
Mitrovica, Tanjug said. 
</P>
