<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asia Faces E-Commerce Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- As its Internet subscriber growth is
becoming the fastest in the world, Asia is warming to
electronic-commerce, which is projected to offer a great promise
to the region's economies.
</P>
<P>
Compared with their American and European counterparts, Asians
are lagging behind in the development of e-commerce at present.
</P>
<P>
While consumers and business purchasing goods and services over
the Internet in the West spent 50 billion dollars last year, a
mere 723 million dollars in on-line retail sales were booked in
the whole Asian region, according to the Internet market research
firm Keenan Vision.
</P>
<P>
But with the world's fastest growth in Internet subscribers,
Asia has great potential for e-commerce expansion. With 10.5
million Internet accounts, subscriber growth in non-Japan Asia is
rising 39 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The Market research firm International Data Corp. estimated
that China will surpass Australia in 2001 as non-Japan Asia's top
Internet user and by the end of 2002 will have about 9.4 million
Internet users, up from a mere 1.4 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2002, Australia is expected to have 5.8 million
users up from just over 3 million now, while South Korea will be
the third biggest Internet user with about 4 million people
logging on, up from less than two million now.
</P>
<P>
With the fast development of Internet, e-commerce is expected
to grow significantly in the next few years, experts said.
</P>
<P>
In a recent survey conducted by PwC for the World Economic
Forum, 60 percent of Asia's business executives said that
e-commerce will contribute more than 5 percent of their company's
total revenues by 2003, with one fifth projecting a revenue
contribution of over 20 percent, although e-commerce makes little
or non-contribution to their companies at present.
</P>
<P>
What has prompted Asia's business executives to promote
e-commerce? Some of them said e-commerce could sweep away market
inefficiencies, such as excessive transaction costs, asymmetric
information, and natural monopolies, breaking up arcane market
barriers.
</P>
<P>
As e-commerce is regarded as the future of business, Asians are
also getting pushed by Western companies demanding for business
over the Internet to save cost, they said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the recent Asian recession has made business
executives more aware than ever of the pressing need to cut their
costs, increase efficiency and stay in touch with their customers.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Asia's e-commerce expansion still faces great
challenges. Many developing economies in the region lack reliable
communications, and state-monopoly of telecommunications in some
countries leads to high cost for consumers. Legal frameworks and
taxation issues governing e-commerce are also uncertain.
</P>
<P>
There are other barriers to consumer e-commerce. Not many in
Asia have credit cards, and many prefer face-to-face buying and
most of the region is served by corner shops. For many Asian
banks, they mistrust on-line transactions, according to the
Economist weekly.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the importance of e-commerce and its challenges,
Asian countries are trying to remove these barriers. In Vietnam,
where just 15,000 people are on-line, the government has slashed
40 percent of access charges to make its use more affordable.
</P>
<P>
For years, India's telecommunications company VSNL charged its
customers 500 U.S. dollars for 500 hours of slow Internet service.
But recently, the government opened the market for competition,
10,000 subscribers signed up for rival Satyam Infoware's service.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that India's Internet subscribers could reach
10 million in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, law makers have adopted laws for e-commerce
activities and the government is encouraging people to use
Internet for business.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor, Singapore's
Singapore-One, and Hong Kong's brand new cyberport are examples of
major government-sponsored projects that demonstrated the
determination of Asian leaders to make the information technology
revolution, and e-commerce," said the Asian Business in its May
1999 issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Extensive Use of Briquette </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Myanmar official has called
for extensive use of briquette, a kind of firewood substitute
fuel, saying it is the most effective means for reduction of
firewood use as well as for conservation of forests in the
country.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here Thursday of a committee for organizing
extensive use of the substitute fuel, Lt. Gen. Tin Oo, second
secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, said
plans were being drawn for the extensive use of the briquette in
the 1999-2000 and 2000-2001 fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need for extensive supply and utilization of
the firewood substitute fuel, calling for an end to felling of
trees.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar started a project of greening nine arid districts in
the central part of the country in 1993, designating 1995 as the
firewood substitute fuel year with some progress reportedly made
in the implementation.
</P>
<P>
Some departments have innovated and demonstrated some kinds of
stoves and solar-powered stoves as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
In addition, coal, paddy-husk and saw-dust briquette are also
being introduced as other kinds of substitute fuel.
</P>
<P>
Firewood, along with charcoal, has been used in Myanmar with an
annual consumption of more than 24 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The indiscriminate felling and cutting of trees including
firewood plantations for fuel and burning of charcoal have been
the cause of forest depletion in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's forest area is shrinking year by year, dropping by 7
percent compared with 36 years ago. The 1962 data showed that 57
percent of the country's total area was then covered by forests,
but the percentage dropped to 50 in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
