<HEADLINE> Latvia Hails Russia's Disarmament in Northwest Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Latvian Foreign Ministry hailed
the disarmament of Russia Thursday in its northwest border area.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry said Russia's move has conformed
with the historical tide following the cold war's end, and it has
been helpful in boosting trust among European countries.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev was quoted by a Latvian
newspaper as saying during a meeting of northern European defense
ministers in Norway's capital Oslo on Wednesday that Russia had
cut 52 percent of the armies of the Leningrad Command and 57
percent of those stationed in Kaliningrad Command.
</P>
<P>
He said 19 percent of the North Fleet and 29 percent of the
Baltic Sea Fleet had also been trimmed, Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the military forces in the northwest of Russia
were only of a "defensive" nature after the disarmament and would
not pose any threat to neighboring countries. 
</P>
