<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Two Credits for Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank on Thursday
approved two credits totaling 48.38 million U.S. dollars to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 26 million dollars will be used to support the
African country's Second Agricultural Research and Training
Project, and the balance amounting to 22.38 million dollars will
be used to finance the Nakivubo Channel Rehabilitation Project.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, the agricultural project is
designed to develop and transfer improved technologies; promote
the adoption by small farm operators of relevant technologies,
indigenous knowledge, and improved cultural management practices,
and enable the decentralization of research and development
activities to the different agro-ecological zones.
</P>
<P>
The project also will reinforce the National Agricultural
Research Organization's technical and in-service training support
for district-level extension services.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the Nakivubo Channel Rehabilitation Project
are to assist the government in building the institutional
capacity of the city council of Kampala, the capital of Uganda, to
plan, manage, and execute complex investment decisions and
programs; establish a framework for general maintenance of
infrastructure and equipment; and physically rehabilitate the
Nakivubo Channel.
</P>
<P>
The two credits will be provided by the International
Development Association, the World Bank's lending arm for poor
countries, and will be payable in 40 years, including a 10-year
grace period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
