<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Tunisia Sign Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Tunisia have signed an
agreement to further boost bilateral ties by strengthening
cooperation in economic, trade, science and cultural fields
between the two countries, media reports here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed Thursday at the end of the talks
between Vietnam's Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Nguyen Manh Cam and Tunisian Foreign Minster Said Ben Moustapha,
who arrived here Thursday for a three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
It is the first official visit to Vietnam by a Tunisian foreign
minister since the two countries established diplomatic relations
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
At the Meeting with the Tunisian foreign minister, Cam said the
two countries had many similarities in economic conditions and
both sides should utilize their available potential to promote
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam would assist Tunisia in irrigation and fresh water
fishing, Cam said.
</P>
<P>
Cam said he was happy to see the progress the Tunisian people
had made in their national development, and appreciated Tunisia's
position in Africa as well as within the Non-Aligned Movement and
the French-speaking community.
</P>
<P>
Moustapha said Tunisia wants to further strengthen and develop
cooperation in all aspects with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed a number of regional
and international issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held that it was a must to have regular exchange of
visits of high-level government officials and business leaders to
identify the specific areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Cam accepted an invitation from Moustapha to visit Tunisia.
</P>
