<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Formulates National Film Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has formulated a National
Film Policy to restore the film industry to its "pristine glory"
through far reaching policy changes, said a press release from the
Presidential Secretariat received Friday.
</P>
<P>
The National Film Policy comes at a time when Sri Lanka is
preparing for a major regional film festival in September.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) Film Festival will be held in Colombo to boost the
interaction within the region.
</P>
<P>
The new scheme seeks to make it viewers friendly and ensure
that cinema artistes are lucratively employed, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The main features of the scheme will be concessionary financing
of up to 2.5 million rupees (36,000 U.S. dollars) for color films
and 1.5 million rupees (21,600 dollars) for black-and-white films,
tax concessions for film production, and reduction of the
entertainment tax paid to local authorities and other state
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The goods and services tax (GST) will be levied only on box
office collections.
</P>
<P>
The laws and regulations governing the import and distribution
of films will also be liberalized. It will be ensured that
imported films strictly conform to the regulations and laws
governing violence, alcohol and narcotics and other dangers.
</P>
<P>
The new policy will seek the integration of cinema and
television to alleviate the cinema industry which has suffered due
to the global introduction of television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
