<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Russia Condemn NATO's Air War on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and
his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin on Thursday denounced NATO's
air war against Yugoslavia in a statement issued at the southern
Ukrainian port of Sevastopol, hoping to restore peace to the
Balkans, the Ukrainian Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Sevastopol, where the Black Sea fleet is
located, celebrated its 55th anniversary of Germany's defeat.
Yeltsin dispatched Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev to attend the
celebration and sent a congratulatory message.
</P>
<P>
He said in the message that upon entrance into the 21st century,
the fate of people cannot be decided by force. NATO's aggression
against the sovereign state of Yugoslavia has cast the shadow of
war over Europe. It has also resulted in the death and casualties
of innocent civilians, to which those who have experienced the
horror of war cannot turn a blind eye.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president noted that as times are no longer what
they used to be, people should not only value peace but also work
toward it. People should not handle interstate relationships on
the basis of "narrow-minded will" but on the internationally-
acknowledged principles stipulated in the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma pointed out that Ukraine has suffered great losses and
sacrifices during the past wars and understands the sharp
conflicts between war and peace. He called on all countries
involved in armed conflicts to act cautiously and be responsible
for their deeds.
</P>
<P>
He noted that historical mistakes should not be repeated in the
Balkans since all arguments and rhetoric will not be able to
justify human suffering, deaths and tears.
</P>
<P>
He also affirmed that Ukraine would not get involved in the
Kosovo military conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
