<HEADLINE> Brazil Predicts 7-Percent Inflation Rate This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Foundation Institute
of Economic Investigation (FIIE) predicted the country's inflation
rate will be seven percent this year, Jornal do Comercio reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said this figure is far below the 12 percent
predicted by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in January when
the real -- Brazil's currency -- experienced a drastic devaluation
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the stock market is up 71 percent this year
and is almost back to its last peak in March 1998. Prices in the
bond market have jumped, as yields, which move in the opposite
direction, have plunged.
</P>
<P>
The yield on Brazil's benchmark long-term bond maturing in 2070
is down to 12.6 percent, from 16.9 percent just two months ago.
</P>
