<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aquiculture Boosts Paddy Field Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Aquatics like crustaceans, grass
carps, chubs, soft-shelled turtles, crabs and eels are now bred
not only in ponds but also in paddy fields in more and more
Chinese rural areas.
</P>
<P>
A technology to develop the aquiculture in paddy fields has
found growing favor among Chinese farmers, especially those living
in eastern and central-southern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Agrotechnicians of the Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences
believe that popularizing the technology could help increase
farmers' income by more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The technology was developed some 30 years ago but it was only
put into large-scale application in recent few years, said Shen
Zufang, an official of the aquiculture bureau of the province.
</P>
<P>
Considering the advantages, aquatic breeding could help
fertilize the paddy fields and help make water oxidization, which
will lead to increased output.
</P>
<P>
Even better, pests in paddy fields are the ideal food for
aquatic creatures, helping reduce the production costs by a big
margin, said Shen Zufang.
</P>
<P>
Farmers rarely spray pesticides or scatter fertilizers in the
paddy fields used for aquatic produce, thus both the rice and
acquatic produce are not contaminated and sell well.
</P>
<P>
The technology has been widely used in Jiangsu, Anhui, Hunan,
Hubei, Guangdong, Fujian, and Zhejiang Provinces and brings in
relatively stable economic returns for local farmers.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu Province, one of the country's leading forces in
agricultural advancement, has set an example for other
agricultural producers across the country with its success.
</P>
<P>
Paddy fields cultivated for aquatic products in the province
has risen to the current 133,333 hectares from the 96,666 hectares
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Output value of local aquatic products in paddy fields hit 3.38
billion yuan in 1998, including 1.66 billion yuan of profits.
</P>
<P>
Average economic returns for each mu (one hectare is equal to
15 mu) were 1,145 yuan for the aquatic products, with the figure
for the breeding of soft-shelled turtle and crabs as much as 2,700
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
