<HEADLINE> U.S. Sets up Anti-Drug Base in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadorian port city of Manta is
becoming a strategic place for the U.S. anti-narcotic war, as the
Pacific coast city has lately been used as one of the U.S. Army's
anti-drug centers in Latin America, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reports confirmed that the first American plane arrived in
Manta last Saturday. On Thursday afternoon, a group of 25 persons -
- army officials and members of the U.S. Anti-drug Agency -- are
expected to arrive at the air base.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. diplomat in Quito, Curtis Struble, said that Manta will
be used to land American aircraft that were previously used in
Panama localities.
</P>
<P>
The United States chose Manta as the anti-drug center after
negotiations failed with Panama's government on operating U.S.
surveillance equipment from the Panamanian isthmus.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Ecuador and the United States, signed in
December 1998, has been in force since April 1. The agreement has
a duration of six months, during which there will be an attempt to
negotiate another 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
The center of anti-narcotic operations for the U.S. Army in
Panama ended their activities Wednesday in order to move to other
places throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States is also establishing similar operation
centers in the Caribbean islands of Aruba and Curazao. 
</P>
