<HEADLINE> Lockheed, Partners to Develop Astrolink Satellite System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Lockheed Marting Corp., TRW inc.
and Telecom Italia will create a new global satellite
telecommunication system called Astrolink to provide multimedia
services, high-speed Internet access and private corporate data
networks, the Wall Street Journal said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 3.5 billion U.S. dollar Astrolink will have nine high-power
and high-orbital satellites which use the newly opening Ka-band of
the radio spectrum.
</P>
<P>
The first four will be launched into space in 2002 and the rest
in the second stage of the Astrolink project, with the service
starting in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The initial funding is one billion dollars from the three
partners with Lockheed as the biggest investor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other competitors in the United States and Europe
are also planning to enter the same market with services on that
frequency band or others, including Teledesic LLc, the venture
backed by Microsoft Corp., cellular pioneer Craig McCaw and others.
</P>
</TEXT>
