<P>
HELSINKI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Finland welcomed the G-8 agreement
reached Thursday by Russia and the Group of Seven industrialized
countries on a political settlement to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Finish government expressed satisfaction
with the agreement and the decision to seek a U.N. mandate for an
international security force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating its support for a political solution to the crisis,
the government said it hoped the U.N. Security Council would pass
a resolution on the issue as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Bonn on Thursday, Russian and G-7 foreign
ministers agreed on a seven-point plan to be endorsed by the U.N.
Security Council that calls for a deployment of "effective
international civil and security presence" in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for a U.N. interim administration for Kosovo and
self-rule, but rejects independence of the Yugoslav province.
</P>
</TEXT>
