<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Going Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
decided to put the provincial government and all its departments
on the Internet by August, according to a provincial government
source.
</P>
<P>
The source says that this is part of China's ambitious campaign
to increase government presence at all levels.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial plan, all government offices at the
provincial level in Shandong will have their own websites by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The move was started by the State Economic and Trade Commission,
the Ministry of Information Industry, and other ministries to
share their information resources with each other and to improve
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission opened a website on
December 1, 1998, and an increasing number of visitors have
expressed their opinions on the site on everything from
environmental pollution to a medical insurance system.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Government made its debut earlier this
year with a website called Window on the Capital that provides
information about the economic situation, job possibilities, and
air-quality reports. The Guangzhou and Shenzhen governments in
Guangdong Province have also opened trial websites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
