<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People In Beijing Applying For Individual Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's City Commercial Bank was
the first bank to offer individual loans to consumers this March
and more than 200 people went to a participating shopping center,
Parkson, in the first month to apply for the loan.
</P>
<P>
The bank's Yanjing branch has provided 270,000 yuan (32,500 U.S.
dollars) worth of loans and 10 other branches recently signed
similar contracts with 16 large department stores.
</P>
<P>
The new spending pattern has been advertised as "spending
tomorrow's money for today's dream", but a lot of people can still
not get used to it because it is so different. The Chinese have
always been quite frugal and careful about every penny. "We used
to be encouraged to add to our bank savings as much as we could,
but now we are being asked to borrow money from the bank and being
told that consuming more will help the economy. It is really hard
for me to accept," said one middle-aged woman.
</P>
<P>
Bank personnel point out that, in applying for loans, customers
need a stable income to cover the loan. Most loans are used to buy
computers. A 9,800-yuan computer requires a down payment of 2,000
yuan, and, with monthly installments of 300 yuan with the interest
added in, the total over a two-year period comes to 10,352 yuan.
</P>
<P>
This is both affordable and worthwhile, one female customer, a
teacher, said, because the computer will undoubtedly increase
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Most people applying have a monthly income of around 1,000 yuan
and are applying for 2 to 5-year loans that range from 8,000 to 10,
000 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
