<HEADLINE> Indonesia Futures Exchange to Begin Trading in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's first futures
commodities exchange will begin operation in August this year
after several delays in its opening, The Jakarta Post reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The president of state-owned commodities clearing house PT
Kliring and Jaminan Bursa Komoditi A. Djunaidi said preparations
for the operation of the futures exchange were completed.
</P>
<P>
The futures exchange will be called Indonesia Futures Exchange
(IFEX) and will have its trading floor at the Menara Kadin
building in South Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"IFEX will be legally established by the public notary in
mid-May," he said.
</P>
<P>
PT Kliring, which operates as the clearing house for the
existing commodities exchange, is one of the main sponsors of the
futures exchange.
</P>
<P>
Other sponsors include the Association of Indonesian Coffee
Exporters and the Federation of Indonesian Vegetable Oil and Fat
Associations.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the futures exchange had been scheduled for the
beginning of 1998 but was postponed several times.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1999 government regulation on the IFEX, the bourse
needs at least 11 members before it can be established.
</P>
<P>
"To date there are about 30 companies who have registered to be
IFEX members," Djunaidi said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Presidential Decree No. 12/1999, palm oil and coffee
can be traded on the exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
