<HEADLINE> Indonesian Cellular Firms Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's three Advanced Mobile
Phone System (AMPS) operators have joined forces in competing with
operators in other systems, The Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three AMPS operators are PT Komselindo, PT Metrosel
Nusantara and PT Telesera.
</P>
<P>
Komselindo director for marketing and business development Zen
Smith said that under an agreement signed early last month, the
three companies, which operate in different locations, would share
transmission facilities to enable them to expand their coverage
area.
</P>
<P>
The three AMPS operators will be better equipped to compete
with operators in other systems which offer wide coverage.
</P>
<P>
"We can now offer more value-added services to our subscribers
because this cooperation will enable us to improve our coverage
nationwide without massive investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Previously, AMPS subscribers could only use their cellular
phones in the areas covered by their operators. They had to change
to other operators if they went to other regions.
</P>
<P>
Under the cooperation agreement, AMPS subscribers will be able
to use their mobile phones in all areas served by the three
companies.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has seven cellular phone providers operating three
systems: AMPS, the Global System for Mobile communications (GSM)
and the Nordic Mobile Telephone (NMT).
</P>
<P>
AMPS currently has some 101,000 subscribers, accounting for 12
percent of the country's 900,000 cellular subscribers. Over 80
percent of mobile phone users in Indonesia are GSM subscribers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Poll Shows Support for NATO Strikes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, May 6 (Xinhua) -- As NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia continue, more and more Polish people have begun to
oppose the war in Kosovo, according to the latest public opinion
poll published by the Polish News Agency on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the approval rating of NATO military maneuvers
in Yugoslavia dropped by eight percentage points from 63 percent
on April 16 to 55 percent at present. About 42 percent disapprove
of NATO launching a ground war, while 38 percent approve.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 63 percent of the respondents are
concerned that the situation in the Balkan region could lead to a
world war, up from 37 percent polled on April 16.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one percent of the respondents are against Polish ground
troops participating in a ground war, compared with a support rate
of only 37 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
