<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Securities Firms Announce Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Two major Chinese securities firms,
Guotai Securities Co. Ltd. and the Jun'an Securities Co. Ltd.
today announced a merger plan that will result in the largest
securities firm in the country.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai-based Guotai had net assets of 1.55 billion yuan by
the end of 1998, making it the fifth largest securities firm in
China, and Shenzhen-based Jun'an is now the second largest, with
assets of 1.86 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The new firm will have assets of 3.4 billion yuan, well above
Shanghai's Shenyin &AMP; Wanguo Securities Co. Ltd., China's top
securities now, which has assets of 2.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guotai had profits of 735 million yuan in 1998, while Jun'an
ranks 9th, with profits of 290.7 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The merger was approved at a general conference of shareholders
of the two companies on April 13. Analysts here say that it means
a reshuffling of the market, with the country's first securities
law expected to take effect in less than two months and the
capital market set to open to foreign competition because China's
membership in the World Trade Organization (WTO) seems to be only
a little ways away from approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
