<HEADLINE> Italian Coach 'Offered England Job' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Former AC Milan boss Fabio Capello
was made an offer for the job of England coach, an Italian
newspaper Gazzetta dello Sport reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Capello could become the first foreigner to
manage England if Kevin Keegan decides not to continue once his
current tenure ends.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper claimed that FA Technical Director Howard
Wilkinson made him an offer during a visit to Milan on 21 April -
the day before Manchester United's European Cup match with
Juventus.
</P>
<P>
Capello is still under contract to the Italian Serie A side,
despite being replaced as manager last summer.
</P>
<P>
The Gazzetta reported that if England failed to qualify for
Euro 2000 by losing its forthcoming qualifying matches against
Sweden and Bulgaria, Keegan would return to coaching Fulham and
the Italian would get the job.
</P>
<P>
Keegan has expressed interest in staying on as England manager,
but he has yet to make it clear if that means under his current"
part-time arrangement, which allows him to continue coaching
recently-promoted Fulham, or if he is prepared to make a full-time
commitment.
</P>
<P>
As coach at Milan, Capello took four Italian league
championships and the 1994 European Cup. He also managed Spanish
side Real Madrid to championship victory.
</P>
<P>
He returned to AC Milan for a less successful tenure in 1997-8
that saw him replaced by current manager Alberto Zaccheroni.
</P>
<P>
Milan are currently lying second in Serie A behind leaders
Lazio. 
</P>
