<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea to Adopt Summer Fishing Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- This year, for the first time, China
will impose a two-month-long summer fishing ban in the South China
Sea to protect marine resources.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Province, the southernmost island in the South China Sea,
will impose the ban beginning on June 1, according to the
provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Trawlers and net-fishing from sailboats will be prohibited
until July 31 in the sea everywhere north of 12 degrees north
latitude, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will conduct a series of supervisions
and inspections during the two months to ensure that the offshore
fishing ban is implemented completely.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, fishery departments in Hainan will provide
maintenance services for local fishermen. In addition, the
province will hold training programs on professional techniques,
fire safety, and scientific explanations of typhoon patterns.
</P>
</TEXT>
