<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Make Full Use of Crop Stalks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China will launch a pilot project in
five provinces to promote comprehensive utilization of crop stalks
in order to save energy and protect the environment, according to
the Ministry of Science and Technology (MST).
</P>
<P>
The new program will be initiated in Hebei, Henan, Shandong,
Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces this year, the Modern Agriculture
Weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
Han Deqian, vice minister of the MST, was quoted by the
newspaper as saying the ministry will list the program as one of
the key projects this year and will change the old heavily
polluting method of burning crop stalks in the five provinces
within two years.
</P>
<P>
China now turns out some 600 million tons of crop stalks each
year, 20 percent of which are burned as garbage.
</P>
<P>
The MST has been devoted to addressing the issue for nearly two
decades and has worked out a number of solutions including the
application of crop stalks as manure, fodder, and raw materials
for the chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have also developed a technique of using
crop stalks to generate electricity in Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The technique now is being applied by the Huagang Rice
Corporation Ltd. in Putian in eastern Fujian Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
