<HEADLINE> Playoff Preview: Knicks, Heat Highlight First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Following is the Playoff preview
from the Sporting News here today:
</P>
<P>
Western Conference
</P>
<P>
San Antonio vs Minnesota: No one is playing with greater
confidence or purpose than San Antonio right now, and no one out
West has more of the necessary ingredients -- size, post power,
defense rebounding differential -- for postseason success. The
Spurs are a gathering storm, and no eight seed is going to change
that reality. Though the Wolves held Tim Duncan to 14 points per
game in their four encounters (2-2 split), three of those games
were played during the bygone Stephon Marbury era.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles vs Houston: Proof that two negatives can make a
positive. Both teams had disappointing seasons, both are still
searching for the best way to play, both are still trying to
incorporate their big acquisitions, both could be facing roster
makeovers after their elimination.
</P>
<P>
We do love our subplots. In the end, it will come down to the
basic playoff elements: Who makes stops, who makes shots --
particularly in crunch time of Game 5. Just a hunch, but the
Rockets have more guys equipped to make plays. But if it comes
down to one shot, make-or-miss to advance, the ball's in Kobe's
hands, all bets are off. Houston in five.
</P>
<P>
Utah vs. Sacramento: The Kings wanted the sixth seed so that
they would match up with Utah. They played them well enough during
the regular season, taking the Jazz into overtime three times (
winning one). Jazz sweep.
</P>
<P>
Portland vs. Phoenix: It is the third-best rebounding against
the one ranked 22nd., and that should decide it. Perhaps Rex
Chapman can return to a previous postseason incarnation and drive
J.R. Rider off the deep end. But there are too many unfavorable
matchups here for Phoenix, and too much quality length for it to
deal with. Damon Stoudamire says the Suns will never win a title
with Jason Kidd at point guard, because he is playing all by
himself. Blazers in four.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Conference:
</P>
<P>
Miami vs. New York: This is the most intriguing encounters of
the first round, because it's one of few one-vs-eight matchups in
which most folks actually favor the underdog. If Patrick Ewing has
problem with his sore Achilles, New York will be dead. Heat in
five typically grueling games.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta vs. Detroit: The Hawks are more stable. If Mookie
Blaylock stays under control, they'll play good defense, and
they'll run the most predictable stuff in the league. Grant Hill
will be a big factor. Piston in four.
</P>
<P>
Orlando vs. Philadelphia: This is a series Orlando should get,
but it hasn't distinguished itself on the road (12-13) this year,
so it had better not muff one of the first two. The Sixers are an
admirable little pack, composed of one uncoachable pocket rocket
who gets every shot and an abundance of tough-minded role players,
but if it comes down to stopping just one score, Chuck Daly will
find a way. Orlando in four.
</P>
<P>
Indiana vs. Milwaukee: Indiana was just bore. No team in the
East comes close to matching its depth, its length, its halfcourt
execution, its shooting ability. But Bucks led the conference in
scoring with 46 percent shooting, and they were the best team in
the league from the arc. They're a physical wreck right now,
however, with Glenn Robinson nursing a knee and Sam Cassell still
hobbled by an ankle. Pacers sweep. 
</P>
</TEXT>
