<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Exports Boost Current Account Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Robust exports coupled with slowing
imports helped boost a surplus in the current account of the
Philippines, the Manila Times said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Central Bank, was quoted as
saying that the current account surplus rose to 570 million U.S.
dollars in January 1999, 10 times higher than 57 million U.S.
dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The hefty current account surplus pushed the balance of
payments to a surplus of 881 million U.S. dollars, a turnaround
from the deficit of 145 million U.S. dollars in January 1998, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The current account is made up largely of the balance of trade
in goods and services, including transfers, profit remittances and
interest payments.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports grew by 22 percent in January to 2.6
billion U.S. dollars as the weak peso makes local goods cheaper
abroad, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, imports fell by 12.7 percent to 2.4 billion U.S.
dollars as demand for goods made overseas becomes more expensive
due to the depreciated local currency, it said.
</P>
<P>
Weak domestic demand caused manufacturers to lower the
importation of raw materials for their production, the newspaper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Hit by 519 Earthquakes So Far This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua has recorded a total of
519 earthquakes this year, of which 473 took place in the Pacific
Ocean and only 12 were felt by the population.
</P>
<P>
These quakes were a result of tectonic plates Coco and Caribe
colliding, Zoila Hernandez, an expert from the Nicaraguan
Institute of Territorial Studies (INETER), explained.
</P>
<P>
The seismologist indicated the probabilities of a seaquake
occurring on the Pacific Ocean's coast were minimal due to the
surface and the low strength of the quakes reported.
</P>
<P>
Hernandez said that INETER will provide information and
training to the heads and directors of various centers of study,
to prevent greater disasters following a natural phenomenon such
as an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
"The population must be certain that Nicaragua is a seismic
country and it needs to create a culture of prevention before
natural disasters occur," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0365 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Population to Reach 100 Million Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican National Counsel of
Population (CONAPO) said Thursday that Mexico's population will
reach 100 million in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
CONAPO predicted that in the first 10 years of the forthcoming
century, the population in Mexico will top 112 million, while by
year 2050 it will be 131 million.
</P>
<P>
A study in perspective said the average life span of Mexicans
in the middle of the 21st century would be 84 years, nine years
longer compared with the current life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
The study also showed a tendency toward a lower birth rate
among Mexican women following increased family planning.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2005, one Mexican woman will have an average of 2.1
children; that figure will be reduced to 1.7 in the following
years of the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
