<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT May 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The high tension between the Kuwaiti parliament
and government, which was sparked by the parliament grilling of a
cabinet minister, has been defused with Tuesday's dissolution of
the legislature by Emir Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The decision to dissolve the parliament and to elect a new one
on July 3 was announced hours after the relations between the
executive and legislative powers seemed irreversibly
irreconcilable. (Kuwait-Parliament-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Top ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova said Thursday
that the presence of an international peace force in Kosovo which
included NATO was a "key condition" to solving the Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference Thursday evening with
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema and Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini, Rugova said that the "installation of an
international peace keeping force composed of NATO and other
countries" was vital to stop the conflict over Kosovo. (Rugova-
Italy-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The Yugoslav Ambassador to the United Nations Office
at Geneva (UNOG) has urged NATO to stop aggression against his
country in order to reach a political and peaceful settlement for
the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The most important precondition to settle all political issues
in Kosovo and Metohija and to resolve humanitarian problems is
halting NATO aggression, destruction and killing of people," said
Branko Brankovic at a press conference here Thursday. (Yugoslavia-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Bonn -- The foreign ministers of the Group of Eight (G-8),
seven western industrialized countries and Russia, ended their
talks Thursday at Petersburg near Bonn with a five- point
statement, including seven "general principles" on a political
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers agreed that Yugoslavia should withdraw
from Kosovo its military, police and paramilitary forces. (G8-
Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- At least four people were killed as a line of
powerful tornadoes blew through the west of the U.S. state of
Tennessee early Thursday, damaging buildings in 30 counties.
</P>
<P>
Two of the victims, a man and woman, died in Linden City when
their home was destroyed by winds. A 14-year-old girl, who had
been missing since Wednesday night, was found early Thursday and
taken to a hospital where she died upon arrival. (US-Storms-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Little progress has been made in the latest talks in
London aimed at ending the stalemate in the Northern Ireland peace
process, a Downing Street spokesman said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said there was no prospect of a quick
breakthrough in negotiations involving Prime Minister Tony Blair,
his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern and key party leaders of the
province. (UK-N.Ireland-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank approved a credit of 30 million U.
S. dollars for Albania to help the country counter the economic
effects of the crisis in neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The credit will provide quick-disbursing budget support to
allow the government of Albania to resume critical public
expenditures which were frozen to allow for the unbudgeted
expenditures incurred as a result of the massive inflow of
refugees since NATO launched air-strikes against Yugoslavia in
March 1999, the bank said. (WB-Albania)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Yugoslav Government approved on Thursday
a humanitarian mission that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
plans to send to Kosovo and other parts of the Balkan country, a
senior United Nations official announced.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira De Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, said in a statement that he has received the
news from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav
Mission to the United Nations, "confirming that his government
would facilitate the conduct of the mission." (UN-Yugoslavia-
Kosovo) 
</P>
