<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Urban District Taking Shape in Shanghai's Pudong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Pudong New Area, a
rising financial and trade zone, has maintained an average annual
economic growth rate of 21 percent for nine consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show its gross domestic product (GDP had increased
to 70.9 billion yuan last year from only six billion yuan nine
years ago.
</P>
<P>
With around 8.3 percent of Shanghai's total area and 10 percent
of the municipal population, Pudong accounted for 20 percent of
the city's value of GDP last year.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth rate for all of Shanghai was 10.1 percent while
the national figure was 7.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute Pudong's fast growth to an improved business
environment and the high quality of overseas-funded enterprises
based in the area.
</P>
<P>
Since it was set up in 1990, the Pudong New Area has already
completed ten major infrastructure projects, with another ten
under construction, including an international airport, a subway
and a pedestrian tunnel across the Huangpu River that separates
the area from downtown Shanghai. At least 200 billion yuan has
been used for infrastructure construction to date.
</P>
<P>
The framework of a financial, trade and manufacturing center is
taking shape in the area.
</P>
<P>
Pudong now has 72 overseas-funded financial institutions and
108 foreign trade firms set up by corporations from other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Investors from more than 60 foreign countries and regions have
launched more than 5,400 projects in Pudong, with total investment
hitting 28 billion U.S. dollars. Eighty-eight of the top 500
multinationals in the world have opened 140 subsidiaries in the
area.
</P>
<P>
These projects cover such sectors as telecommunications,
electric appliances, biological engineering, automobiles,
computers, machinery and electronics, turning the area into a new
and high-tech industrial center of the city.
</P>
<P>
Pudong is now focusing on becoming an international center of
finance, trade, tourism, and conference and exhibition in the
coming century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Bank Loans Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Despite policy moves by the
Philippine government and monetary authorities to encourage banks
to increase their lending, bank loans fell again in March, the
Business World newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Central Bank were quoted as saying that total
loans released by local banks shrank by 0.72 percent on an annual
basis in March, after dropping by 0.16 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The continued contraction has become a worrisome issue for the
government, which is hoping for an increase in bank lending to
speed up the country's economic recovery this year, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
In line with the goal, the government has pursued a policy of
lower interest rates since last year to encourage banks to lend to
business.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall decline in bank lending, the Central Bank
sees some positive signs, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Loans to the private sector, comprising 79 percent of the net
domestic credit, fell by only 4.17 percent during March, compared
with a decline of 5.37 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Loan quality, not profits, is still the main issue for bank
credit right now, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
