<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with details U.S. House Approves 13.1 Billion U.S. Dollars for Kosovo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of Representatives
on Thursday approved a 13.1 billion U.S. dollar package to pay for
the air war against Yugoslavia and increase the nation's military
readiness.
</P>
<P>
The measure, approved by a vote of 311 to 105, would more than
double the six billion dollars requested by President Bill Clinton
last month to persist the war until September and care for the
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Most of the bill will be paid for from this year's expected
federal surplus of 111 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has not produced its own version of the legislation.
The Republican leaders there have said they prefer a package
closer in size to Clinton's request.
</P>
<P>
Congressional leaders have set a May 14 deadline for final
passage. Analysts say that the House and Senate would reach a
compromise of about nine billion dollars next week.
</P>
<P>
The House-approved package includes three billion dollars for
spare parts, depot maintenance and to address other service
shortages, 1.8 billion dollars for a military pay raise and more
than one billion dollars for military construction. 
