<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0373 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Crackdown on Business Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- In the first quarter, 69,600 cases
of business scams were handled across China, up 13.4 percent over
the same period last year, a senior official with the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce told Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the cases largely involve fake and shoddy products,
the sale of smuggled goods, violations of consumers' rights,
commercial fraud and other dishonest business practices, valued at
1.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases involving more than 1 million yuan surged
to 105 by the end of March, more than twice the number reported
during the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Confiscated fake and shoddy commodities include 600 tons of
food, 1.5 million bottles of alcoholic drinks, 1,380 tons of
chemical fertilizer, 338 tons of seeds, 1,071 farm vehicles and 1.
2 million video compact discs, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the January-March period, some 900 cases relating to the
sale of smuggled goods were cracked with a total value of 170
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The illegal imitation of brand-name products, the forgery of
quality approval certificates, and misleading advertisements
accounted for more than 75 percent of the total cases, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
