<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tamed White Storks Returned to Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Three tamed white storks in the
Xianghai Nature Reserve, northeast China's Jilin Province, have
recently been returned to nature.
</P>
<P>
They are now contentedly living with their wild cousins and
looks as though the may even start breeding together. The managers
of the reserve said that the three birds, which were raised in
captivity, were used for study soon after they were born.
</P>
<P>
The reserve made a decision last winter to release the birds
back into the wild this spring.
</P>
<P>
White storks, just one kind of wading bird, are under the
state's first-class protection. One manager revealed that about 50
wild white storks have visited the reserve every year in the past
dozen or so years.
</P>
<P>
The reserve has also set up taming labs for rare birds
including red-crown cranes and golden eagles. They gained success
in helping the white storks with the reproduction in 1989, and the
reproduction between the tamed red-crown cranes and the wild ones
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, with an area of 105,467 hectares, was ranked among
the state-level reserves in 1986. And the number of bird species
in the reserve have now reached 286 from the 175 in the beginning,
and species of animals including Mongolian gazelles and roe deer
now number 37. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
