<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tracks of South China Tiger Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientific survey group
found the tracks of a south China tiger during a recent trip to
Fobao primeval forest in southwest Chin.
</P>
<P>
In late April, the 12-member survey team saw a dozen new paw
prints of what is reckoned to be a tiger when it came to a
vegetable plot at a mountainous area which covers a 600 square
kilometer area at the juncture of Sichuan and Guizhou provinces
and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
A forest worker named Tao Jiahai told team members that he had
heard the sounds of an animal at night a few days before the
arrival of the survey team and saw a string of tiger footprints
the following morning.
</P>
<P>
Yang Changgang, from Xinqian Village in Guizhou Province, told
team members he had seen the remains of four sheep which he
assumed had been eaten by a tiger in January last year.
</P>
<P>
An earlier study reported that wild tigers have been completely
extinct in China since 1960s but this exciting discovery suggests
that may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are only 53 South China tigers still in
existence, all of them in 21 Chinese zoos and most are sick,
handicapped or aged.
</P>
<P>
The South China tiger is rarer than the Giant Panda and is
listed among the 10 species in extreme danger of extinction by
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
It was usually found in Hunan, Jiangxi, Jiangsu and Fujian
provinces. In the 1950s, China had more than 4,000 of them but 675
were killed by illegal hunters between 1952 and 1964.  
</P>
</TEXT>
