<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Tackle Acid Rain in Pearl River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to tackle the acid rain
problem in the Pearl River Delta, Guangdong Province in south
China has decided not to build any more coal consuming power
plants in the area.
</P>
<P>
All cities in the area have begun to take measures to control
exhaust emission by motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 23 million tons of sulfur dioxide are
discharged into the atmosphere in China every year, causing acid
rain to fall over 40 percent of the nation's territory, according
to the State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
A report from the Provincial Environmental Protection
Monitoring Center said that the Pearl River Delta in south China
has been seriously plagued by acid rain in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong
Province, had more frequent occurrences of acid rain last year,
with an average rate of about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall with a pH (a measure of acidity and alkalinity) lower
than 5.6 is regarded as acid rain in China.
</P>
<P>
High-sulfur coal fuel consumption by thermal power plants and
exhaust emission by motor vehicles are believed to be the main
causes of acid rain in the area. From Shenzhen to Zhuhai, a
coastal city in Guangdong, there are 10 large thermal power plants.
</P>
<P>
So far, 17 cities in Guangdong and all cities in the delta have
been included into the State's acid rain control plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0382 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
