<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Reaffirms Support for Supachai in Contest for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of South
East Asian Nations (ASEAN) have reaffirmed their support for
Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand to become the new
director-general of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
In a statement delivered at the Thursday meeting of WTO's
ruling General Council, the ASEAN countries said that they support
the formal proposal made by Kenya on Tuesday to form consensus
around Supachai because there is now no chance to build consensus
on the other contender, Michael Moore of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Still divided over which of the two candidates would be their
new leader, trade envoys of the 134-member WTO ended the
six-hour-long meeting, mainly on procedural matters, with no
result and no date for the next meeting set.
</P>
<P>
In a statement made public here Tuesday, former
Director-General Renato Ruggiero, whose four-year term of office
expired on April 30, expressed disappointment that his successor
has not yet been selected.
</P>
<P>
"This organization needs now a director-general who is fully
empowered to help the preparation for the ministerial conference
and the subsequent negotiations," said Ruggiero. "I emphasize that
the strength of this organization is largely based on our reaching
decisions by consensus and it appears to me that there is no
reason why a consensus could not be reached on this issue."
</P>
<P>
On April 30, Ruggiero selected WTO Services Director David
Hartridge to handle the day to day affairs of the secretariat
until the new director-general assumes office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
