<DOCNO> XIE19990507.0387 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economists See Easing of Global Economic Slides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Global economic slides are
easing; multilateral lending institutions are playing a favorable
role in Asia; and China is the most attractive Asian market in
1999 from the standpoint of U.S. exporting.
</P>
<P>
These are some of the results of two economic outlook surveys
released Thursday by the Business Council, a voluntary association
representing a broad range of large American corporations from all
major industries and regions. The 300-member council meets three
times a year for the free exchange of ideas among themselves and
representatives of the government.
</P>
<P>
One of the released surveys was among the council membership,
and the other was a consensus forecast of business economists who
serve as technical consultants to the Business Council.
</P>
<P>
"A large majority of active Business Council members believe
the worst of the global economic downturn is now over, a sentiment
shared nearly unanimously by the panel of economists," said the
council.
</P>
<P>
About half of the council members and economists believe the
prospects for business activity in the United States are
"stronger" in 1999, relative to 1998. And about half feel the
prospects are "little changed." They also have a mixed view of the
prospects for business activity outside the United States in 1999,
compared to 1998, although a majority of the council members
expect "little change."
</P>
<P>
The probability of the U.S. economy entering a recession at
some point over the next two years is less than 50 percent,
according to a large majority of the economists. Over the next 10
years, a large majority of economists and a majority of council
members expect the average inflation rate to be between 2 percent
and 2.9 percent in the United States -- only modestly higher than
the current rate.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Asia, half of the economists have a favorable
overall assessment of the role that multilateral lending
institutions are playing in the region, although a large minority
believes it is too soon to judge.
</P>
<P>
Reducing direct investment in the region and capital spending
in general were among the cost-cutting initiatives cited by a
majority of council members as a response to the economic crisis
in Asia. But a large majority of economists and nearly half of the
council members characterized the level of business activity for
their firms in the Asian region as "slightly higher" than six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
China received the greatest number of votes from the economists
as the most attractive Asian market in 1999 from the standpoint of
U.S. export. The region of Taiwan was close second. Among the
council members, China received the most votes, followed by South
Korea. A large majority of the economists cited Indonesia as the
least attractive export market in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
