<HEADLINE> Microsoft Reaches Agreement With AT&AMP;T </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp. agreed Thursday to
invest 5 billion U.S. dollars in AT&AMP;T in exchange for a bigger
role in AT&AMP;T's digital future.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement announced here, AT&AMP;T will double its
purchases of Microsoft software to 10 million copies, giving the
software giant up to 40 percent of AT&AMP;T's cable business.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after AT&AMP;T made a deal with its bidding
rival Comcast Tuesday to pave the way for the MediaOne merger.
Comcast dropped its bid for MediaOne after AT&AMP;T allowed the cable
company to buy two million of AT&AMP;T's cable subscribers.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, MediaOne accepted an offer for 54 billion dollars to
be acquire by AT&AMP;T, abandoning a previous deal to merge with
Comcast for 48 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agreement with Microsoft secured AT&AMP;T's acquisition of
MediaOne since the deal indicated that Microsoft dropped its
consideration to team up with Comcast to counter AT&AMP;T in the
bidding war for MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also gave Microsoft more role in AT&AMP;T digital
future and the company would burst its business in cable industry.
Since 1993, Microsoft has been seeking a role in consumers' living
rooms as well as their offices and is now counting heavily on
software for non-PC devices to fuel its future growth.
</P>
<P>
The two companies will deploy Microsoft's TV software, based on
the Windows CE operating system that will deliver television,
telephone service and high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
</TEXT>
