<HEADLINE> Belgrade Okays U.N. Humanitarian Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Government
approved on Thursday a humanitarian mission that U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan plans to send to Kosovo and other
parts of the Balkan country, a senior United Nations official
announced.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira De Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, said in a statement that he has received the
news from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav
Mission to the United Nations, "confirming that his government
would facilitate the conduct of the mission."
</P>
<P>
U.N. relief workers have not been in Yugoslavia since the March
24 beginning of the NATO air strikes for the sake of safety and
security.
</P>
<P>
An advance team of about five people would leave for Belgrade
at once to make arrangements and another team of about 15 would
follow in one or two weeks, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
Annan on Thursday said he planned to send a U.N. mission to
"assess the situation on the ground, determine the magnitude of
the refugees to go back to Kosovo," a Serbian province where
conflicts broke out in February last year after local ethnic
Albanians started fighting with Serbs for independence.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief also said that he had not asked for a pause or
lull in the NATO bombing while the team was in the Balkan country
but indicated some arrangements might be made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
