<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks ended lower
Thursday in fears of higher interest rates after Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan expressed worries about "imbalances" in
U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 8.59 at 10,946.82.
The index changed direction several times and fell as much as 103
points during the trading session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 15.26 at 1,332.05 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq index was dow 62.16 at 2,472.28.
</P>
<P>
Federal Chairman Greenspan said at an international conference
on Banking in Chicago that he was concerned with "imbalances in
our expansion" and worried about tight labor markets. the remarks
were interpreted as a caution that the Federal will raise interest
rates to cool the economy later this year.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was down 4.32 at 636.22 but the
American Stock Exchange index was up 2.32 at 787.81. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies was down 0.89 at 433.38.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange. NYSE volume declined to 873.05 shares
from 889.79 million in the previous session. 
</P>
