<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Eases with Falling Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- International benchmark Brent crude
oil futures lost nearly 50 cents to dip to as low as 16.55 U.S.
dollars a barrel, shedding the gains that took the June contract
to a 16-month high of 17.09 dollars on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil's recent price rally has increased costs for
refiners, who have started cutting back their consumption and
depressing demand for crude.
</P>
<P>
Traders said crude oil hoarded in storage tanks around the
world during last year's price crash was beginning to be sold off,
piling further downward pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, oil's rapid rally has brought crude flooding
out of the giant tanks at the Saldhana Bay storage facility, used
last year to offload excess supply, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
But some brokers dismissed the slide, suggesting an upward
march would continue on signs that the OPEC cartel has stuck to an
agreement reached in March to cut oil production by 2.1 million
barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have risen steadily since mid-February, when they
dropped below 10 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
A Reuters survey of OPEC and industry officials, analysts and
consultants published on Thursday found the cartel had completed
the majority of the cutback package.
</P>
<P>
OPEC had cut April output by 1.34 million bpd to 26.38 million
bpd from a revised 27.72 million bpd in March, according to the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
